<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Aug. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Reynolds' Shareholders Get Alcoa Bid  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Alcoa Inc. is taking a hostile $4.2 billion  
takeover bid directly to the shareholders of Reynolds Metals Co. 
Alcoa, the world's largest aluminum maker, is offering $65 a share 
in cash for No. 3 Reynolds, an offer deemed inadequate by Reynolds' 
board yesterday. Alcoa said today that while it would prefer to 
negotiate a takeover with Reynolds' management, it will begin an 
all-cash offer to Reynolds' shareholders this week. Alcoa stock 
closed down 5/16 at 66 3/16. Reynolds' shares closed down 7/16 at 
68 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	VNU Buys Nielsen for $2.7 Billion  
</P>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Nielsen Media Research Inc., the  
company synonymous with TV ratings in the United States, is being 
acquired by Dutch publisher VNU for $2.7 billion. The planned 
purchase will enable VNU to shift the focus of its operations away 
from traditional print media into electronic media and market 
information. Most significantly, New York-based Nielsen will give 
VNU entry into its fast-growing Internet ratings business, Net 
Ratings, which provides information about Internet advertising and 
customer behavior. Nielsen stock gained 4 1/2 to 37 5/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Venator To Exit Noncore Businesses  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Venator Group Inc. moved closer to becoming  
primarily a sporting goods retailer with its announcement today to 
sell or close eight of its noncore businesses, totaling more than 
500 stores. It's been a tough few years for Venator, which has 
attempted to boost profits by reducing costs and closing more than 
4,000 stores -- including the entire chain of Woolworth 
five-and-dime stores and all of its Kinney Shoe stores. It is now 
mostly a sporting goods chain, with 6,000 stores including Foot 
Locker and Champs Sports. Venator shares closed up 1 1/8 at 10. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Closes Up 73.14 at 11,046.79  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While shares of the nation's major computer  
makers rose sharply, the broader stock market held to slim gains 
today, with investors making few bets while they awaited the 
government's consumer price report. At the close of trading on Wall 
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 73.14 at 11,046.79. 
It was the Dow's first close above 11,000 since July 21. Broader 
stock indicators ended slightly higher. Much of the Dow's strength 
came from Hewlett Packard, which rose 3 3/4 to 109 3/4 in advance of its 
fiscal third-quarter earnings report. IBM also rose, gaining 4 to 
127 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
