<P>
	Another Shakeup at Waste Management  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Waste Management Inc. has ousted its No. 2  
executive as part of a companywide overhaul designed to get the big 
trash hauler's ailing business back on track. The company also 
acknowledged in a filing today with the Securities and Exchange 
Commission that the SEC and the New York Stock Exchange are 
conducting inquiries into insider sales of the company's stock 
prior to an earnings warning it issued on July 6. As part of the 
filing, Waste Management said that $30.2 million was incorrectly 
reported as operating income for the quarter ending March 31. Waste 
Management stock ended down 1/2 at 23 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Time Warner Names Ames Music Head  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner Inc. named Roger Ames as head of the  
media giant's Warner Music Group, filling the second half of a hole 
left when the two leaders of its movie, television and music 
division announced their resignations last month. Ames joined 
Warner Music International in April, after leaving The PolyGram 
Music Group, where he had served as president since 1996. On Aug. 
2, Time Warner announced that Barry Meyer had been selected to run 
the company's studio operations. Time Warner stock fell 9/16 to 
67 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom Offering Free Service  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom, its data network back online after  
10 days of intermittent outages, is offering 20 days of free 
service to compensate about 3,000 businesses affected by the costly 
disruptions. MCI WorldCom, besieged by complaints that it reacted 
slowly to the problem and failed to keep customers updated, took 
the entire network down for repairs over the weekend and said 
service was more than 99 percent back to normal today. The network 
began breaking down Aug. 5 after a software upgrade from Lucent 
Technologies. MCI WorldCom stock closed down 1/4 at 78 7/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Throws Out AOL Case vs. AT&AMP;T  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal judge tossed out America Online Inc.'s  
case against AT&AMP;T Corp. over the ``You have mail'' slogan, ruling 
that AOL doesn't have exclusive rights to the popular expression. 
The judge also refused to block AT&AMP;T from using ``buddy list'' and 
the abbreviation ``IM'' with its free instant messaging service. 
The dismissal of the lawsuit was the latest setback to AOL's 
attempt to control the spread of phrases it coins for its own 
Internet service. AOL shares lost 2 1/16 to 94 13/16. AT&AMP;T stock 
shed 3/16 to 49 1/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Union Bank of Calif. To Cut Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Union Bank of California disclosed plans  
today to shed 1,400 workers, or 15 percent of its work force, in an 
effort to boost profits and expand other parts of its business. 
Employees will get four weeks to a year of severance pay, depending 
on seniority. UnionBanCal Corp., the bank's San Francisco-based 
parent, said the layoffs will boost pre-tax profits by $135 
million. Net earnings will rise another $90 million through 
increased fees. 

</P>
<P>
	Toys R Us Earnings Fall  
</P>
<P>
	PARAMUS, N.J. (AP) -- Toys R Us Inc.'s second-quarter earnings  
fell 14 percent compared with the same period a year ago, due to 
costs associated with the development of its Internet subsidiary, 
toysrus.com. The company reported today that it earned $12 million, 
or 5 cents a share, compared with $14 million, or 5 cents a share, 
a year ago. The 1999 results include a $4 million charge to cover 
costs from toysrus.com. Last year's second-quarter results also 
included a $4 million charge related to debt extinguishment. Toys R 
Us stock gained 5/8 to 15 13/16. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL Teams With EMusic.com  
</P>
<P>
	DULLES, Va. (AP) -- America Online Inc. has reached a three-year  
deal with Internet music service EMusic.com that will allow online 
visitors to buy and download music from three Web sites owned by 
AOL. Under the agreement, EMusic's 20,000-song collection will be 
available on AOL's Spinner.com and Winamp.com, as well as ICQ.com, 
a chat service. EMusic will develop co-branded sites for the three 
services, selling music in the MP3 format. 

</P>
<P>
	PlayStation, Nintendo 64 Cut Prices  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Prices on both the Sony PlayStation and  
the competing Nintendo 64 will be cut to $99 as the gaming console 
companies prepared for the upcoming release of Sega's new Dreamcast 
system. An analyst said that the new low prices -- both dropping 
from $129 -- will allow consumers without a lot of extra 
entertainment money to go ahead and buy a console. Reviewers say 
Dreamcast's new system, priced at $199, push the entertainment into 
new, exciting realms with enhanced graphics and sound. 

</P>
