<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani Prefers Entering Race Late </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- New York City Mayor Rudolph  
Giuliani said Monday that Republicans will benefit if he delays 
entering the New York Senate race. 
</P>
<P>
	The longer Hillary Rodham Clinton ``runs against herself, the  
better we do,'' he said. ``The longer the concentration is on her 
and what views she has and doesn't, questions about her connections 
to the state ... that may account for the dramatic drop from being 
19 points ahead to in some polls being 9 or 10 points behind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is exploring a run for the Democratic Senate  
nomination. Early polls in New York had shown her with a wide lead 
over Giuliani but those same polls now show the race even or with 
her trailing the mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani made his comments after Republican Rep. Rick Lazio of  
Long Island asked the mayor to quickly announce his intentions. 
Lazio has put his own Senate hopes on hold at the request of Gov. 
George Pataki while Giuliani weighs the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every day that a Republican candidate is not in this race is a  
good day for Hillary Clinton and the Democrats,'' the congressman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor refused to say when he might announce his plans.  
</P>
<P>
	Both Giuliani and Lazio were meeting with top Republican  
officials at the Saratoga race track. 
</P>
<P>
	While Giuliani has the backing of top state GOP leaders,  
including a recent grudging endorsement from Pataki, one of his top 
boosters said Monday that the mayor's candidacy wasn't a sure 
thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say that they're probably 50-50,'' state Senate  
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said when asked about the odds on the 
mayor running. 
</P>
<P>
	But he later conceded during an interview with Albany's WROW-AM  
radio that ``if I were going to bet, I would put (money) on the 
nose that he's going to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If elected, Giuliani would have to leave City Hall a year early  
and ``that's weighing heavily on his mind,'' Bruno said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current city law of succession, liberal Democrat Mark  
Green, the city's elected public advocate, would fill out the 
mayor's term. Giuliani has appointed a charter revision commission 
to review the succession law. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing earlier Monday on the same radio show, the mayor said  
he was ``certainly getting closer'' to running. 
</P>
<P>
	``Campaigning, I love. It's just great fun,'' the mayor added.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
