<HEADLINE> Team To Oversee Texas Funeral Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- The state is dispatching a team to  
temporarily oversee the Texas Funeral Service Commission, an agency 
at the center of a whistleblower lawsuit in which Gov. George W. 
Bush has been subpoenaed. 
</P>
<P>
	The former funeral agency director claims she was fired after  
investigating a company that donated money to Bush, the front 
runner for the Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander told The Associated Press on  
Monday that she's assembling a team at the request of the funeral 
commission's governing board and Bush's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The comptroller employees will work at the funeral agency for 30  
to 90 days with ``complete authority to manage administrative 
affairs at the agency,'' Ms. Rylander said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the agency has a backlog of both consumer complaints  
and applications from funeral service providers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Rylander said her actions aren't related to the firing of  
the former funeral agency director, which resulted in the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush isn't a defendant in the lawsuit filed by former commission  
executive director Eliza May. His lawyers are scheduled to be in 
court Aug. 30 to argue that the subpoena should be dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has said he knows nothing about the firing of Ms. May, who  
lost her job in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May, once treasurer of the Texas Democratic Party, led an  
investigation into embalming practices of Service Corp. 
International, the owner of 3,700 funeral homes. SCI's political 
action committee gave Bush $35,000 in 1996 and 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	That inquiry resulted in a recommended fine of $445,000. SCI is  
fighting the fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May's lawsuit says she was dismissed nine months after being  
called into the office of Joe Allbaugh, Bush's executive assistant, 
and asked to explain inspections on April 10, 1998, at two SCI 
affiliates. Allbaugh now manages Bush's presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has denied any wrongdoing. Bush filed an affidavit  
swearing he had no conversations with SCI officials about the state 
probe. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
