<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 14:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gunman Says Sorry, He Had Wrong Guy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAGERSTOWN, Md. (AP) -- Volunteer firefighter Andrew Ebner was  
heading home from battling a late-night blaze when a shotgun blast 
hit the tailgate of his borrowed pickup truck. 
</P>
<P>
	Ebner sped up but so did the truck on his tail. Boom! Boom! Two  
more blasts. Glass showered the cab from the shattered rear window. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Ebner stopped the truck along the country road.  
</P>
<P>
	``I figured if I stayed in the truck, he was going to keep on  
shooting,'' Ebner said. ``I got out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's when the shooter realized he had the wrong guy. Kenneth  
Ramsburg apologized, offered to pay for the damage and gave Ebner 
his business card. Then, police say, he drove 10 miles to a liquor 
store parking lot, where he found his intended victim and shot him 
in the leg. 
</P>
<P>
	On his way back home, Ramsburg passed Ebner and two sheriff's  
deputies who were taking his statement. The deputies pursued and 
arrested Ramsburg, who was being held without bail Monday on 
charges including attempted murder and driving while intoxicated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I honestly believe that when the guy woke up this morning, he  
probably realized he did something he wished he never did,'' said 
Ebner, who wasn't hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramsburg, 38, a construction machine operator, told police he  
shot at Ebner's gray 1997 Ford pickup three times after mistaking 
it for a red 1986 Ford truck that had been on his property earlier 
Saturday night. He said someone in that pickup had shot at his 
house. 
</P>
<P>
	John C. Smith, the victim in the liquor store shooting, denied  
firing at Ramsburg's house. He said he and two friends had 
encountered a drunken and disagreeable Ramsburg earlier that night 
at a bar, then left in his red Ford pickup and drove to the liquor 
store, where they talked in the parking lot until Ramsburg showed 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to talk to him,'' Smith said. ``But you can't control  
someone when they're drinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said Ramsburg shot at his truck and then shot him in the  
right calf. He was in fair condition Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
