<DOCNO> APW19990816.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:29:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Parliament OKs Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's parliament approved Vladimir Putin as the  
country's new prime minister today, yielding to Boris Yeltsin 
rather than risk a showdown with the unpredictable president. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite its frustration with Yeltsin's revolving-door  
governments, parliament's lower house, the State Duma, voted 233-84 
to approve Putin, a former KGB agent who was the head of the 
country's main security agency. Putin needed a simple majority -- 
226 votes -- to be confirmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin said he would keep the Cabinet of ousted Prime Minister  
Sergei Stepashin largely unchanged and promised to strengthen 
social policies to help the poor. Previous premiers have pursued 
the same aims, with little success. 
</P>
<P>
	``To a large degree, the Cabinet's economic policy will be a  
continuation of the course of our predecessors,'' Putin said. ``We 
will continue reforms started by previous Cabinets, but the reforms 
aren't a goal by themselves, they must improve peoples' 
condition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Putin also tried to cater to Communists and other hard-liners by  
promising to help war veterans, write off huge debts run up by 
Russia's ailing defense plants and defend the interests of ethnic 
Russians living in other former Soviet republics. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that Russia must act to protect its global role:  
``Russia must not be shy of its interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin has fired the government four times in the past 17  
months, and while parliament has had bitter fights over his 
candidates for the prime minister's post, lawmakers have ultimately 
approved them all. 
</P>
<P>
	During the debate, most Duma leaders assailed Yeltsin for firing  
Stepashin but did not criticize Putin. 
</P>
<P>
	``Putin's appointment isn't his fault, the real problem is the  
country's Constitution,'' which allows the president to shuffle the 
government so easily, said Nikolai Kharitonov, the leader of the 
hard-line Agrarian faction. 
</P>
<P>
	If legislators had rejected Putin, it could have triggered a  
full-scale confrontation with Yeltsin. The Russian Constitution 
says Yeltsin must dissolve parliament if it rejects his candidate 
three times. But with parliamentary elections set for December, 
lawmakers were in no mood for a showdown that could cost them their 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Communists, who make up the largest faction in the Duma, met  
with Putin before the ballot today and said each party member would 
make his or her own decision on his candidacy, clearing the way for 
a quick approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Many politicians and the media have speculated that the Kremlin  
was considering introducing a state of emergency to put off 
parliamentary elections in December and the presidential vote set 
for next summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin denied that today.  
</P>
<P>
	``Once again I firmly and resolutely state as the president of  
the country: There will be no state of emergency,'' he told 
reporters in the Kremlin. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin, 42, promised that the elections would be held as  
scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	``The essential goal is to ensure law and order and hold honest  
and fair parliamentary and presidential elections,'' he told 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin will face a host of challenges as premier. The country's  
economy continues to struggle, Yeltsin's erratic behavior has left 
the government unstable, and Russian forces are battling Islamic 
rebels in the southern republic of Dagestan. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin gave no reason for firing Stepashin, but the president  
apparently wanted a tougher prime minister to keep his political 
foes at bay as he struggles through his final year in office. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
