<DOCNO> APW19990816.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 03:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Graham Makes Sure of No QB Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Even before Kerry Collins took his first  
snap with the New York Giants, Kent Graham ended any possibility of 
a quarterback controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham solidified his job as the No. 1 quarterback on Friday  
night by going 5-of-6 for 145 yards and two touchdowns in New 
York's 36-21 win over the Minnesota Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kent is not going to give it up easily. He is a competitor, so  
everybody better get used to seeing him play well,'' Giants 
defensive end Michael Strahan said Sunday. ``He is just not going 
to go out there and lay over like everyone expects him to do. I 
feel he is so underrated. At this point, he is playing for a 
measure of respect and he is doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Giants coach Jim Fassel never wavered in his commitment to  
Graham as his starter, much was made of the Giants' decision to 
sign Collins in the offseason to an almost $17 million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line was a team doesn't pay someone about $5 million  
in his first season to sit on the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't seem to make any difference that the troubled Collins  
was coming into this year after a couple of bad seasons and that 
Graham led the Giants to five wins in their last six games last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	At some point, many expected the strong-armed Collins to make a  
run at the starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins looked OK going 8-of-17 for 127 yards and a TD against  
the Vikings. But that paled in comparison to Graham's 15 plays and 
three series to open the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins had to sit out Sunday's practice because of a bruised  
right thigh suffered against the Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will probably take a couple of days,'' Collins said.  
``Luckily, it wasn't serious. But it's always tough to watch 
practice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham connected with rookie Sean Bennett on a 53-yard screen  
pass for a touchdown on a three-play, 77-yard drive on New York's 
first possession Friday. He found Joe Jurevicius on a 37-yard 
scoring pass to cap a five-play, 67-yard second drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Brad Daluiso kicked a 48-yard field goal on Graham's last drive.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I played well and did what I had to do out there,''  
Graham said. ``When I looked at the film, it was pretty much what I 
saw out there on the field. We made big plays and that was really 
good to see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham tried to downplay the quarterback situation, even though  
he gets asked about it often. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people are saying there is a controversy, and I don't  
think there is, to be honest,'' Graham said. ``I haven't felt that 
pressure. I know I have to go out and play well, but I haven't felt 
it from the coaching staff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham said the reason people think there is going to be a  
quarterback controversy is the money. He makes about $1.1 million, 
a lot less than what Collins is getting this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Money is in the back of everyone's mind and it's in the back  
of mine, too,'' Graham said. ``I understand that. But I haven't 
gotten that feeling around here from the coaches or organization as 
a whole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the rest of the preseason, Graham hopes to see the Giants'  
offense continue to get yards in big chunks, something it hasn't 
done in years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have that potential in this offense,'' said Graham,  
a journeyman drafted in the eighth round by the New York in 1992 
and eventually played in Detroit and Arizona before coming back 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been in this offense long enough to know we have that  
potential especially with our receivers now being so big and strong 
and fast.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
