<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 22:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Filmmaker Ready for New Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The huge success of ``The Blair Witch  
Project'' has opened doors for the film's young creators. Now 
they're waiting for the attention to die down so they can 
concentrate on new projects. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fame part kind of gets in the way of the filmmaking part,  
so hopefully the fame will fade and we can get back to 
filmmaking,'' producer Michael Menello said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The film, which was made for about $35,000, has become one of  
the largest grossing independent films in history, bringing in 
around $108 million since it went into wide release three weeks 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The success has elevated the five former University of Central  
Florida film students from starving artists to press-hounded 
celebrities. 
</P>
<P>
	The mock documentary has given directors Daniel Myrick and  
Eduardo Sanchez and producers Gregg Hale, Robin Cowie and Monello 
the financial freedom to focus on the creative side of filmmaking 
instead of spending nearly half their time fundraising. 
</P>
<P>
	But fame has also created new demands on their time, including  
juggling interviews and phone calls from agents, fans and 
``long-lost friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``All we've been doing is struggling to keep up with things,''  
said Sanchez. ``It's amazing how much non-filmmaking there is.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 09:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alcoa Goes to Reynolds Shareholders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Alcoa Inc., the world's largest aluminum  
maker, said today it is taking its offer to buy Reynolds Metals Co. 
directly to Reynolds shareholders after the No. 3 aluminum 
company's board rejected the multibillion-dollar bid as inadequate. 
</P>
<P>
	In turning down Alcoa's offer at a Sunday meeting, the Reynolds  
board opened the door to other offers in what an aluminum industry 
expert says marks the final days of Richmond-based Reynolds as a 
solo company. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm confident that at least one or two other players will come  
into the game at this stage,'' said Ilker Baybars, senior deputy 
dean of the Carnegie Mellon Graduate Business School. ``Reynolds is 
going to be with somebody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Traders already have bid the price of Reynolds above Alcoa's  
hostile offer in expectation of a bigger bid. In afternoon trading, 
Reynolds was down 43 3/4 cents at $68.93 3/4 a share on the New York 
Stock Exchange, where Alcoa was down 12 1/2 cents at $66.37 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to saying it would pursue a cash offer for all of  
Reynolds' shares this week, Alcoa said it would ask Reynolds' 
shareholders to replace the Reynolds board with one that would 
support the Alcoa bid. A spokeswoman for Reynolds did not 
immediately return a telephone call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Pittsburgh-based Alcoa disclosed its unsolicited  
$65 a share cash-and-stock offer. Alcoa valued its deal at $5.6 
billion, though it did not provide additional details. At $65 a 
share, the deal would be worth only $4.2 billion based on the 
number of Reynolds shares outstanding. 
</P>
<P>
	By week's end, a Chicago-based investment firm, Michigan Avenue  
Partners, said it made a superior all-cash offer for Reynolds but 
declined to disclose details of its bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds' board held a special weekend meeting to discuss the  
Alcoa offer. Afterward, the company issued a statement calling the 
Alcoa bid ``inadequate'' and saying the board decided unanimously 
that Reynolds ``should explore all alternatives to maximize 
shareholder value, including the sale of the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the alternatives would include soliciting rival bids to  
Alcoa's offer was unclear. Lou Anne Nabham, a spokeswoman for 
Reynolds, declined to elaborate on the company's statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcoa President Alain J.P. Belda was not available Sunday. A  
call to his home was not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Several analysts have said Alcoa's offer was too low and  
predicted a bidding war. 
</P>
<P>
	``Numerous people who follow the industry made remarks last week  
that the Alcoa bid was too low,'' Baybars said. ``There's a little 
gaming going on here. I think Alcoa is prepared to offer a little 
more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds could get anywhere from $4 to $18 a share more than the  
$65-a-share Alcoa offered, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other possible contenders: Alcan Aluminium Ltd. of  
Canada. Last week, after Alcoa's offer was made public, Alcan 
president and chief executive officer Jacques Bougie said his 
company wouldn't rule out making a bid for Reynolds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We exclude no options,'' Bougie said, despite the announcement  
of Alcan's plans for a three-way merger with Alusuisse-Lonza 
Holding (Algroup) of Switzerland and Pechiney S.A. of France. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian and European companies have combined revenues of  
$21.6 billion, which would just eclipse the $21 billion in combined 
revenues of an Alcoa and Reynolds merger. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 05:40:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Electrocuted Saving Girl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SENECA, S.C. (AP) -- Electrical current running through a boat  
dock injured a young swimmer and then killed the retired professor 
who came to the girl's rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	Haley Hendrix, 9, was swimming in Keowee Lake about 35 miles  
southeast of Greenville on Saturday when she grabbed hold of a boat 
dock. She became unconscious and went into cardiac arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	After calls for help, Alan Dexter Wheeler swam toward the dock  
and knocked Haley free. The girl was resuscitated by Wheeler's 
nephew and treated and released from a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wheeler, 73, died of a heart attack caused by the same  
current running through the dock, Deputy Coroner Mike Crowe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators were unsure what caused the electrical charge,  
Crowe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler was a 30-year veteran of the U.S. Air Force and a  
professor emeritus at Clemson University, where he taught logistics 
and transportation. A professor emeritus is a professor who is 
retired from active service but retains his title. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Daewoo To Sell More Subsidiaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's ailing Daewoo group  
bowed to pressure from creditor banks on Monday and agreed to sell 
or spin off all but six of its 25 subsidiaries under a tightened 
restructuring program. 
</P>
<P>
	The new program, approved by Daewoo's six domestic creditor  
banks, will allow the troubled conglomerate to retain its 
automobile unit and five other affiliates -- three fewer than 
previously proposed -- after the restructuring is finished by the 
end of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo officials said the restructuring does not affect their  
overseas plants in France, Poland and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The move came a day after President Kim Dae-jung called for  
stronger reforms at Daewoo and four other top chaebol, or 
conglomerates -- Hyundai, Samsung, LG and SK -- which he said have 
been slow in restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim said a full recovery of South Korea's economy will be  
impossible without reforming or restructuring the debt-ridden 
conglomerates. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he ``will become the first president in South Korean  
history to reform chaebol and straighten the economy so that it 
will grow on the basis of the middle class.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its initial proposal on July 30, Daewoo had offered to sell  
or spin off all but nine subsidiaries. Domestic creditors had 
rejected the plan as insufficient and asked Daewoo to pare down 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	In its latest plan, Daewoo agreed to sell three more profitable  
affiliates engaged in brokerage, shipbuilding and construction. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision will leave Daewoo with six units: automobile, car  
sales, machinery, telecommunications, trade and finance. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Daewoo's main creditor banks, Korea First Bank, said the  
new restructuring plan should bring Daewoo's debt-to-equity ratio 
to below 200 by the end of the year, as ordered by the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo, South Korea's second largest conglomerate, narrowly  
escaped becoming the nation's largest bankruptcy in July when 
domestic creditors agreed to delay repayment of $5.8 billion in 
short-term debt for six months and extend $3.3 billion in new 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Daewoo promised to cut its debt drastically by  
selling or spinning off most of its 40 subsidiaries and attracting 
foreign investment. But doubt persists that Daewoo can or is 
willing to fulfill its promise. 
</P>
<P>
	About half a dozen South Korean conglomerates collapsed under  
huge bank debts in 1996-97, forcing the country to call in the 
International Monetary Fund to bail out its sinking economy. A 
restructuring of chaebol was a key condition of the $58 billion IMF 
bailout, the world's largest. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
