or spin off all but nine subsidiaries. Domestic creditors had 
rejected the plan as insufficient and asked Daewoo to pare down 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	In its latest plan, Daewoo agreed to sell three more profitable  
affiliates engaged in brokerage, shipbuilding and construction. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision will leave Daewoo with six units: automobile, car  
sales, machinery, telecommunications, trade and finance. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Daewoo's main creditor banks, Korea First Bank, said the  
new restructuring plan should bring Daewoo's debt-to-equity ratio 
to below 200 by the end of the year, as ordered by the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo, South Korea's second largest conglomerate, narrowly  
escaped becoming the nation's largest bankruptcy in July when 
domestic creditors agreed to delay repayment of $5.8 billion in 
short-term debt for six months and extend $3.3 billion in new 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Daewoo promised to cut its debt drastically by  
selling or spinning off most of its 40 subsidiaries and attracting 
foreign investment. But doubt persists that Daewoo can or is 
willing to fulfill its promise. 
</P>
<P>
	About half a dozen South Korean conglomerates collapsed under  
huge bank debts in 1996-97, forcing the country to call in the 
International Monetary Fund to bail out its sinking economy. A 
restructuring of chaebol was a key condition of the $58 billion IMF 
bailout, the world's largest. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 14:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Armstrong Competes on Mountain Bike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- For his first bicycle race in the United  
States since winning the Tour de France, Lance Armstrong is giving 
up his skinny road racing tires for the fat nobbies of a mountain 
bike. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, who overcame cancer to win the world's most famous  
cycling race, plans to compete this weekend in the national 
championships of mountain bicycling at the Mount Snow resort in 
West Dover. 
</P>
<P>
	He's entered in the cross-country race, an event that covers  
close to 30 miles in the woods surrounding the resort's ski slopes. 
Armstrong is not expected to dominate the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to face some pretty serious competition here,''  
said Rich Wanninger, chief spokesman for USA Cycling, which 
sanctions the competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The weekend races are the finals of the Chevy Trucks National  
Championship series, a six-event competition in which riders 
accumulate points toward the national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're a pro rider, that's the way you become a national  
champion,'' said Patrice Quintero, communications coordinator at 
USA Cycling. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong will not be in line for the national championship on  
Friday because he has not been accumulating points throughout the 
series. Instead, he's riding because he enjoys occasional off-road 
racing, Wanninger said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He looked at his schedule earlier in the year and he had  
wanted to fit the World Cup (of mountain biking) in Europe, but 
training for the Tour was going so well and he didn't want to 
interrupt it,'' Wanninger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong has ridden in a few single-day events in Europe since  
his victory in Paris in July, but has spent much of his time in the 
United States being welcomed as a returning hero at the White House 
and in his hometown of Austin, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong's strong Tour de France win has been an inspiration to  
millions. 
</P>
<P>
	The 27-year-old rider learned in 1996 that he had testicular  
cancer, which spread to his bones and brain. He underwent 
aggressive chemotherapy and three operations. With his cancer in 
remission, Armstrong returned to competitive bicycling. 
</P>
<P>
	Mountain biking, however, is not his forte. He entered a similar  
event in Park City, Utah, last year and dropped out before he could 
finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think his motivation this time is to finish,'' Quintero  
said. ``In Utah last year, he said it was the hardest race he ever 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mount Snow, a resort in the southern Green Mountains, has become  
a mecca for mountain bicycling enthusiasts and has staged an event 
in the national championship series for the past eight years. This 
year it is drawing the top competitors in the country for the 
finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The tightest race for a national title will be among the women  
in the cross-country event. Alison Dunlap of Colorado Springs, 
Colo., has a 14-point lead over Ruthie Matthes of Durango, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Since there's a difference of 14 points between the winner and  
second-place finisher at Mount Snow, Friday's race will determine 
which woman becomes national champ. 
</P>
<P>
	The other events over the weekend are downhill, dual slalom,  
observed trials and short-track cross country. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 14:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
