<DOCNO> APW19990816.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 20:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> VNU Buys Nielsen for $2.7 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Nielsen Media Research Inc., the  
company synonymous with TV ratings in the United States, is being 
acquired by Dutch publisher VNU for $2.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The planned purchase announced Monday will enable VNU to shift  
the focus of its operations away from traditional print media into 
electronic media and market information. 
</P>
<P>
	Most significantly, New York-based Nielsen will give VNU entry  
into its fast-growing Internet ratings business, Net Ratings, which 
provides information about Internet advertising and customer 
behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dutch company will offer shareholders $35.60 per share, or a  
total of $2.5 billion, for all of Nielsen's outstanding stock. The 
bid is a premium of 15 percent over its Friday closing share price. 
VNU will also assume $200 million of Nielsen's debt. 
</P>
<P>
	VNU said the addition of Nielsen will significantly increase its  
earnings over a period of five years. However, it said the deal 
would likely have a negative effect on earnings in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts were positive about the agreement, but said the bid was  
slightly on the high side. 
</P>
<P>
	Ab Barneveld, an analyst at MeesPierson in Amsterdam, called the  
buy a ``strategically brilliant step,'' and said it will help VNU 
become less cyclical, as businesses need marketing information 
regardless of the broader economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Nielsen's Net Ratings, which executives say may go public next  
year, is believed to have a great deal of growth potential. 
</P>
<P>
	The TV ratings operation has made Nielsen a household name in  
the United States, but the major American networks have been 
dissatisfied for several years, complaining about alleged errors in 
Nielsen ratings. In 1998, the networks contributed $12 million to 
help fund a rival system created by Statistical Research Inc., but 
that system was shut down earlier this year, leaving Nielsen with 
its monopoly in the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Nielsen is developing new systems to measure audiences as TV  
technology evolves, including ways for assessing ratings when 
networks are able to send several signals on the same channel. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, VNU had a net profit of $520 million on sales of $2.6  
billion. Nielsen, which has 3,300 employees, had net income of $49 
million and sales of $402 million. 
</P>
<P>
	VNU, with 13,300 employees, provides consumer and professional  
information through publishing and printing operations in the 
Netherlands, Europe and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	VNU shares rose immediately after the opening of trade on the  
Amsterdam Stock Exchange, jumping over 4 percent, but closed 3.5 
percent higher at $38.90 a share. Nielsen rocketed over 13 percent 
shortly after the start of trade in New York, and traded at $37.19 
a share, up $4.38, or 13 percent, in afternoon trading on the New 
York Stock Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 03:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Picking Ryder Team No Easy Task  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- The players had their say, and more. Then  
it was Ben Crenshaw's turn. 
</P>
<P>
	After a PGA Championship that saw almost every player voice an  
opinion on Ryder Cup pay but none play their way onto the team, 
Crenshaw was to announce today his two captain's picks for next 
month's matches in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Lehman was one leading contender, and Fred Couples another.  
But even Crenshaw may have had to toss and turn thinking about this 
one. 
</P>
<P>
	``One choice may be fairly obvious to me and the other will keep  
me up at night,'' Crenshaw said last week. 
</P>
<P>
	If Crenshaw was paying attention in the locker room before  
missing the cut Friday at the PGA Championship, he may have noticed 
a simple plea. 
</P>
<P>
	It was written in black marker on Crenshaw's green locker: ``Ben  
-- Pick me,'' it read, with four dashes, a blank, and then seven 
more dashes beneath it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's funny. I didn't write it,'' Couples said. ``I would  
love to play on the team. I think anybody would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The top 10 places on the 12-member team didn't change in the PGA  
Championship, despite No. 10 Jeff Maggert giving Bob Estes and 
Lehman an opening by not making the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Estes, needing to finish in fifth place to make the team, came  
closest, getting as high as fourth Sunday before bogeying Nos. 16 
and 17 to drop into a tie for sixth. Lehman finished in a tie for 
34th. 
</P>
<P>
	While Lehman hoped for an invitation, the top 10 included PGA  
champion Tiger Woods, David Duval, Payne Stewart, Davis Love III, 
Mark O'Meara, Hal Sutton, Justin Leonard, Jim Furyk, Phil Mickelson 
and Maggert. 
</P>
<P>
	Which leaves Crenshaw with his two captain's picks -- and one big  
headache trying to figure out who should get them. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's just a lot going on,'' Crenshaw said, looking a little  
harried. ``It is tough. Whomever I pick knows they have to step up 
and try to do their very best job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Crenshaw could forget Stricker and Huston. Neither has played  
well this year, and they don't have any experience. He had already 
hinted he would use one pick on Lehman, a two-time Ryder Cup 
member, if Lehman didn't make it on points. 
</P>
<P>
	Lehman plays well at courses like The Country Club in Brookline,  
Mass., where the Ryder Cup matches will be played Sept. 24-26. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it's true,'' Lehman said of being a captain's pick. ``I  
definitely would be honored to be picked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couples was another matter. He's been on every U.S. team since  
1989, and his five Ryder Cup berths are the most among active 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike Lehman, who added tournaments to get more Ryder Cup  
points -- he played the Greater Milwaukee Open rather than heading 
to the British Open a week early -- the PGA was Couples' first 
tournament since the end of June. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I am chosen, I will play more,'' Couples said. ``I will  
practice. These are things that make you work harder. I have a 
funny feeling if I'm chosen, I won't have any problem playing in 
the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The European choices aren't nearly as messy, but captain Mark  
James also has another week and another tournament before he has to 
make his decisions. Sergio Garcia, who was in 12th place, helped 
him out by playing his way onto the team with the runner-up finish 
to Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesper Parnevik, Bernhard Langer and even the aging Nick Faldo  
are possibilities, but James isn't giving any clues as to what 
he'll do. He won't even say whether he'll play if he makes the team 
on points. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have, yes,'' he said when asked if he'd made a decision.  
``That's yet to be announced.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:30:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisco Systems Is Buying Calista </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Cisco Systems Inc., a leading maker of  
computer networking equipment, announced today it is acquiring 
privately held Calista Inc., a provider of Internet-based phone 
technology, for $55 million in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Calista, based in Bucks, England and San Jose, develops  
technology that allows phone systems from different vendors to work 
together over networks built on Internet standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition enables San Jose-based Cisco to offer its  
customers the ability to transmit data, voice and video services 
across the Internet rather than over traditional phone lines, the 
company said. 
</P>
<P>
	The transaction is expected to close by the end of October.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 23:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Sixth Sense' Tops Box Office Again / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Sixth Sense'' starring Bruce Willis  
continued to scare away the competition for the second straight 
weekend, taking in $25.8 million, as scary movies continued their 
summertime strength. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eddie Murphy-Steve Martin comedy ``Bowfinger'' debuted in  
second place with $18.1 million. ``The Blair Witch Project,'' the 
season's horror juggernaut, was third at $14.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 20 movies at North American theaters Friday through  
Sunday, followed by distributing studio, gross, number of theater 
locations, average receipts per location, total gross and number of 
weeks in release, as compiled Monday by Exhibitor Relations Co. 
Inc.: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``The Sixth Sense,'' Disney, $25.8 million, 2,395 locations,  
$10,758 average, $69.7 million, two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Bowfinger,'' Universal, $18.1 million, 2,706 locations,  
$6,675 average, $18.1 million, one week. 
</P>
<P>
	3. ``The Blair Witch Project,'' Artisan, $14.5 million, 2,412  
