<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 23:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf of Mexico Damage Repair Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers worry that a government study of the  
Gulf of Mexico's oxygen-deprived ``dead zone'' could lead to curbs 
on fertilizer and land use in the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Every year an area of the gulf as big as New Jersey becomes  
depleted of oxygen, or ``hypoxic,'' because of the heavy flow of 
nitrogen and other nutrients down the Mississippi River. 
Fertilizers used on Midwestern farms are blamed for much of the 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House's Office of Science and Technology Policy  
completed the study this spring. It is to propose recommendations 
this fall and issue a final report next spring for Congress and 
state governments to consider. 
</P>
<P>
	The study concluded that the most cost-effective way to protect  
the gulf would be to reduce fertilizer use by 20 percent and to 
restore 5 million acres of wetlands that could trap nutrients 
before they reach the Mississippi and its tributaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Farm Bureau Federation sees no justification for  
doing that. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists ``have not established an identifiable, variable link  
between nitrogen fertilizer and the hypoxic zone,'' the federation 
said in comments filed with the White House science office. ``No 
one has defined what the impact of a cutback in nitrogen fertilizer 
would be on the nitrate levels in the Mississippi River.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the study could not identify damage to gulf fisheries  
because of oxygen depletion, it warned that they will ``decline, 
perhaps precipitously,'' if the gulf suffers the same fate as the 
Black Sea and other hypoxic areas around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's very little question about whether or not the loads of  
nitrogen and other nutrients in the Mississippi River drive the 
dynamics of the hypoxic zone,'' said Don Scavia, overseeing the 
report as director of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric 
Administration's National Ocean Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists are trying to figure out which areas of the  
Mississippi basin to target for controlling the pollution and the 
best way to do that, he said Monday. ``To the extent this is going 
to affect agriculture, we want to make sure it's not disruptive,'' 
Scavia said. 
</P>
<P>
	The gulf's ``dead zone'' doubled in size to about 7,000 square  
miles after widespread Midwest flooding in 1993. This summer it 
expanded to 7,728 square miles, about 700 square miles larger than 
the previously recorded maximum of 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Algae thrives on the excess nutrients and hogs the oxygen in the  
water that is needed by fish, shrimp and other aquatic life. The 
Mississippi River drains water from about 40 percent of the United 
States and carries more than a million tons of nitrogen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 22:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Ill. Detective Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A former police detective has been convicted of  
conspiracy and extortion for taking part in more than a decade of 
shakedowns and payoffs in corruption-plagued Cicero in suburban 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Darlene Sobczak, 42, was found guilty Monday following four days  
of testimony last week before U.S. District Judge Suzanne Conlon. 
</P>
<P>
	The former police officer, who joined the police force in 1984  
and left last year, is scheduled to be sentenced Oct. 27. 
Prosecutors estimate she'll receive a three- to five-year prison 
term. 
</P>
<P>
	Sobczak was convicted of plotting with another former Cicero  
detective, Robert Biziarek, to get payoffs, starting as far back as 
the mid-1980s and continuing until August 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Biziarek has pleaded guilty. He is to be sentenced Oct. 7.  
</P>
<P>
	Many of those who paid police to stay out of jail were Gypsies  
who were picked up in Cicero on a variety of real and trumped up 
charges, prosecutors said. Four Gypsies took the stand as 
prosecution witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Sobczak attorneys argued that the government's witnesses were  
not truthful and that the former police officer had been unfairly 
roped into matters that she had nothing to do with. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
