<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Corning President Is Named CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) -- Dow Corning Corp. announced Monday that  
president Gary Anderson, who guided the company through bankruptcy 
due to claims over silicone breast implants, has been named chief 
executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson replaces Richard Hazleton, who will remain chairman of  
the company's board of directors. In a statement, Hazleton said the 
move was part of a succession plan for Dow Corning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gary has done an exemplary job of leading this company through  
the Chapter 11 process, and now, with that hopefully approaching 
closure, it is appropriate that he assume the role of CEO to lead 
Dow Corning into the next century,'' Hazleton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Corning, which was once the largest supplier of silicone  
used in breast implants, filed for bankruptcy in 1995 after 19,000 
women sued the company, blaming implants for a variety of health 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Hearings on Dow Corning's $4.5 billion bankruptcy plan ended  
last month. The plan includes a $3.2 billion settlement for 
hundreds of thousands of women with implants. A judge must approve 
the plan, though it's unclear when his ruling might be made. 
</P>
<P>
	Dow Corning no longer makes silicone breast implants, but still  
produces thousands of silicone-based products. Last year, it earned 
$207 million on revenue of $2.6 billion, with more than half its 
sales coming from foreign markets. The company is co-owned by The 
Dow Chemical Co. and Corning Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson holds a bachelor's degree in chemical engineering from  
Michigan Technological University and an MBA from Central Michigan 
University. He joined the company in 1967, and has worked as 
president since September 1994. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 17:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Freeman Gets $42M Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Antonio Freeman became the NFL's  
highest-paid wide receiver Monday, agreeing to a seven-year, $42 
million contract with the Green Bay Packers. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman's agent, Joel Segal, told The Associated Press the deal  
also includes a $10 million signing bonus, the largest ever paid to 
a wide receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a landmark contract,'' Segal said. ``This is something  
that's never been done before. It breaks the ice for all the other 
receivers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The contract includes two voidable years, meaning the All-Pro  
wideout can opt out of the deal after five seasons. The contract is 
contingent on Freeman playing in 25 percent of the Packers' 
offensive plays in any season. 
</P>
<P>
	Contracts for wide receivers historically have lagged behind  
those for other skill position players, in part because of the 
higher likelihood of injury at the position. But the Packers felt 
Freeman was an impact player who deserved top dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was everything I hoped and dreamed,'' Freeman said of the  
contract. ``I'm just happy to be a Green Bay Packer for a long, 
long time to come. I love it here, and I always wanted to be 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit receiver Herman Moore signed a five-year, $28 million  
contract extension in July that included a signing bonus between $8 
million and $9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman's signing bonus is the second largest ever paid by the  
Packers, who gave quarterback Brett Favre a $12 million bonus in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the 1998 season, the Packers offered Freeman a five-year,  
$17 million contract with a signing bonus of just over $3 million. 
Freeman rejected the deal, choosing instead to play for the team's 
tender offer of $1.153 million and become a free agent at season's 
end. 
</P>
<P>
	The gamble paid off spectacularly. Freeman set career-highs with  
84 catches for 14 touchdowns and a league-best 1,424 yards, despite 
breaking his jaw late in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The variables we took into consideration paid off,'' Segal  
said. ``This deal brings receivers into the big-money contracts 
going into the new millennium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers designated Freeman as their franchise player, and  
the team worked with Segal to reach agreement on a long-term deal. 
Freeman held out through the first two weeks on training camp, but 
on Friday, with his contract all but completed, he signed a 
tender-offer deal allowing him to join camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Segal came to Green Bay on Sunday and hammered out the final  
details of the contract on Monday morning. The voidable years on 
the deal were the final hurdle, and the agreement was finalized 
shortly before the Packers' afternoon workout. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was really no need for animosity,'' Freeman said of the  
negotiations. ``I took into consideration a lot of past deals I've 
seen ... where negotiations really get nasty and the fans and the 
media take a different view of that player. That's something I 
wanted to avoid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want the fans thinking I was a greedy guy. I just  
tried to remain respectful through the negotiation period, and the 
Green Bay Packers did as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman briefly participated in drills on Monday morning, but  
will spend most of the week working with strength and conditioning 
coach Barry Rubin. Freeman won't play in Green Bay's exhibition 
game against the Denver Broncos next Monday, coach Ray Rhodes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really is the leader of the receiver group,'' Rhodes said.  
``Our players love him because of his work ethic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Segal's Worldwide Entertainment and Sports also closed lucrative  
deals for receivers Charles Johnson in Philadelphia and O.J. 
McDuffie in Miami during the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman's signing allows the Packers to breathe a sigh of relief  
about their depth at wide receiver. With Robert Brooks' retirement 
last month, Green Bay entered training camp with Bill Schroeder, 
Derrick Mayes and Corey Bradford as their top wideouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis said Freeman will be able to  
easily fit back into his old role with the team. Lewis also is 
considering using Freeman, normally a split end, at flanker this 
season, a position he has played sporadically in the last three 
years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
