<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Summer Break a Hollowed Tradition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Playing a fish rising in cool waters, whacking  
a small white ball down a green fairway, piloting a sailboat off a 
breezy coast, America's chief executives have been getting away 
from it all ever since the presidency began. 
</P>
<P>
	Theodore Roosevelt rode horses and hunted. John Kennedy sailed.  
William Howard Taft, Dwight Eisenhower, George Bush and Bill 
Clinton golfed. Ronald Reagan rode horses and cut brush on his 
California ranch, liking it so much he was there for 335 days of 
his eight-year presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry Truman played poker late into the night with cronies on  
the south porch of his quarters at Key West, Fla. The official 
White House log said he ``visited with members of his party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some presidents just returned to the comforts of home -- homes  
with names like Mount Vernon, Monticello, Montpelier, Sagamore 
Hill, Hyde Park and the LBJ Ranch. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, Bill and Hillary Clinton embark on their seventh  
presidential vacation, returning for the fifth time to the 
Massachusetts island of Martha's Vineyard. It's a split-decision 
vacation. They'll move on at month's end to New York's Finger Lakes 
in a state where the first lady will likely seek a Senate seat next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Vacations have generally been a good thing for presidents.  
</P>
<P>
	Truman liked the warm sun and blue waters of Key West so much  
that he said he wished he could move the government there ``and 
just stay.'' As it was, he spent 175 vacation days on the southern 
tip of Florida over seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisenhower was so pleased with golf in Augusta, Ga., that he  
visited 29 times for a total of 222 days during eight years as 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Calvin Coolidge learned to fish while vacationing on the lakes  
of northern Wisconsin. He spent the entire summer of 1927 in a 
rustic lodge in the Black Hills of South Dakota and drew headlines 
after a public spat with his wife when she returned hours late from 
a hike in the woods with a handsome Secret Service agent, blameless 
but flustered. 
</P>
<P>
	Coolidge jolted reporters later that summer by handing out typed  
notes reading, ``I do not choose to run for president in 1928.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abraham Lincoln found a stone cottage at the Soldiers' Home a  
short carriage ride from the White House a perfect escape. 
</P>
<P>
	Grover Cleveland used a vacation getaway in the summer of 1893  
to give reporters the slip and schedule secret surgery to remove a 
cancerous growth in his mouth. Fearing that news of his condition 
could be used to undermine his economic recovery program, Cleveland 
had the operation performed on board a yacht steaming to his summer 
home at Buzzards Bay, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	When Theodore Roosevelt visited Yellowstone National Park in the  
early 1900s, reporters were told to stay away. One persistent 
correspondent rode in, accompanied by a dog. 
</P>
<P>
	Retribution was not long in coming. The reporter was arrested,  
The New York Times reported on its front page. The horse was 
confiscated. The dog was shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite being swatted away at times, reporters have swarmed  
after vacationing presidents for most of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's vacations have generally followed the golf course,  
with an occasional celebrity sail followed by leisurely dinners out 
and perhaps a walk to an ice cream shop. 
</P>
<P>
	The president took the advice of consultant Dick Morris and  
spent his summer vacation time in 1995 and 1996 golfing and hiking 
against the backdrop of the Grand Teton Mountains at Jackson Hole, 
Wyo. Voters like outdoor, western family vacations. Morris had 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	On most Clinton vacations the buzz of the summer was how many  
mulligans -- repeat strokes -- the president took on the golf course, 
or what books he had read. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer the world came with him to peaceful Martha's  
Vineyard. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons arrived just hours after the president's nationally  
televised speech acknowledging he'd had a relationship with Monica 
Lewinsky that was ``not appropriate'' and had ``misled people, 
including even my wife.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an abrupt change of pace, Clinton switched from casual attire  
and appeared before reporters in a crisp white shirt, dark suit and 
grave voice to announce he had just ordered U.S. forces to strike 
terrorist facilities in Afghanistan and Sudan to retaliate for 
bombings of the American embassies in those countries. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, golf is expected to again dominate the president's  
vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	And mulligans are back in style.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. He has 
covered five of Bill Clinton's six presidential vacations and is 
set to cover the seventh. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
