<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Down, Tokyo Share prices Up / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	soar  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Selling by Japanese exporters drove the dollar  
slightly lower against the yen today while Tokyo stocks surged in 
line with big gains on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.84 yen in late-afternoon trading, down  
0.08 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and below its late New York 
level of 115.74 yen Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average jumped 390.86  
points, or 2.24 percent, to close at 17,826.03. On Friday, the 
average finished up 12.20 points, or 0.07 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese exporters, such as automakers, sold dollars for yen to  
lock in profits for the first half of the fiscal year ending 
September. 
</P>
<P>
	``Japanese exporters were aggressive in selling dollars,'' said  
Shigeru Hashimoto, vice president of foreign exchange at Sanwa 
Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Surging stocks also pushed the yen higher as Japanese investors  
dumped foreign assets and rushed back into yen to get in on the 
rally, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar traded as high as 115.90 yen and as low as 114.62 in  
Asian trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 121.58 yen, down  
from 122.76 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, international blue-chip issues marked  
strong gains in line with a surge in share prices in the United 
States last week. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average picked up  
184.26 points Friday to close at 10,973.65. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's big blue chip stocks often rise in tandem with Wall  
Street because they do much of their business in the United States 
and their fates are closely linked to those of U.S. companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But some market participants doubted the rally would continue in  
Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the gain came from speculative trading that had a  
disproportionately large impact due to low volumes, said Kiyoshi 
Kimura, strategist at Societe Generale. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was light as many market participants had yet to return  
from summer vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 26.02 points, or 1.80 percent, to 1,468.51. The 
TOPIX closed up 4.05 points, or 0.03 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 378.53 million shares, down from 455.06 million shares 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.9350 percent from Friday's finish of 1.8550 percent, 
driving its price down to 98.86 yen from 99.53 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
