<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Albanians Call Off Kosovo Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians called  
off a protest today in this tensely divided Kosovo town, averting a 
potentially violent confrontation with NATO peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	The demonstration was canceled after U.N. and NATO officials  
reached a deal with ethnic Albanians allowing 25 families per day 
to return to homes they lost in the Serb-dominated portion of 
Kosovska Mitrovica during the Kosovo conflict, all sides said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement was a positive development in the city, where  
ethnic Albanians clashed several times last week with French 
peacekeepers preventing them from crossing the bridge that divides 
the city's ethnic Albanian and Serb neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Another favorable event was the arrival early today in Kosovo  
Polje of some 200 Serb railway workers -- the largest known group of 
Serbs returning to Kosovo since June. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the 200,000 Serbs had fled to escape the wrath of ethnic  
Albanians infuriated by atrocities and torching of their homes by 
Serb forces who pulled out in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Bajram Rexhepi, mayor of the ethnic Albanian sector in Kosovska  
Mitrovica, announced the compromise deal to a crowd of some 150 
people who had gathered near the bridge for the scheduled protest 
on the bridge over the Ibar River. 
</P>
<P>
	The local commander of the Kosovo Liberation Army, Rrahman Rama,  
dressed in a camouflage uniform with the rebel group's badge, waded 
through the crowd, telling people to go home. 
</P>
<P>
	Some would-be demonstrators were confused, others clearly angry  
at the cancellation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sleeping in a front yard with my eight children. So how  
can somebody stop me from going to my home. We shouldn't listen to 
anybody. We should just cross this bridge and go to our homes.'' 
Jashar Osmani, 52, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Albanians had originally wanted 100 families a day to go  
back, Rexhepi said. About 1,200 families were waiting to go back to 
the Serb-dominated side, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary-Pat Silveira, the deputy U.N. chief in the city, said the  
informal proposal had received ``tacit agreement'' from the Serb 
side. The arrangement was reached in talks between U.N. and NATO 
officials, Rexhepi and a Serb delegation. 
</P>
<P>
	Silveira said she hoped that some families could begin returning  
this week. However, some of the homes are now occupied by other 
displaced people, in some cases Serbs, and officials have to find 
alternative shelters for the current residents before the Albanians 
return, she said. ``We will not put people out in the street,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was also unclear how much protection the ethnic Albanians  
will receive once they return to their homes. They will be escorted 
back by French peacekeepers, and a U.N.-NATO committee will make 
daily visits to ensure they are all right, Silveira said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, three buses crossed the border between  
Yugoslavia and Kosovo, carrying 200 Serbs returning to Kosovo Polje 
to start working at the local railroad station. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the workers, Andjelka Sup, said she had left Kosovo  
alongside Serb forces and now returns with KFOR, the name of the 
international peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will start working immediately and I hope that KFOR will  
bring more people here so that they provide more security,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In another step in U.N. efforts to create a pluralistic society  
amid Kosovo's ethnic hatreds, 50 ethnic Albanian and Serbian judges 
agreed to form a commission to draw up a new, democratic body of 
laws for the Serb province, said U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes. 
Some Albanian judges had threatened to step down rather than 
enforce laws that discriminated against ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence and lawlessness that has plagued the NATO-led  
mission continued, however. A patrol of German peacekeepers were 
fired on by a group of men they stopped to demand identity papers 
on Sunday. One peacekeeper was hit but saved by his flak jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	In Belgrade, one of the closest allies of Yugoslav President  
Slobodan Milosevic resigned after criticizing his policies. 
Bogoljub Karic had been a Serbian government minister without 
portfolio. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition has been growing against Milosevic, fueled by anger  
at policies that many in the public blame for the 78-day NATO 
bombing, Yugoslavia's international isolation and its economic 
problems. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
