<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 14:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Rebounds from French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MASON, Ohio (AP) -- Pete Sampras has found an antidote for the  
depression he suffers after losing the French Open. It's called 
winning. 
</P>
<P>
	Every year Sampras loses -- often early -- at Roland Garros and  
has to hear the same old thing about tanking the big one on clay. 
This year was particularly painful, the loss coinciding with a 
breakup with a longtime girlfriend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Up until the French Open and after the French, I was about as  
low as I've ever been, personally and professionally,'' Sampras 
said Sunday. ``It was a very tough time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he went home to Orlando, Fla., to collect himself, he  
decided a new outlook was needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I looked at Queen's and the rest of the year as a new  
beginning and tried to put what happened at the French behind me 
and the whole year just behind me,'' Sampras said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I learned from it. That's a sign, or a time, to really show  
your true colors when things aren't going well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He went to London to play in the Queen's Club, a grass court  
tournament, to get ready for Wimbledon. He won there and hasn't 
stopped since, adding titles at Wimbledon -- his sixth -- Los Angeles 
and the ATP Championship in Mason. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since Queen's, winning that tournament and getting the  
confidence I needed to get going in Wimbledon, it's just kind of 
all just carrying over to the summer,'' Sampras said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a big relief winning Wimbledon because I felt like I  
achieved my main goal this year, which was to win a Grand Slam 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just riding the wave, and I hope that wave doesn't crash  
anytime soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's straight-set victory over Patrick Rafter gave Sampras  
the 60th title of his career. He'll play at Indianapolis this week, 
then take a week off before the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know what I have to do at the Open, but this definitely  
helps,'' Sampras said. ``There's no question that to win tough 
matches and to beat the top players in the world is what I'm trying 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The streak of 22 consecutive wins is the second longest of his  
career. He won 29 in a row in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first three or four months of the year, I was struggling  
and not really playing much,'' Sampras said. ``I felt like my game 
wasn't really in sync.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras was exhausted from a December push to finish the year at  
No. 1 -- something he says he won't do again now that he has 
finished the year at No. 1 a record six times. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not play in January, passing up the Australian Open,  
although he has won it twice and his goal is to amass Grand Slam 
tournament titles. 
</P>
<P>
	He suffered an ankle injury and withdrew from the only  
tournament he entered in February, and he had a miserable early 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	He made it to the quarterfinals at Key Biscayne, Fla., but lost  
to Richard Krajicek for the fourth consecutive time. He took off 
nearly two months, then lost in the second round at Rome and then 
to Rafter -- for the third consecutive time -- in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the French Open, where Sampras lost to Andrei  
Medvedev, at the time ranked 100th in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	But this past week gave Sampras a chance to settle some old  
scores. In successive matches, he beat his nemesis Krajicek, 
longtime rival Andre Agassi and Rafter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look at the Krajicek match as a hurdle because he's been  
pretty dominant in blowing me off the court a couple times,'' 
Sampras said. ``And Pat beat me the last three times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rafter said Sampras had definitely elevated his game.  
</P>
<P>
	``Pete never let me play well, it's as simple as that,'' Rafter  
said. ``I couldn't get into the game. He just served too big and 
too hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras served 12 aces, landing 67 percent of his first serves.  
In the first-set tiebreaker, one serve broke four strings on 
Rafter's racket. 
</P>
<P>
	Sampras said he was surprised that so many of his serves were  
clocked over 130 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played at a time when it was hot and dry and the ball was  
going through the air very quick,'' Sampras said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only five players in the open era have more tournament titles  
than Sampras -- Jimmy Connors (109), Ivan Lendl (94), John McEnroe 
(77) and Bjorn Borg and Guillermo Vilas (62). 
</P>
<P>
	Winning the ATP Championship kept Sampras at No. 1 for a record  
273rd week. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just get into a certain rhythm, and my rhythm is there at  
the moment,'' Sampras said. ``The challenge is just trying to 
maintain it for the next couple of weeks.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 12:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander To Quit Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander  
ended his presidential campaign today after finishing poorly in 
Saturday's Iowa straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``My heart my heart tells me to keep going and so do a lot of  
telephone calls this morning, but there's really no realistic way 
to do that,'' said Alexander, flanked by his wife and son at the 
state Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	There also were troubling signs for former Vice President Dan  
Quayle, who was surprised today with the desertion of campaign 
leaders in South Carolina, a critical GOP primary state. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rats may be jumping off the ship, but the ship isn't  
sinking,'' said Quayle spokesman Jonathan Baron. 
</P>
<P>
	Having campaigned almost nonstop for six years, Alexander had  
waged an all-out battle for the weekend straw vote, but placed a 
meager sixth. He appeared resigned but lighthearted as he faced a 
crowd of news cameras this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I may learn a lesson from this. I seem to be attracting more  
attention getting out than I did getting in,'' he said, joking that 
his immediate plans included perfect attendance at University of 
Tennessee football games. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander did not endorse any of his remaining rivals, but said  
he hoped they would adopt his signature proposals on education and 
expanded tax deductions for families. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that the successful Republican nominee for president of  
the United States -- whoever he or she may be -- does a remarkably 
good job of bringing out the best in our country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, 59, did not endorse any of his remaining rivals, but  
said he hoped they would adopt his signature proposals on education 
and expanded tax deductions for families. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, who ran unsuccessfully for president in 1996, had  
focused all his energies on the initial caucus state. He received 
1,428 out of 25,549 votes cast in the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	That contest was won by Texas Gov. George W. Bush, whose  
front-running campaign has dried up Alexander's fund-raising 
sources and competed for the same base of moderate Republican 
voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush stands to benefit from today's announcement, because many  
Alexander supporters could be expected to shift to Bush. Sen. John 
McCain of Arizona and former American Red Cross president Elizabeth 
Dole, who finished a strong third in Saturday's poll, also may pick 
up some Alexander backers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor is expected to pick up most of Alexander's  
fund-raising team and perhaps his top adviser in Iowa, former Gov . 
Terry Branstad. Michigan Gov. John Engler, a top Bush operative, 
has been courting Branstad, according to the Alexander officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle and his senior advisers rejected any talk that he, too,  
might quit, saying they purposely spent little money on the straw 
poll and were prepared for a poor showing. The vice president, they 
said, is determined to emerge as the only credible, conservative 
alternative to Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing has changed,'' Baron said.  
</P>
<P>
	Still, there was talk from some of his aides that his campaign  
might be short-lived. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's campaign announced today that he had signed up members  
of Quayle's team in South Carolina, including his campaign 
director. Spokesman Howard Opinsky said the moves had been 
discussed before the straw poll, but Quayle's poor showing sped up 
the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	According to angry Quayle aides, Edward McMullen Jr. and Jim  
Merrill submitted their resignations by fax with no warning, after 
McCain's campaign announced the departures. Merrill was Quayle's 
state director; McMullen was a critical supporter, but was never 
officially named chairman, the Quayle campaign said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With their help, we will challenge the status quo and begin to  
restore honesty and integrity back to our government,'' McCain 
said. ``Our common cause of conservative reform is key to restoring 
the nation's lack of confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush was elated about his straw poll win. ``We met our  
expectations,'' he declared Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswoman Karen Hughes told NBC that Bush is increasingly the  
target of rivals because ``they think he's well on the road to 
being the Republican nominee for the White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Publisher Steve Forbes said his strong second-place showing  
means Bush must now engage him on issues and in serious campaign 
debate. ``So far, he (Bush) hasn't put a lot on the table,'' he 
said on ABC's ``This Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dole gave her campaign a boost with a third-place showing. ``We  
have an invisible army, and that's another reason we won,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other clear developments emerged as strategists began assessing  
the impact of a straw poll that drew heated competition and 
millions of dollars in spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Commentator Pat Buchanan mounted a strong showing for the GOP  
nomination in the last election cycle but finished fifth in the 
straw poll. He dodged questions on CBS and Fox about whether he 
would bolt the party to run as an independent or third-party 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	And on NBC and CNN, Gary Bauer said his fourth-place showing  
solidified him as the leader of social conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, the only contender to skip the straw poll, said he might  
bypass Iowa's leadoff precinct caucuses next February as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now I'm leaning toward it,'' McCain said today on ABC's  
``Good Morning America'' when asked if he would skip Iowa. ``I'd 
like to see how the climate looks. ... New Hampshire is the 
first-in-the-nation status, South Carolina is right after that. ... 
I think they are of transcendent importance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press reporters Ron Fournier in  
Washington and Mike Glover in Des Moines contributed to this 
report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
