<HEADLINE> Brazilian Co., Microsoft Sign Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. has signed a deal  
with the Brazilian media giant Globo to form a series of online 
joint ventures, the companies said late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft will pay $126 million in for an 11.5 percent stake in  
Globo's cable subsidiary, Globocabo, a Microsoft spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies will also sign technical cooperation agreements to  
explore delivery of WebTV, develop a joint Internet Service 
Provider and merge their respective Web portals in Brazil, the 
spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Globo President Roberto Marinho was quoted in a report by  
Globo's TV news network Monday as saying the company's ``quality of 
content'' and Microsoft's expertise in technology would benefit 
Brazilian consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Globo dominates pay and broadcast television in Brazil. Globo  
controls much of the nation's top broadcasting talent and produces 
its most watched television programs, including favorite soap 
operas and the country's top ranked news program. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet use in Brazil is growing rapidly. The country of almost  
170 million people has installed more than 11 million new phone 
lines within the last year and added more than one million Internet 
users, according to market researchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently at around 3 million, the number of Brazilians  
accessing the Internet is expected to rise to 7 million in three 
years, and to account for 60 percent of all users in Latin America. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
