<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sotomayor Must Answer Doping Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Track and field's world governing body  
rejected appeals by Cuban officials today and ruled that world high 
jump champion Javier Sotomayor must face doping charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor, the world-record holder in the high jump, tested  
positive for cocaine earlier this month at the Pan American Games 
in Winnipeg, Canada, and was stripped of his gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor has denied knowingly taking any banned drug. Cuban  
officials have supported him and suggested his test was manipulated 
as part of a conspiracy, possibly involving the CIA. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was discussed today at a meeting of the International  
Amateur Athletic Federation Council in Seville. 
</P>
<P>
	Sotomayor was defended at the meeting by Cuba's delegate on the  
Council, former Olympic 400- and 800-meter champion Alberto 
Juantorena, who is head of Cuba's national athletics federation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The opinion of the Cubans is there is not a doping case,''  
IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri said. ``The opinion of the doping 
commission of the IAAF is that it is a doping case. They asked the 
Cuban federation to follow the normal procedure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF expects national federations to suspend any athlete  
testing positive for banned drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless the Cuban federation suspends Sotomayor, the IAAF could  
ban him, Reineri said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the spokesman said the case is not urgent because  
Sotomayor is scheduled to undergo surgery for a herniated disc in 
his lower back and has pulled out of the World Championships 
opening this weekend in Seville. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
