<HEADLINE> Fumes Overcome 9 at Senate Cafeteria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nine workers were taken to a hospital for  
treatment Monday after strong fumes were reported in the cafeteria 
of a Capitol office building. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the Everett M. Dirksen Senate Office Building was  
evacuated while a hazardous materials crew tried to find the source 
of the fumes. Checks for natural gas, carbon monoxide and other 
substances came up negative. 
</P>
<P>
	What was the problem?  
</P>
<P>
	``There was a very strong and somewhat noxious odor of onions in  
the area,'' said Officer James P. Rohane of the Capitol Police. But 
cafeteria workers were skeptical of that explanation. 
</P>
<P>
	The cafeteria reopened for lunch featuring ham, fried chicken,  
stir-fried shrimp and filet of sole. None of the dishes was 
prepared with copious amounts of onions, the workers said. 
  	   	
