<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Jar' Characters Cast With Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The recriminations fly fast and furiously in  
``Jar the Floor,'' playwright Cheryl L. West's enchanting if 
overstuffed comedy that concerns four generations of black women. 
</P>
<P>
	The ladies have gathered for the 90th birthday celebration of  
MaDear, a flinty yet increasingly feeble matriarch whose 
descendants seem to bring out the worst in each other. Yet their 
bickering and their blowups produce some effective theatrics, 
guaranteed to please audiences who are after a good time. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because West has a flair for character, real people who  
stay with you after the curtain has come down. In ``Jar the 
Floor,'' she has created five distinctive women. And fortunately, 
the off-Broadway production currently on view at Second Stage has 
cast them with care. 
</P>
<P>
	Let's start with Lola, a brazen grandma played to the comic hilt  
by Lynne Thigpen. She sashays and struts her way around the stage 
with more than enough sass to spare, singing ``Whatever Lola wants, 
Lola gets.'' Watching the amazing Thigpen, you know she will. 
</P>
<P>
	Lola has had to contend with her mother, the 90-year-old MaDear,  
and her daughter, Maydee, a determined, embittered academic 
nervously awaiting news of a possible tenured position. 
</P>
<P>
	Maydee is also awaiting the arrival of her own daughter, the  
college-age Vennie. Vennie eventually does show up, along with a 
white girlfriend named Raisa. 
</P>
<P>
	The complications may be predictable but director Marion  
McClinton knows how to keep things lively. Thigpen gets ample 
support from the rest of the fine cast. 
</P>
<P>
	Regina Taylor may be saddled with the play's sourest character,  
the self-sacrificing Maydee, but the actress invests the role with 
a dignity and common sense that takes her beyond being just a 
scold. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Powell plays Maydee's lesbian daughter with the right  
amount of petulance. She, too, doesn't get off easy as West creates 
another woman whose frailities inevitably get an airing. 
</P>
<P>
	These battles reach a head in Act 2 with a piling on of  
problems. Abortion, sexual molestation, abandonment. They all get 
ample discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet walking along with the heartache is a lot of humor, too.  
There is something quite wonderful in the reaching across 
generations, particularly in a scene between great-grandmother 
MaDear (a terrific Irma P. Hall) and the young white girl, sweetly 
played by Welker White. They discuss their tribulations -- Raisa, a 
bout with breast cancer and MaDear, the fact of having lived as 
long as she has. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite its obviousness, the moment is filled with a gentle,  
good-natured comic spirit. Much like a lot of ``Jar the Floor.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 10:44:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Poll a Momentum Boost for Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush threw down a  
gauntlet to the Republican presidential field with a clear and 
convincing victory in a battle he had been advised to duck. 
</P>
<P>
	In some ways, the story line of the upcoming campaign will be  
how those rivals respond to the challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``The race is now George W. Bush's to lose,'' said Drake  
University political scientist Hugh Winebrenner. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush started late, raised the bar of expectations by vowing to  
win Saturday's straw poll against candidates building toward the 
event for months, and then did precisely that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have more than accomplished what we set out to do,'' an  
elated Bush declared. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no way to say this is anything but a solid win,''  
Michigan Gov. John Engler said as the strategists and campaigns 
began to assess a straw poll eagerly awaited by many to take the 
measure of a large and diverse Republican field. 
</P>
<P>
	Publisher Steve Forbes met one challenge, and then found himself  
confronted immediately by another. He demonstrated that an 
expensive and intensive grass-roots campaign could land him a 
second-place showing, and he was arguing that set him up as the 
alternative to Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now Bush will have to engage us on the issues and the issues  
are our playing field,'' said Forbes strategist Greg Mueller. ``The 
wind of inevitability is out of the Bush sails.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I am the conservative alternative to challenge the  
status quo candidates,'' Forbes said. Like the third-place 
finisher, Elizabeth Dole, Forbes has never held elective office and 
faces the challenge of seeking the nation's highest office as his 
first. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole argued that her showing earned her top-tier standing and  
respect from the pundits, saying a brand-new pool of young and 
professional women is fueling her campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have an invisible army and that's another reason we won,''  
she said. ``It's the people the pollsters didn't survey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's far from clear that Dole can motivate that army in numbers  
that pose a threat to Bush, well beyond the 3,410 votes she drew in 
the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservative activist Gary Bauer finished fourth with his  
church-based network and seeks to coalesce social conservatives, 
although Forbes is courting the same group. The publisher brings 
along a personal fortune, and some pragmatists argue he can level 
the financial playing field with Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I've got staying power,'' Bauer contended. ``We expect  
to go all the way to the convention. 
</P>
<P>
	For the other Republican candidates, there was little good news  
in the straw polls results. Some acknowledged it openly, others did 
not. 
</P>
<P>
	``The No. 1 rule in politics is to peak on Election Day'' and  
not in a summertime straw poll, former Vice President Dan Quayle 
said on CNN. He said he ``absolutely'' will continue in the race 
despite his eighth-place finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander headed home to assess his  
options. Aides said today that he had decided to drop out of the 
race. Both he and Quayle faced serious fund-raising questions, and 
it would be hard to convince financial backers they have a 
realistic shot at the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been frequent suggestions that commentator Pat  
Buchanan could move to another party if his bid for the GOP 
nomination falters. His fifth-place showing, along with his 
reaction to it, did little to quell the rumbling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know exactly where I'm going to be in August of  
2000,'' when the nomination is awarded, Buchanan said. His fiery 
blend of conservative populism isn't a good fit with most of the 
alternative parties, and it's difficult to see him carving out a 
role within the GOP either. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Sen. John McCain skipped the straw poll, and he has left  
little doubt he'll bypass Iowa's leadoff caucuses next February to 
focus on the New Hampshire primary. 
</P>
<P>
	``I may not want to be a part of that,'' said McCain, arguing  
he'd prefer to focus on more traditional election campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	He faces trouble, however, because he is left out of the  
political mix in the meantime, and candidates criss-crossing in 
Iowa get far more attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a meaningless kind of senseless thing,'' McCain said of  
the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	It also offered an early definition of the presidential  
campaign, and McCain wasn't included. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Mike Glover has covered Iowa presidential  
campaigns for The Associated Press since 1984. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
