<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PlayStation, Nintendo 64 Cut Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Prices on both the Sony PlayStation and  
the competing Nintendo 64 will be cut to $99 as the gaming console 
companies prepared for the upcoming release of Sega's new Dreamcast 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is obviously a defensive move in an extremely competitive  
market,'' said Chris Byrne, a toy industry analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne said that the new low prices announced Monday -- both  
dropping from $129 -- will allow consumers without a lot of extra 
entertainment money to go ahead and buy a console. He said that 
high-end buyers interested in the best systems will probably 
replace their existing systems with the $199 Dreamcast, a system 
reviewers say push the entertainment into new, exciting realms with 
enhanced graphics and sound. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the cuts are also going to help get consoles under  
more Christmas trees this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new pricing is certain to have a positive impact on unit  
sales during the upcoming holiday selling season,'' says David 
Leibowitz, managing director of Burnham Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony introduced PlayStation in 1995 at $299. Since then, Sony  
has sold more than 55 million units worldwide, landing in one out 
of every five U.S. households. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony's closest competition has been the Nintendo 64. Nintendo  
has sold almost 20 million of the units. 
</P>
<P>
	Sega Enterprises Ltd. -- which holds a distant third position in  
the market -- is preparing to launch Dreamcast on Sept. 9. So far, 
demand for the Dreamcast has been strong, with more than 200,000 
pre-orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Nintendo's executive vice president of sales and marketing Peter  
Main said the timing is right for his company to gain significant 
market share. 
</P>
<P>
	``Historically, whether on home systems like the 16-bit Super  
Nintendo Entertainment System or the handheld Game Boy, Nintendo's 
share of sales grows as the product cycle extends,'' Main said. 
``For every avid game player anxiously watching for a new hardware 
platform, there are five or more discriminating consumers just 
waiting for the existing library of top games to come within their 
financial reach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Kaz Hirai, president of Sony Computer Entertainment America,  
said the PlayStation will continue to dominate the market, with the 
lower price serving to broaden the company's audience. 
</P>
<P>
	Nintendo said the price cuts take effect immediately, while Sony  
said the cuts go into effect Aug. 23. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 22:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burlington To Buy Poco Petroleums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Burlington Resources has agreed to buy Canada's  
Poco Petroleums Ltd. for $1.75 billion in stock, making 
Houston-based Burlington the fourth-largest natural gas producer in 
North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement announced Monday, Poco shareholders will  
receive .25 Burlington share for each share of Poco held, or a 
one-for-four exchange. Based on Burlington Resources' closing stock 
price Monday of $45.31 1/4, the deal values each Poco share at $11.33. 
That represents a 25 premium over Poco's closing price Monday of 
$9.03 (13.40 Canadian dollars) before it was halted on the Toronto 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Burlington also will assume $750 million in Poco debt.  
</P>
<P>
	Poco's 300 employees will be retained and added to Burglington  
Resources' staff of 1,750, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal marks Burlington Resources' entry into the Canadian  
market and further strengthens its position as the dominant 
independent exploration and production company in the U.S. market, 
President Bobby S. Shackouls said. 
</P>
<P>
	``BR, with Poco as its partner in Canada, will be better  
positioned than at any time in its history to continue the 
implementation of our aggressive, global, value-oriented capital 
program,'' he said. ``In short, Poco is an ideal company to be BR's 
growth platform in Canada, and to build value for the shareholders 
of the combined enterprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Ferguson, Poco's vice president and chief financial  
officer, said merger talks had been under way for about three 
months. He said the two companies are comparable in their 
aggressiveness and the youth of their staffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a very large producer of natural gas in Canada, and  
they're a very large producer of natural gas in the U.S., but they 
don't have anything in Canada so it's a good fit. The cultures are 
very similar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which is expected to close by the end of the year, has  
been approved by directors of both companies but is subject to 
shareholder and regulatory approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company will rank behind only Exxon, BP Amoco and  
Royal Dutch/Shell in North American natural gas production. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies had a combined total of 9.9 trillion cubic  
feet in worldwide reserves as of Dec. 31. Combined 1998 worldwide 
gas production was 2.1 billion cubic feet per day; oil production 
was approximately 106,000 barrels per day. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 18:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks' Lee Out 3-5 Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The Arizona Diamondbacks placed first baseman  
Travis Lee on the 15-day disabled list Monday and acknowledged he 
will be out much longer than that. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee sprained his left ankle while fielding fly balls during  
batting practice before Sunday's game against Milwaukee. Lee said 
he's been told he'll be sidelined for at least 3-5 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it rains it pours,'' Lee said. ``After what's gone on the  
last couple of months, this is the icing on the cake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, considered a cornerstone of the franchise when he signed a  
$10 million signing bonus in 1996, had lost his starting job in 
recent weeks and was mired in a 2-for-43 slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Buck Showalter had been starting either Erubiel Durazo,  
the hot-hitting youngster just called up from Triple-A Tucson, or 
Greg Colbrunn at first, with Lee coming in as a defensive 
specialist in the late innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee was hitting .236 with nine home runs and 50 RBIs, and there  
was talk that he would be sent to Triple-A Tucson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks were considering using him some in the  
outfield, and he was working on judging fly balls off the bat when 
he turned his ankle on the outfield grass and fell to the ground in 
pain. He had to be taken off the field in a medical cart. 
</P>
<P>
	There was ligament damage to the ankle, and Lee left the  
ballpark on crutches. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you tell me he'll be back in three weeks, I'd be fine with  
that,'' Showalter said. ``It has the potential to be longer than 
that. When ligaments are involved, you're dealing with a lot of 
unknown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To replace Lee on the roster, the Diamondbacks called up  
outfielder Rob Ryan from Triple-A Tucson. Ryan, like Lee, is a 
left-handed batter. He was hitting .290 with the Sidewinders with 
30 doubles, 19 home runs and a team-high 88 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's always mention as being as a lot like (David) Dellucci,''  
Showalter said. ``We hope so, because that's a heck of a 
compliment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan, 26, is one of the first players to work his way up through  
Arizona's farm system. A 26th-round selection in the 1996 free 
agent draft, Ryan started at Lethbridge in 1996, moved up to South 
Bend in 1997 and spent the last two seasons with Tucson. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exciting, and to come up here and by right in a pennant  
race, that's really something,'' Ryan said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
