<DOCNO> APW19990816.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 17:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexicans' Families To Be Paid $30M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Insurers for an American clothing company have  
agreed to pay $30 million to the families of Mexican workers killed 
and injured when a bus taking them to a factory in Mexico crashed. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen people died and 12 were injured in June 1997 when the  
bus went off a rain-slicked road, crashed and caught fire before 
rolling into a sewage ditch near the Mexican town of Valle Hermosa, 
about one hour south of Brownsville, Texas. Lawyers for the workers 
charged the bus was unsafe, that officials ignored warnings about 
faulty brakes, and that the driver was untrained. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawsuit filed by the workers and their families against New  
York-based Salant Corp. went to a jury trial in state district 
court in the border town of Eagle Pass. After two weeks of 
testimony from 11 witnesses, including a survivor, the lawsuit was 
settled before the company began its defense. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement was disclosed Monday in a Salant filing with the  
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Caddell, lead lawyer for all but one of the plaintiffs,  
said the amount of the settlement should convince foreign companies 
they won't be protected from Mexico's ``lax'' enforcement of 
worker-safety laws. 
</P>
<P>
	But a trade group questioned the ruling's legitimacy and said it  
would be detrimental to the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``If frivolous lawsuits get going because of this, it could be  
devastating,'' said Dennis Charlton, an official with the 
Maquiladora Association in Mexico and owner of a rainwear factory 
in Piedras Negras, Mexico. ``The big question is, what's the 
legality of having a jury in Eagle Pass decide about something that 
happened in Mexico?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salant and a Mexican trade official protested hearing the case  
in Texas, but an appeals court in San Antonio and the Texas Supreme 
Court allowed it to go ahead because the subsidiary and its 
officers were based in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Caddell said it was crucial that the case be heard in U.S.  
courts. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Mexico, you get no jury, and I frankly don't think a judge  
in Mexico would've made the same award as a jury in Eagle Pass,'' 
he said. ``Mexico is so eager to attract foreign investment that 
it's willing to look the other way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its filing with the SEC, Salant denied liability. It is  
expected that Salant's insurance companies, Chubb, Cigna and 
Hartford, will pay the entire $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer has been appointed to decide how the settlement will be  
divided among families of the dead and the survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	Salant's lawyers declined to discuss the company's view of the  
case. 
</P>
<P>
	``The insurers offered to settle, and it was settled,'' said  
Howard Close, a Beaumont lawyer who represented Salant. 
</P>
<P>
	Salant, which had 1998 sales of $300 million, makes several  
lines of Perry Ellis menswear. The factory where the dead and 
injured workers were employed was operated by a subsidiary, Texas 
Apparel Co., and made jeans for Wal-Mart, Sears and Kmart. Salant 
sold the factory and other clothing lines earlier this year in an 
unrelated post-bankruptcy restructuring. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
