<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Straw Poll Runs as Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The expected winner won. The expected casualty  
quit the campaign. The rest of the field of Republican presidential 
candidates, just as predictably, claimed satisfaction, or at least 
survival. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowa straw poll ran to form, a forgettable, expensive  
episode in the campaign for the 2000 GOP presidential nomination. 
These straws pointed no change in the winds. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Gov. George W. Bush won as he'd said he would. Lamar  
Alexander, who already was struggling for lack of funds, ran sixth 
and dropped out of the race Monday. Steve Forbes outspent 
everybody, came in second, 10 points behind Bush, and said that 
showed he'd be the real challenger to the front-runner. Elizabeth 
Dole finished third and called it a strong victory. Conservatives 
Gary Bauer and Pat Buchanan were next among nine entries. 
</P>
<P>
	It probably was the last straw for this Republican campaign. For  
the leading candidate, just-for-show votes like the one Saturday 
night in Ames, Iowa, can only be traps. Win, and the political 
world yawns, while rivals say the margin was not impressive, as 
they are saying now of Bush's 30 percent. Lose, or be tied, as Bob 
Dole was in 1995, and it is read as evidence of weakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida Republicans have staged straw polls in prior campaigns,  
but not this time. Gov. Jeb Bush quietly squelched that. 
</P>
<P>
	Celebrating his Iowa victory, George Bush told his supporters:  
</P>
<P>
	``Some pundits said I had nothing to gain and potentially a lot  
to lose. Well, thanks to you, we gained a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But what he gained was far less than what he staked when he  
entered the straw poll campaign two months ago and said he'd win. 
Anything else would have been an embarrassing setback for the man 
in command of the public opinion poll rankings and the competition 
for Republican campaign cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush probably did gain with Alexander's exit, since allies of  
the former Tennessee governor may well sign on with the 
front-runner now. But the one rival who skipped the straw poll, 
Sen. John McCain of Arizona -- he called it a sham -- gained in the 
fallout. After former Vice President Dan Quayle's forlorn eighth 
place in the straw poll, four leaders of his campaign in South 
Carolina defected to McCain, who is concentrating on the 
presidential primaries there and in New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said he will absolutely keep running, but his campaign  
already has had fund-raising trouble, and the Iowa showing could 
make it worse. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander had cut his campaign staff to save money for his  
all-or-nothing quest for a straw poll showing that might have 
persuaded donors to help him. No go, but the straw poll only 
accelerated the inevitable end of a campaign that had to compete 
with Bush for centrist GOP donors. 
</P>
<P>
	At his farewell in Nashville, Tenn., after campaigning almost  
nonstop for six years, Alexander said that while there is ``a 
powerful force'' for a Bush nomination, he won't join it with an 
endorsement now because there should be competition in next year's 
primary elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be better off if the contest runs,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Forbes has the personal fortune to make sure of that, as he did  
with his attack ad campaigns against Bob Dole and Alexander in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes got 20 percent of the straw poll vote, after a campaign  
that cost at least $1.4 million, closer to $2 million according to 
his rivals. The Bush campaign spent more than $750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush and Forbes were the only two who could afford it, because  
they aren't bound by state spending limits that apply to candidates 
who accept federal funds for their campaigns. Forbes with his own 
money, Bush with the $40 million plus he has raised from GOP 
donors. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can buy a straw poll,'' Quayle said, who got 4 percent.  
``You can't buy an election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it takes money to run. Bush's challengers did not come away  
from the straw poll with evidence to sway donors their way. With 
his long lead in the public opinion polls and his command in fund 
raising, Bush has what he needed: Nothing unexpected, a field 
narrowed by one but with no major changes in the ranking of the 
leading candidates, and a win to add to his front-runner's resume. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
