<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colts' James Gets Ready for Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TERRE HAUTE, Ind. (AP) -- First-round draft pick Edgerrin James  
had his first extensive training camp practice Monday since ending 
his three-week holdout with the Indianapolis Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	The fourth overall draft pick gave himself a passing grade.  
</P>
<P>
	``I felt pretty good,'' said James, designated the team's  
starting tailback when he was drafted in April, joined the team in 
camp after signing a seven-year, $49 million contract Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'm a little further ahead than people expected. A lot  
of time when I was holding out, I was doing a lot of working out. 
Also, I was studying my plays, so I'm making very few mistakes,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The need to get James ready for Saturday's exhibition game at  
New Orleans became more crucial when Darick Holmes became the first 
member of the team to suffer a major injury. Holmes, the starter at 
tailback in place of James in the first two exhibition games, 
suffered a broken fibula near his right ankle as the Colts defeated 
Cincinnati 20-17. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jim Mora said that Holmes, who watched practice on a golf  
cart and is walking with crutches, would be out for about six 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes was injured on the Colts' first possession of the second  
quarter after catching a swing pass from Peyton Manning. He was 
originally tackled by Bengals cornerback Artrell Hawkins and then 
was hit by linebacker Oliver Gibson when he attempted to get back 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was definitely the second hit that produced the injury,''  
Holmes said Monday. ``He said he didn't hear a whistle, so I don't 
know if it was a late hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James, surprisingly drafted ahead of Heisman Trophy winner Ricky  
Williams, denied feeling any added pressure about playing his first 
NFL game this week against Williams and the Saints. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ricky is on offense. I'm on offense, so I really don't look at  
it as my first game being against Ricky Williams. The first game is 
against the New Orleans defense,'' said James who hopes to boost a 
running game that has netted only 86 yards on 36 carries by running 
backs in two games. 
</P>
<P>
	It's too early to judge the running game, James said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have to come together as a team,'' he said. ``In the  
preseason, you have to get everything correct and we have enough 
time leading up to the first game. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the preseason, you're going to try different things and  
different looks. To the fans, it looks like we aren't doing 
anything, but we're just trying things out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest disappointment to me so far has been our running  
game,'' Mora said. ``I think we'll do a better job as we get 
going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mora said it was too early to decide how much James will play  
against the Saints. However, he doesn't plan to rush James because 
of the injury to Holmes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll stick with what we would have done. We're not going to  
push him, or rush him. We've got two games and we've got three 
weeks,'' Mora said in reference to the opening game of the regular 
season against Buffalo on Sept. 12. ``He'll be ready. He's a pretty 
sharp guy, he'll study hard. He went out there today. He didn't 
make a lot of mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seemed comfortable.''  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Colts cut their roster by waiving linebacker  
Antony Jordan, quarterback Jim Kubiak and tight end Joe Kuyendall. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other players didn't practice Monday. Defensive back Paul  
Miranda, who sprained a ligament in his right knee Saturday, is 
expected to be out for 3-to-4 weeks. Defensive back Craig Miller 
was excused to attend the funeral of a relative. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
