<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Throws Out AOL Case vs. AT&AMP;T </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal judge tossed out America Online Inc.'s  
case against AT&AMP;T Corp. over the ``You have mail'' slogan, ruling 
that AOL doesn't have exclusive rights to the popular expression. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also refused to block AT&AMP;T from using ``buddy list''  
and the abbreviation ``IM'' with its free instant messaging 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	The dismissal on Friday by U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton of  
Alexandria, Va., was the latest setback to AOL's attempt to control 
the spread of phrases it coins for its own Internet service. 
</P>
<P>
	When AOL subscribers get electronic mail, a computer voice  
announces ``You've got mail'' and the message ``You have mail'' 
appears on the screen. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL sued after AT&AMP;T started using ``You have mail'' last  
December on its WorldNet e-mail service. But the term already had 
expanded into popular culture with the release of last year's movie 
``You've Got Mail,'' starring Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan as e-mail pen 
pals. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T maintained that it is a commonly used English phrase. The  
court agreed on that phrase as well as on the terms ``buddy list,'' 
which is a catalog of a computer user's frequent electronic pen 
pals, and IM, shorthand for the instant messaging service. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL said an appeal was planned.  
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the court's decision incorrectly interprets  
well-established foundations of trademark law,'' AOL's general 
counsel, Paul Cappuccio, said in a statement. ``We are confident 
that the ruling will be reversed.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 18:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
