<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:06:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  East Timor Vote On Despite Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- The United Nations will go ahead with the  
upcoming vote on East Timor's future despite continued threats 
against civilians and U.N. staff, a U.N. envoy said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamsheed Marker, the United Nations' top envoy for the  
half-island territory, did not specify who had made the threats. In 
the past, however, officials of the U.N. Assistance Mission in East 
Timor have accused anti-independence militiamen of similar acts. 
</P>
<P>
	``UNAMET is not going to be put off course one degree by  
elements, rogue elements or ... hoodlums. We have a job to do and 
we will do it,'' Marker said of the vote slated for Aug. 30 that 
will allow East Timorese to decide whether to stay part of 
Indonesia as an autonomous region or to become fully independent. 
</P>
<P>
	Marker said he had informed Indonesian security forces about the  
threats, including a report that one armed group planned to attack 
U.N. staff on polling day. He had also heard of other threats 
against thousands of displaced villagers who have fled their homes 
to escape earlier attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Marker's remarks come only a week after rival East Timorese  
factions signed a code of conduct that bans violence and threats 
during the campaign period, which started peacefully last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to parliament today, President B.J. Habibie vowed to  
respect the outcome of the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	While Habibie said he was confident that the rest of Indonesia  
would remain united, even if East Timorese chooses to secede, he 
floated a warning just in case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Political actions that are against the constitution -- for  
example breaking away from the republic of Indonesia -- we cannot 
tolerate at all,'' he said. ``Democracy and freedom must follow the 
constitution, law, ethics and morality that were laid down by the 
founders of the Indonesian republic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The upcoming election has sparked secessionist demands from  
other provinces, such as oil-rich Aceh in the far west of Sumatra 
island and Irian Jaya on New Guinea. Rebels are fighting Indonesian 
troops in both regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia occupied the former Portuguese colony in 1975 and East  
Timor has been wracked by guerrilla warfare and human rights abuses 
since then. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of an independent East Timor has polarized the  
region's 800,000 people. Anti-independence militias, allegedly 
formed with the support of Indonesia's military, are blamed for a 
wave of violence in recent months. Dozens of civilians have been 
killed and tens of thousands displaced. 
</P>
<P>
	Independence activists say the majority of East Timorese want to  
break away. They accuse the militias of waging a terror campaign to 
stymie the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the pro-Indonesian militias handed over 97 guns today, in  
keeping with an accord by all armed groups to disarm ahead of the 
ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.N. representative, Brig. Gen. Resaquel Haider, attended the  
ceremony in the village of Atabae, 100 miles southwest of Dili. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:06:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  East Timor Vote On Despite Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- The United Nations will go ahead with the  
upcoming vote on East Timor's future despite continued threats 
against civilians and U.N. staff, a U.N. envoy said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamsheed Marker, the United Nations' top envoy for the  
half-island territory, did not specify who had made the threats. In 
the past, however, officials of the U.N. Assistance Mission in East 
Timor have accused anti-independence militiamen of similar acts. 
</P>
<P>
	``UNAMET is not going to be put off course one degree by  
elements, rogue elements or ... hoodlums. We have a job to do and 
we will do it,'' Marker said of the vote slated for Aug. 30 that 
will allow East Timorese to decide whether to stay part of 
Indonesia as an autonomous region or to become fully independent. 
</P>
<P>
	Marker said he had informed Indonesian security forces about the  
threats, including a report that one armed group planned to attack 
U.N. staff on polling day. He had also heard of other threats 
against thousands of displaced villagers who have fled their homes 
to escape earlier attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Marker's remarks come only a week after rival East Timorese  
factions signed a code of conduct that bans violence and threats 
during the campaign period, which started peacefully last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to parliament today, President B.J. Habibie vowed to  
respect the outcome of the ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	While Habibie said he was confident that the rest of Indonesia  
would remain united, even if East Timorese chooses to secede, he 
floated a warning just in case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Political actions that are against the constitution -- for  
example breaking away from the republic of Indonesia -- we cannot 
tolerate at all,'' he said. ``Democracy and freedom must follow the 
constitution, law, ethics and morality that were laid down by the 
founders of the Indonesian republic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The upcoming election has sparked secessionist demands from  
other provinces, such as oil-rich Aceh in the far west of Sumatra 
island and Irian Jaya on New Guinea. Rebels are fighting Indonesian 
troops in both regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia occupied the former Portuguese colony in 1975 and East  
Timor has been wracked by guerrilla warfare and human rights abuses 
since then. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of an independent East Timor has polarized the  
region's 800,000 people. Anti-independence militias, allegedly 
formed with the support of Indonesia's military, are blamed for a 
wave of violence in recent months. Dozens of civilians have been 
killed and tens of thousands displaced. 
</P>
<P>
	Independence activists say the majority of East Timorese want to  
break away. They accuse the militias of waging a terror campaign to 
stymie the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the pro-Indonesian militias handed over 97 guns today, in  
keeping with an accord by all armed groups to disarm ahead of the 
ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.N. representative, Brig. Gen. Resaquel Haider, attended the  
ceremony in the village of Atabae, 100 miles southwest of Dili. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
