<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 17:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Skip Debate on Yom Kippur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Despite protests by the United States and  
Israel, the annual debate at the U.N. General Assembly this year 
will start on Yom Kippur, the holiest day for Jews -- but without 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, as leader of the host country, traditionally  
speaks on the first day of the two-week general debate, which 
brings leaders from around the world to New York. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton is skipping the Sept. 20 opening session ``out of  
respect for the Jewish residents of the New York area,'' and will 
instead deliver his address on Sept. 21, said deputy U.S. 
ambassador Peter Burleigh. 
</P>
<P>
	While United Nations is closed on two Christian holidays,  
Christmas and Good Friday, and two Muslim holidays, Eid al-Adha and 
Eid al-Fitr, it has never acknowledged the holiest day for Jews. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to Secretary-General Kofi Annan earlier this month,  
the head of the American Jewish Congress urged a postponement of 
the start of the General Assembly until Sept. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the attitude so often demonstrated by the U.N. towards  
Israel, it is perhaps not surprising that Yom Kippur is ignored,'' 
wrote congress executive director Phil Baum. ``We are asking only 
for basic fairness -- that the same treatment and recognition 
accorded to Christianity and Islam be extended to Judaism as 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baum noted that Yom Kippur, the day of atonement, is observed by  
Jews around the world -- from Australia, Japan and Russia, to 
Britain, South Africa, and Mexico, in addition to Israel and the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In his reply made public Monday, Annan said the date had been  
decided by the 185 member states of the General Assembly -- and that 
only the General Assembly could reconsider the date. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me express my sincere regret for the discomfort that the  
decision of the General Assembly may have caused you and members of 
the Jewish faith around the world,'' the secretary-general said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to assure you of my commitment to promoting warm  
and harmonious relations between the United Nations and the Jewish 
community,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Democratic congressmen, Benjamin Gilman of New York and Sam  
Gejdenson of Connecticut, also sent a letter to Annan several 
months ago protesting at the Sept. 20 starting date. 
</P>
<P>
	At meetings earlier this year Burleigh said he had pushed not to  
have the session start on Yom Kippur. But he said Sept. 20 ended up 
having almost ``universal agreement.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0081 </DOCNO>
