<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Racial Segregation Accepted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- About half the young adults in a recent poll  
said racial separation in America is all right ``as long as 
everyone has equal opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the poll released Monday in Washington by Hamilton College of  
Clinton, N.Y., 50.3 percent of respondents said they strongly or 
somewhat agreed with the statement: ``It's OK if the races are 
basically separate from one another as long as everyone has equal 
opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, 47.3 percent of those polled strongly or  
somewhat disagreed with the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, co-sponsored by the NAACP and Zogby International,  
surveyed 1001 randomly selected people ages 18 to 29 over one week 
in April and had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	``This indicates that many young Americans are comfortable with  
the notion of a segregated society,'' said Phillip Klinkner, 
director of the Arthur Levitt Public Affairs Center at Hamilton 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a cause for concern since many school districts are  
dismantling their integration efforts at a time when new data show 
rising levels of school segregation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other poll findings included:  
</P>
<P>
	--Some 56 percent said the federal government should make sure  
black people receive fair treatment in jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	--About 57 percent agreed that generations of slavery and  
discrimination have created conditions that make it difficult for 
blacks to work their way out of the lower class. 
</P>
<P>
	--Some 54 percent said it was unlikely the United States would  
elect a black president in the near future. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 17:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baerga Back With Cleveland Indians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Carlos Baerga, once considered the heart and  
soul of the Cleveland Indians, returned to the team on Monday as a 
backup infielder hoping for yet another chance at resurrecting his 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga, who played with the Indians from 1990-96, was acquired  
from the San Diego Padres for a player to be named or cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland plans to use him to back up third baseman Enrique  
Wilson, who in turn can play middle infield to give shortstop Omar 
Vizquel and Roberto Alomar some rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Following San Diego's 7-6 win over Florida on Sunday night,  
Baerga, who earlier this year was back in the minor leagues, was 
told by Padres general manager Kevin Towers that a deal with 
Cleveland was on the table. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, 'Do you want to go?','' Baerga recalled before Monday  
night's game against Texas. ``I said, `Yeah, I want to go.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	After arriving from San Diego early in the afternoon, Baerga was  
back at Jacobs Field for the first time since the Indians traded 
him in 1996. He made his first start for Cleveland since July 25, 
1996, and batted eighth as the Indians opened a four-game series 
with the Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	When Baerga came to the plate in the second inning, the 351st  
straight sellout crowd at Jacobs Field gave him a standing ovation 
and he waved to fans before digging in and striking out in his 
first at-bat. 
</P>
<P>
	During his first stint with the Indians, Baerga was one of the  
club's most productive and popular players. He batted over .300 
four straight seasons, and in 1992 joined Hall of Famer Rogers 
Hornsby as the only second baseman to hit .300, have 200 hits, 20 
homers and 100 RBIs in a season. He named to three All-Star teams. 
</P>
<P>
	His energy was infectious in the clubhouse as was his smile, and  
when the Indians went from being baseball's laughingstock franchise 
to legitimate contenders, Baerga became one of the club's stars. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Indians detected a decline in his talent, and coupled  
with concerns about Baerga's off-the-field behavior, the club 
traded him along with Alvaro Espinoza to the New York Mets on July 
29, 1996, for Jeff Kent and Jose Vizcaino. 
</P>
<P>
	``That may have been the toughest day I ever had as a manager,''  
Cleveland's Mike Hargrove said. ``Because he was Carlos. I remember 
saying it then and still meaning it, he was really the heart and 
soul of this ballclub for a long, long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga said it took him more than 1 1/2 years to get over the shock  
of the trade. Initially, he was critical of the Indians and 
Hargrove, but said before long he understood that it was a business 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Following an inconsistent 2 1/2 seasons, Baerga was not re-signed  
by the Mets, and he signed as a free agent with St. Louis last 
January. The Cardinals released him during spring training, and he 
signed a minor-league deal with Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	But Baerga felt he should be playing in the majors, and asked  
the Reds for his release in late May. He signed with Las Vegas, San 
Diego's Triple-A affiliate, and after 21 games was promoted to the 
Padres, the same team which gave him his start in 1986. He hit .250 
in 33 games with San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people who went through what I went through this year  
would have retired,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	With starting third baseman Travis Fryman, out with a knee  
injury, not expected to be ready until September, the Indians were 
looking for a dependable backup for Wilson, a middle infielder 
forced to play third. 
</P>
<P>
	``Carlos gives us more options so we can give some of our  
regulars some rest,'' Hargrove said. ``I'm glad to have him here. I 
think it's going to be good for us. The energy level, the 
experience he has of playing in big games and big situations, I 
think it's a perfect fit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baerga realizes he needs to perform well to have a future in  
Cleveland beyond the next few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is my house; this is where I started, '' he said. ``I'm  
just looking to help the team.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
