<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harrah's May Buy Players for $272M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Players International Inc. said  
Monday it has agreed to be acquired by Harrah's Entertainment Inc. 
for $272 million in cash, and would terminate a merger agreement 
reached earlier with Jackpot Enterprises Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Gambling industry analysts applauded the move, saying it will  
open new markets for Harrah's, particularly in the Houston area. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlantic City-based Players said its board accepted Harrah's  
offer of $8.50 per share -- a 30 percent premium over Players' 
Friday closing price of $6.56 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal surpasses an $8.25-a-share cash and stock for Players  
made by Jackpot, a Las Vegas-based slot machine operator. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately known if Jackpot would come back with a  
higher bid and possibly start a bidding war for Players. 
</P>
<P>
	``The board of directors is reviewing their options,'' Jackpot  
spokeswoman Tina Fleischmann said Monday. ``I can't say we were 
expecting it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackpot and Players shareholders were scheduled to vote Sept. 14  
on their deal, in which Jackpot would pay $6.75 in cash and $1.50 
in Jackpot stock for each Players share. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrah's, based in Memphis, Tenn., said it anticipated entering  
into a binding agreement with Players by Thursday. The deal 
requires approval from regulators and Players shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street liked the Harrah's bid. The company's stock rose 75  
cents to $22.63 a share on the New York Stock Exchange, while 
Players was up $1.34 at $7.91 on the Nasdaq Stock Market and 
Jackpot rose 44 cents to $7.94 on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just another feather in Harrah's cap,'' said analyst John  
J. Rohs at Schroder &AMP; Co. Inc. ``It's a very good move for the 
company. Obviously, it's not a done deal yet, but strategically it 
makes a lot of sense for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal puts Harrah's into two new markets -- Lake Charles, La.,  
and Metropolis in southern Illinois -- allowing the company to add 
two more sites on its ``Total Gold'' frequent user program, Rohs 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal also gives Harrah's access, through Lake Charles, to  
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The price, which includes assuming $150 million of Players'  
debt, is ``very attractive,'' said Stuart Linde, an analyst at 
Lehman Brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrah's is one of the country's largest gambling companies,  
with 18 casinos in the United States under the Harrah's, Showboat 
and Rio names. 
</P>
<P>
	Players International operates two cruising riverboat casinos in  
Lake Charles, La.; a riverboat casino on the Ohio River in 
Metropolis, Ill.; two dockside riverboat casinos in Maryland 
Heights, Mo.; and a horse racing track in Paducah, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Harrah's would also gain complete control of a  
joint venture it has with Players, operating a landside hotel and 
entertainment facility in Maryland Heights, a St. Louis suburb. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
