<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney Eyes Young Bride's Motives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- The attorney for a 74-year-old man who  
disappeared from a nursing home last week and married a 56-year-old 
woman is questioning the motives of the bride. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry W. Strouse, a wealthy, retired, antiques dealer, has been  
in hiding since sneaking out of the Rose Haven Convalescent Home 
and marrying Molly Bennett Aitken. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple, speaking from an undisclosed location, has said if  
Strouse hadn't fled, his attorney would have involuntarily 
committed him to the nursing home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to go back there,'' Strouse said. ``Call me the  
runaway groom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strouse was reported missing Wednesday. He married Aitken in a  
civil ceremony in New York City on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Strouse's attorney, Peter Litwin, called a news  
conference. He said his client suffers from ``progressive 
dementia,'' and may not be in control of his actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Litwin, who has power of attorney for Strouse, has not accused  
Aitken of stealing from his client, but pointed out that his client 
is wealthy and said that a collection of antique silver is missing 
from Strouse's estate. 
</P>
<P>
	He would not say how much the silver is worth.  
</P>
<P>
	State police confirmed they were investigating.  
</P>
<P>
	Aitkin said she was motivated by love, not money.  
</P>
<P>
	``I love Harry. I will do anything to protect him,'' she said,  
adding that she is well provided for by a trust fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
