<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-NBA Player Dismissed of 2 Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A judge on Monday dismissed the two most  
serious charges against ex-NBA player Dontae' Jones in connection 
with a spring shooting outside a Nashville nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 24, was accused of simple assault with bodily injury,  
reckless endangerment and felony vandalism after a shootout outside 
the Players Draft House club April 25. Seven people were wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	General Sessions Judge Michael Mondelli dismissed the reckless  
endangerment and felony vandalism charges after the testimony of 
Darryle L. Tyce, a security guard, during a preliminary hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who has been free on $8,000 bond since his arrest, was  
bound to the grand jury on the assault charge. If convicted, he 
would face a maximum of 11 months and 29 days in jail and a $2,500 
fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I protested my innocence,'' Jones said after the hearing.  
``When this is all over with, I'll go back to doing what I do best, 
and that's play basketball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who grew up in Nashville, led Mississippi State to the  
Final Four and was MVP of the Southeastern Conference tournament in 
1996. He was then drafted by the New York Knicks in the first 
round, and subsequently traded to the Boston Celtics who released 
him in January. 
</P>
<P>
	He was scheduled to play with La Crosse of the CBA this fall as  
part of his effort to make it back to the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyce said he didn't see Jones shoot at him April 25 outside the  
club, though he did see Jones' friend Karshma Dardy hand Jones a 
gun shortly before the shooting began. In an affidavit, Tyce had 
previously claimed that he saw Jones fire at him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many times, detectives will help with the wording of the first  
statement,'' prosecutor T.J Haycox said. ``It's not uncommon for a 
witness to think about it and change some details.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyce said he couldn't see if Jones shot at him because he was  
turning away and ducking for cover. Tyce was shot in the stomach, 
and required surgery to remove eight inches of his colon. 
</P>
<P>
	The simple assault with bodily injury charge against Jones stems  
from Vergena Forbes, who was collecting admission at the door of 
the club April 25. Forbes testified that Jones used profanity as he 
threatened her, and lunged towards her because he wanted money. 
</P>
<P>
	The club was the site of a party for organizers of a downtown  
Nashville music festival when things started getting rowdy, Tyce 
said. When he started shutting down the club early at the owner's 
direction, music performers were upset they wouldn't be allowed to 
perform. 
</P>
<P>
	Friction between a group of rappers from Memphis and Jones'  
entourage developed over the money collected at the door of the 
club, Tyce testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Mondelli bound charges of reckless endangerment and felony  
vandalism against Jones' friend Dardy over to a grand jury. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
