<HEADLINE> Dow Up 25.33 at Midday / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher today as investors  
awaited the next inflation indicator and tried to assess whether 
the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
25.33 at 10,998.98. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also up slightly. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was up 2.76 at 1,330.44, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was up 16.71 at 2,654.52. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said some investors were locking in profits from  
Friday's big rally, when the Dow gained 184.26 points and the 
Nasdaq soared 88.32. Stocks rose after a moderate rise in the 
Producer Price Index suggested the Fed might not need to implement 
a big rate hike to fight inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed has already raised rates once this year, and has  
signaled its willingness to do so again if it believes the economy 
is growing too fast. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Commerce Department will release its Consumer  
Price Index, another widely watched gauge of inflation that could 
determine the Fed's course of action at its next policy-making 
meeting Aug. 24. Many analysts believe investors will be reluctant 
to make major new bets until then. 
</P>
<P>
	Hewlett Packard rose 4 15/16 to 110 15/16. The computer maker  
was scheduled to release its fiscal third-quarter earnings report 
after the close of trading today. Analysts surveyed by First 
Call/Thomson Financial called for Hewlett Packard to earn 80 cents 
per share, compared to 58 cents per share a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Optimism about computer companies' earnings helped the Nasdaq  
extend its gains today. Applied Materials, up 1 13/16 to 71 9/16, 
is scheduled to report its earnings Tuesday, and most analysts 
expect the semiconductor company to post strong profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds Metals fell 1/2 to 68 7/8 after Alcoa began a tender offer  
for the company. Last week, Reynolds rejected a $5.6 billion 
takeover offer from Alcoa and began weighing an offer from 
investment firm Michigan Avenue Partners. Alcoa slipped 1/8 to 66 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 260.20 million 
shares, well behind Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 0.66 at 622.04, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 2.06 at 781.68. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.07 to 433.98.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
