<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thompson Placed on Disabled List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- After Justin Thompson's rough start Sunday,  
Detroit manager Larry Parrish said the left-hander was ``mentally 
beat up.'' Now the Tigers are giving him a couple of weeks off to 
check out physical problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, 9-11 with a 5.11 ERA, was placed on the 15-day  
disabled list Monday because of neck and shoulder problems. 
Thompson, an All-Star in 1997, has led the Tigers in innings 
pitched, strikeouts and complete games the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Matt Anderson was recalled from Triple-A Toledo to  
replace Thompson on the roster. 
</P>
<P>
	The move came a day after Thompson gave up six earned runs in  
five innings during a 10-2 loss to Anaheim. Thompson is 0-3 with a 
9.82 ERA in four starts since July 21. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's tried to pitch through this for a while, but the time has  
come where we have to get his neck and shoulder checked out,'' 
Parrish said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson will have an MRI exam on Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's just something I've been battling all year. I've been  
having just a roller coaster ride, just up and down,'' Thompson 
said. ``Finally I just said I can't do it no more. I can't go out 
there and get beat up and not give our team a chance to win. I need 
to go ahead and get this thing healthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parrish said Sunday that Thompson might not start again this  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel confident I'll be back,'' Thompson said. ``If I get  
well and I feel like I'm able to go out there and throw and be 100 
percent, then I won't be happy if they shut me down. But I'm not 
coming back until I'm 100 percent. I know not everyone is going to 
be 100 percent every start, but you can't go out there and pitch 
feeling like I have. ``I can't really remember the last time I went 
out there and actually felt good. I don't even know where the ball 
is going when I throw it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Willie Blair (1-9) will make Thompson's scheduled start Saturday  
at Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who turns 23 Tuesday, was touted as the Tigers'  
``closer of the future'' when he was Detroit's top pick in the 1997 
amateur draft. His 100 mph fastball quickly made him a fan favorite 
when he was called up last season. 
</P>
<P>
	But he had a 6.08 ERA in 24 appearances as a late-inning set-up  
man this year before he was sent to Toledo on June 7. He had a 6.39 
ERA with the Mud Hens, allowing nine home runs and 31 walks in 38 
innings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
