<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bailey, Heck To Start for Redskins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FROSTBURG, Md. (AP) -- It took just three weeks of training camp  
-- and one exhibition game touchdown -- for Champ Bailey to earn a 
starting cornerback job for the Washington Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 7 overall draft pick took his place among the first-team  
unit Sunday, promoted over Darryl Pounds after a 46-yard 
interception return for a score in Friday night's 20-14 victory at 
New England. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is what I've been working toward,'' Bailey said. ``It was  
one of my goals and come out and start as a rookie. It took a lot 
of hard work. Darryl Pounds is a great corner, so I don't think it 
was anything that he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey and Pounds actually started Friday's game, but only  
because Darrell Green had a jammed finger. Now, with Green back at 
practice, Pounds has been relegated to backup and nickel duty. The 
coaches expect Bailey to start the remaining exhibition games, and, 
of course, the regular season opener against Dallas on Sept. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got better each and every week,'' defensive backs coach  
Tom Hayes said. ``He's doing a lot of good things. Is he there yet? 
No. He needs to continue working, and he needs to keep on pace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey wasn't the only player moving up the depth chart Sunday.  
Andy Heck started working with the first unit at left tackle ahead 
of Joe Patton, who gave up a sack on a blown assignment Friday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had some problems early with protection,'' coach Norv  
Turner said. ``I thought (moving Heck up) was the appropriate thing 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches expected Heck, an 11-year veteran, to be their starting  
left tackle when he was signed as a free agent in June, but he's 
done little to stand out. He struggled at times Sunday, getting 
knocked to the ground more than once and finding defensive end 
Marco Coleman to be a handful. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've just been trying to knock some rust off from the  
offseason, learning this system as best I can,'' Heck said. 
``There's a lot of evaluating left to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Heck or Patton can't hold the position, the only alternatives  
left on the current roster are career backups Kipp Vickers and 
Jamie Brown. Shar Pourdanesh, who has 36 NFL starts at tackle, was 
upset when he was demoted to the second-team earlier in camp and 
was traded to Pittsburgh on Friday for a seventh-round draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Bailey, he scored the first time he touched the ball,  
bringing back memories of Green doing the same as a rookie 16 years 
ago. Green returned a punt 61 yards in the exhibition opener 
against Atlanta in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey said he had a gut feeling the throw was coming his way  
from Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who was calling an audible 
at the line of scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	``He checked, he looked at me, he looked back the other way, and  
it was just the anticipation of a quick throw,'' Bailey said. ``I 
just happened to be on my toes at the right time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, competition for two other positions remains wide  
open. Turner said he would alternate running backs Skip Hicks and 
Stephen Davis with the first-team unit this week before deciding 
which player starts Friday against Buffalo. Davis started against 
New England. 
</P>
<P>
	At kicker, Brett Conway and Cary Blanchard will both handle  
kickoffs and field goals against the Bills. Jeff Hall will sit out 
the game after missing badly on a 23-yard attempt against the 
Patriots. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't give up. I'm going to keep working,'' said Hall, a  
sixth-round draft pick. ``What if I'd made a game-winning field 
goal? What if? Am I going to base the rest of my football career on 
one kick? So whether it's good or bad, there's another day coming, 
another practice, and hopefully after that another game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
