<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Titans' Debut Spoiled by Mistakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Tennessee Titans wanted their  
exhibition opener to be the start of a whole new era for the team. 
They're still waiting. 
</P>
<P>
	``An awful start,'' coach Jeff Fisher said Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	The Titans stumbled out of the gate in the 22-20 loss at Kansas  
City on Sunday night as their first two possessions ended in an 
intentional grounding for a safety and an intercepted pass returned 
for a touchdown. The much-improved pass rush didn't touch the 
quarterback once. 
</P>
<P>
	Receivers dropped five balls, while the defense missed two  
interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fisher sounded much more positive after watching the film,  
pointing out the Titans have plenty of time to improve with three 
more exhibition games before the season opener on Sept. 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``Big plays against the defense will hopefully diminish and the  
big plays in our offense ... should increase as the preseason goes 
along,'' Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve McNair, who has spent the offseason working on his  
passing, was the third-best quarterback for the Titans despite 
being the starter. He was 6-of-11 for 66 yards and one touchdown 
compared to backup Neil O'Donnell who was 10-of-17 for 73 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher quickly doused any questions about McNair, who has missed  
several practices due to a stiff back in training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no concern whatsoever about our starting quarterback  
being Steve McNair. It's preseason. These are things you learn from 
... I do know what he's capable of. There is not going to be a 
quarterback controversy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Donnell, signed to a one-year deal, has picked up the Titans'  
offense quickly. But he reverted to his old snap count a couple of 
times, including one time before he had even gotten under the 
center. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the beauty of the preseason,'' Fisher said.  
</P>
<P>
	The defensive line, which has four new players, also looked good  
to Fisher. He liked what he saw from rookies Jevon Kearse and John 
Thornton. Kearse keyed a goal-line stand in the first quarter with 
a hit that allowed linebackers Joe Bowden and Barron Wortham to 
stop Bam Morris. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very optimistic and encouraged about the potential that we  
have there to increase the pressure on the quarterback despite the 
fact it didn't necessarily show up,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no reason to be alarmed.''  
</P>
<P>
	Once the Titans got moving, they looked like the Oilers of last  
year with Eddie George doing most of the work. The Titans have 
promised since last season ended that they will throw the ball deep 
to take the pressure off George. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said nine deep pass plays were called even though McNair  
completed the longest pass at 22 yards. He said the game plan will 
be more complicated Friday night when the Titans visit the Arizona 
Cardinals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
