<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fumbles Pose Threat to Buffalo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Bills rushed for 188 yards in  
their exhibition opener against Seattle. Not too bad an effort. 
</P>
<P>
	But subtract quarterback Rob Johnson's 53 yards, remember that  
starter Antowain Smith is hobbled by sore groin and add in the 
fumbles of backup Jonathan Linton and suddenly, the Buffalo ground 
game is a lot scarier on paper than it is on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who led Buffalo with 1,124 yards in his second season  
last year, started training camp with a bang then came up limping 
and has been unable to go full speed in practice for any length of 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Shawn Bryson, the team's third-round draft pick and a Tennessee  
teammate and close friend of second-round selection Peerless Price, 
was lost for the season when he tore a knee ligament last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of Bryson increased the load on Linton, who was cured  
by coaches of a tendency to drop the ball last year. Linton 
relapsed in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of four drives led by Doug Flutie early in the game ended  
with fumbles by Linton, two of which were lost. Linton recovered 
his own fumble on a fourth-down play at the goal line that should 
have been a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no excuses for that,'' Linton said Monday. ``That  
should never happen. It was just lack of focus and lack of 
concentration. I can't let that happen if I want to be part of this 
football team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills are losing patience with Linton, who has a habit of  
holding the ball too low when he makes his cuts. Protecting the 
ball is key for Linton, a straight-ahead back who is more likely to 
run over an opponent than around him. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had some concern with Jonathan,'' Bills coach Wade  
Phillips said. ``Hopefully this game helped him, because we've been 
on him in practice about the same thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A loose grip cost Linton the confidence of his coaches last  
year, after he fumbled near the goal line in an exhibition game 
against Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got him to where he felt comfortable holding the football,  
then he kind of reverted back this year,'' Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been on him in practice and talked to him in meetings.  
Once we get him out of that he'll be fine, because he ran the ball 
good; he just didn't hold on to it. But that's not good enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo has to be worried about Smith, even though Smith isn't.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's still some tightness,'' he said. ``But if there was a  
game today I'd be able to play, so I'm not really concerned about 
it too much. But it's going to take some time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony Gray, a rookie free agent from Western New Mexico who  
was listed third on the depth chart, carried 13 times for 74 yards 
and scored on a 24-yard run in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	On the touchdown run, Gray dodged one defender as he broke  
through the line and eluded another in the secondary. ``It looks 
like he may have enough talent to run in this league,'' Phillips 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo led the AFC last season in turnover ratio, collecting 11  
more than it lost and making that area of its game a priority. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the coaches fumed over Linton's fumbles, Flutie  
shrugged. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just write them off as a bad day,'' said Flutie, recalling  
that four fumbles and one interception cost the Bills a playoff win 
against Miami last year. ``Those days are going to happen, but you 
hope to minimize them and hope they don't happen at the wrong 
time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
