<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Painter Ion Pacea Dies at 74 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Romanian painter Ion Pacea, whose  
images of peasant women and shepherds have been exhibited on three 
continents, has died. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Pacea died Friday after suffering a long, undisclosed illness,  
Ioana Berenda of the Romanian Artists' Union said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pacea, famed for his simple oil paintings in vivid color, was  
inspired by peasant women, shepherds, birds, flowers and other 
symbols of the Romanian countryside. 
</P>
<P>
	During his career, he participated in numerous exhibitions in  
New York, Sao Paulo, Ankara, Munich, Rome and other cities. His 
last exhibition was at Bucharest's National Art Museum in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981, he was awarded the Italian Trionfo prize. He also was  
honored with a medal from the Caravaggio cultural center in Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Horopan, Macedonia, in 1924, he was loved for his  
personality as much as his work. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very modest and very polite with everyone,'' said  
Berenda. ``He was one of a golden generation. There are not many 
left like him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His funeral will be held Tuesday. Pacea is survived by a wife  
and a son, both painters. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
