<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Seeks Funds in Puerto Rico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Mining for campaign funds and votes  
in Puerto Rico, Bill Bradley allied himself Monday with local 
leaders who oppose turning the island into the 51st U.S. state. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as the people of Puerto Rico select commonwealth  
status, I will respect that commonwealth status and work with the 
people of Puerto Rico and Congress to even obtain more autonomy,'' 
the Democratic presidential candidate said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a nonbinding December referendum, voters rejected statehood  
by 54 percent to 46 percent. As a commonwealth, Puerto Rico's 3.8 
million residents are U.S. citizens but can't vote for president or 
Congress. The island, which is solidly Democratic, does send 
delegates to the presidential nominating conventions. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Rico is unfriendly ground for Bradley: pro-statehood Gov.  
Pedro Rossello serves on Vice President Al Gore's campaign staff 
and is one of his top fund-raisers, and most of the local party 
leadership supports Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	The pro-commonwealth faction of the local Democratic party, led  
by San Juan Mayor and gubernatorial candidate Sila Calderon, is 
disillusioned with the Clinton administration for what it sees as 
White House support for Rossello's statehood drive. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Bradley openly courted that faction.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know that just like in the rest of the country, there are  
people here who support me,'' he said. ``I'm looking for delegates 
... and each delegate is important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He got a warm response from Calderon's supporters.  
</P>
<P>
	``Up to this point, he of all the candidates has spoken most  
clearly to the people of Puerto Rico,'' said Anibal Acevedo Vila, 
who is running for Puerto Rico's nonvoting seat in the U.S. 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley was expected to raise thousands of dollars at a luncheon  
and a dinner at San Juan's Ritz-Carlton Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	A handful of business leaders attended Bradley's news  
conference, including contractor Ruben Velez, who surfaced during a 
1997 Republican probe into Clinton's campaign fund-raising. He 
appeared in a videotape trying to give Clinton a check during a 
visit to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said he was ``troubled'' by U.S. Navy exercises on the  
outlying Puerto Rican island of Vieques. The Puerto Rican 
government wants the Navy to leave Vieques, saying frequent bombing 
runs have stunted economic development and hurt the environment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there has been humanitarian and environmental damage  
that is unacceptable,'' Bradley said of Vieques. But he refused to 
take a position on the dispute until a commission appointed by 
Clinton presents its recommendations later this month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
