<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Insurance Mulls Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong  
said Monday the insurance industry may be liberalized to allow new 
foreign players. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at an insurance conference, he said Singapore's  
closed-door policy towards life insurers, in place since the 
mid-1980s, has insulated the domestic market from international 
trends. 
</P>
<P>
	``For Singapore to become a world class financial center, and  
for Singaporeans to have access to high quality insurance services, 
our industry must keep abreast of developments in the international 
financial services market,'' Lee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee said Singapore aims to become the top insurance hub in Asia  
by 2003, complementing its efforts to build a vibrant debt market 
and sophisticated asset management and banking industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, who also heads the Monetary Authority of Singapore, noted  
that Singapore's insurance industry needs to look into ways of 
improving performance. 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested local companies consider consolidation or seeking  
strategic alliances with foreign companies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
