<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani, Indian Troops Trade Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAMMU, India (AP) -- Pakistani troops fired machine guns and  
rockets at an Indian border post today, killing one soldier and 
wounding six others in a two-hour battle, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani forces opened fire before dawn during an attempted  
infiltration by Muslim militants into the Indian state of 
Jammu-Kashmir, police said on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian troops responded with machine-gun fire and forced the  
infiltrators back across the border, police said. An Indian soldier 
was killed and six Border Security Force members were wounded, 
three seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee accused Pakistan in a  
speech Sunday of training and arming militants waging war in 
Kashmir, and ordered them to stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of Islamic militant groups in Kashmir have been fighting  
a 10-year insurgency that has left more than 25,000 people dead. 
Some of the groups want independence for Kashmir, while others are 
seeking to join neighboring Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack destroyed most of the Indian border post at Charwah,  
50 miles south of Jammu, the winter capital of Kashmir, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	India says attacks by militants have increased since the Indian  
army launched a campaign in May to oust Pakistan-based fighters 
from the Himalayan heights of Kashmir. By late July, most of the 
Islamic fighters had been pushed back across the cease-fire line 
that divides the disputed region between India and Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	But skirmishes along the border and guerrilla attacks have  
continued. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian government contacted the International Committee of  
the Red Cross today to arrange repatriation of eight Pakistani 
prisoners of war from the Kashmir fighting. An offer for their 
return had been made Friday to the embassy of Pakistan, which has 
not acknowledged that any of its soldiers were fighting on the 
Indian side of the cease-fire line. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, separatist militants killed five people and wounded  
15 in bomb explosions and an attack on a police station in Kashmir, 
local officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Terrorists are being trained in Pakistan,'' Vajpayee said in  
his speech marking India's 52nd anniversary of independence from 
Britain. ``They are killing innocent people and targeting women and 
children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif made the same charge  
against Indian forces in his Independence Day speech on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan -- the world's newest nuclear powers -- have  
fought two wars over Kashmir, India's only Muslim-majority state. 
</P>
<P>
	In the worst violence in Kashmir on Sunday, guerrillas fired  
automatic rifles and rocket launchers at a remote police station in 
Chenani, 50 miles north of Jammu. 
</P>
<P>
	When police reinforcements came from a neighboring town, the  
guerrillas set off a land mine and opened fire on their vehicles 
from a mountaintop. Four officers were killed and 12 wounded, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pakistan-based Lashkar-e-Taiba rebel group sent a fax to The  
Associated Press claiming responsibility for the attack in Chenani. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, police said a civilian was killed in cross-fire between  
militants and officers in Anantnag, 40 miles south of Kashmir's 
summer capital, Srinagar. 
</P>
<P>
	In other violence blamed on separatists Sunday, two bombs  
exploded in the northeastern state of Assam, killing one person and 
wounding two others, a district police official said on condition 
of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Tribal militants are fighting for an independent homeland in the  
northeast. More than 10,000 people have been killed in fighting in 
Assam over the past decade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
