<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Tumbles, Cotton Rises  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures prices plummeted Monday, with the September  
contract falling to a five-year low, on news that cold weather over 
the weekend in Brazil apparently had little impact on the crop. 
</P>
<P>
	On other commodity markets, soybeans, corn and cotton all  
jumped. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices on Monday gave back the gains made Friday when  
prices rocketed higher on forecasts that a cold front could move 
through growing regions in Brazil, the world's largest producer. 
The front, however, never reached any coffee plantations, and 
prices tumbled. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we saw was the market's collective response to the  
realization that although there were patches of weekend frost ... 
there was no statistically significant damage,'' said Arthur 
Stevenson, an analyst with Prudential Securities Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a massive move and we had very heavy trading volume,''  
he added. ``It was a dramatic day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee prices have slumped over the past year with inventories  
of gourmet arabica beans high and demand in the U.S. low, as it 
always is in summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee for September delivery fell 8.85 cents to 89.75 cents a  
pound Monday on the Board of Trade of the City of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans and corn futures prices were higher in trading Monday  
on the Chicago Board of Trade on a forecast of dry Midwest weather. 
</P>
<P>
	A new dry spell would further stress crops already under  
pressure from July's heat wave. 
</P>
<P>
	Many traders continue to believe the crop production report  
released last week was overstated for corn supplies, providing 
further support for prices, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were also supported by word that China may be in the  
market for soybeans, as well as soy oil and meal. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains in soybeans prices were tempered by feelings that, the dry  
weather aside, recent rains may have benefited the crop. Market 
participants were also cautious ahead of the release of crop 
ratings after markets closed Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat prices followed corn and soybeans higher at the open but  
then turned slightly lower to close mixed. Weak export news, 
countered by support from soybeans and corn, led to a choppy trade. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Monday, wheat for September delivery rose 1/2 cent to  
$2.68 3/4 a bushel; September corn was up 4 1/2 cents to $2.14 a bushel; 
September oats were unchanged at $1.09 a bushel; and August 
soybeans were up 10 1/2 cents to $4.56 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, livestock and meat futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose 0.30 cent to 66.35 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell 0.07 cent to 77.20 cents a pound; October lean 
hogs rose 0.27 cent to 45.42 cents a pound; and August pork bellies 
rose 1.00 cent to 53.30 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Cotton futures were sharply higher Monday on the Board of Trade  
of the City of New York, with the December contract reaching a 
seven-week high. The market has received support from continued 
stress on the crop in the American South. 
</P>
<P>
	A few weekend showers did little to alleviate dry crops  
throughout the region, and high temperatures continued. 
</P>
<P>
	Cotton for October delivery rose 0.65 cent to 53.55 cents a  
pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
