<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's benchmark stock index closed the Tuesday  
morning session down slightly after investors took profits 
following a strong gain the previous day. The dollar rose against 
the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 6.19 points,  
or 0.03 percent, to 17,819.84 at the end of the morning session. On 
Monday, the average finished up 390.86 points, or 2.24 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.89 yen at midday, up 0.05 yen from its  
level of 114.85 yen late Monday in Tokyo and above its level of 
114.65 yen late Monday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei index fell on profit taking  
after a 2.2 percent gain the previous day, but underlying sentiment 
was still good as foreign investors continued to hunt for 
relatively inexpensive securities, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tokyo has had six straight days of market gains, so there is  
some profit-taking movement out there,'' said Kazunori Jinnai, 
deputy general manager of the equity department at Daiwa Securities 
SB Capital Markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 3.83 points, or 0.26 percent, to 1,472.34. The 
TOPIX closed up 26.02 points, or 1.80 percent, on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign exchange, the dollar rose marginally after Japanese  
institutional investors bought back oversold positions, a trust 
bank trader said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 121.22 yen, down  
from 121.58 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond  
yield rose to 1.9500 percent from its close Monday of 1.9250 
percent, driving its price down to 98.73 yen from 98.94 yen Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
