<HEADLINE> Pageant Eases Swimsuit Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- The Miss America Pageant hopes to  
boost ratings by easing restrictions on the types of swimsuits 
contestants can wear, stopping short of allowing anything too 
skimpy. 
</P>
<P>
	The pageant, which already announced it was cutting back on the  
number of talent acts it broadcasts, will hit the airwaves an hour 
earlier this year to draw more viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	There will also be scoring changes, with more emphasis on  
contestant interviews, pageant chief Robert Beck said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the pageant began allowing contestants to wear  
two-piece swimsuits that fell within recommended guidelines for 
color and style. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've taken away the details for the rules and left it to  
their common sense as long as they use some judgment,'' Beck said. 
``We're giving them another opportunity to be themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thongs or bikinis, however, are still forbidden.  
</P>
<P>
	``That wouldn't really match up with a family show,'' Beck said.  
</P>
<P>
	Swimsuits can be solid colors or prints and won't have to meet  
any measurement guidelines, though contestants must still register 
their swimsuit in advance. 
</P>
<P>
	The 79th annual Miss America Pageant airs Sept. 18 on ABC. Donny  
and Marie Osmond will be co-hosts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
