<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Questionable Assumptions / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Assumptions have a tendency to persist, even  
when an assumption is shown to be questionable. 
</P>
<P>
	Such as, for example, the assumption that the jobs being created  
in the 1990s are inferior to the manufacturing jobs that have been 
lost. It doesn't get much support from the numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics show that in the past four years, 9 million new jobs  
have been added to the economy, and that 7 million of them have 
been in managerial, technical and professional categories. 
</P>
<P>
	As cited by Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, the educational level also is  
improving. Over the past five years, college grads have accounted 
for 63 percent of the increase in the working-age population. And 
the number of high school dropouts has fallen. 
</P>
<P>
	Such evidence suggests strongly if not convincingly, that jobs  
are being created for more than hamburger flippers. Or, perhaps, 
that McDonald's is employing well-educated flippers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Judging from the number of initial public offerings, or IPOs, on  
the stock market, it is understandable you might think that new 
companies are being formed at a record pace. Not so. 
</P>
<P>
	Business startups actually fell 7 percent in 1998, according to  
Dun &AMP; Bradstreet, whose calculations are generally accepted as the 
final word. Moreover, new-business employment fell 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	People often assume that when the economy is strong, so also is  
business formation. But if last year's numbers -- and those of 
several other years too -- are an indicator, the opposite is true. 
</P>
<P>
	D&AMP;B identified 155,141 startup establishments in 1998, down from  
166,740 in 1997. Jobs fell to 906,105 from 939,310. The falloff was 
in every industry but agriculture and finance. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The late Julian L. Simon, a University of Maryland professor,  
spent two decades seeking to undermine what he said were imperfect 
perceptions about the environment, resources and population. 
</P>
<P>
	You might have noticed that much of the news about such economic  
categories has tended toward the dismal. Needlessly so, said Simon, 
who believed a great gap existed between perception and reality. 
</P>
<P>
	``The current gloom and doom about an environmental crisis is  
all wrong on the scientific facts,'' he argued, and more often than 
not he won his arguments. Bias, he suggested, was inherent. 
</P>
<P>
	An example: Attendees at an Audubon Society meeting were asked  
their estimates of how much of landfill volume was from fast-food 
packaging. Responses averaged 20 percent to 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The actual volume, said Simon, was no more than one-third of 1  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	How did he account for such misperceptions? Psychological and  
cultural mechanisms make people more receptive to bad news than 
good, he suggested. And, he said, journalists just didn't 
understand statistics, while politicians used them in service of 
policy goals. 
</P>
<P>
	His findings are collected in his last book, ``Hoodwinking the  
Nation,'' published by Transaction Publishers and available from 
the Cato Foundation, Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- ``Hoodwinking The Public'' can be obtained by  
calling 1-800-767-1241. The price is $29.95. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
