<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls in Quiet Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar lost ground against the euro and the  
yen in a quiet session Monday, as traders avoided risk in advance 
of the release Tuesday of the Consumer Price Index figures on U.S. 
inflation at the retail level. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro rose to $1.0575 from $1.0564  
late Friday. The dollar also was quoted at 114.68 Japanese yen, 
down from 115.74. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a risk-reduction period prior to the release of the  
CPI numbers,'' said Ricardo Gomes, head of foreign exchange at 
Republic National Bank. ``Everyone wants to see where those numbers 
stand before heading in a new direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The market is awaiting the CPI report because it comes a week  
before Federal Reserve policy-makers meet to decide whether to 
raise interest rates for a second time this summer. The Fed raised 
rates slightly on June 30 in a pre-emptive bid to prevent a 
resurgence in inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Gomes predicted that the U.S. stock and bond markets will rise  
or fall Tuesday based on the CPI numbers, and that the dollar would 
follow the lead of those two markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5154 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5159 Friday, and 1.4835 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4764. The 
British pound fell to $1.6013 from $1.6057. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8500 German 
marks, down from 1.8515; 6.2029 French francs, down from 6.2112; 
and 1,830.9 Italian lire, down from 1.831.5. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
