<HEADLINE> Senators, Yashin Unable to Agree </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Ottawa Senators center Alexei Yashin made it clear  
Monday that unless the last year of his contract is redone, he 
won't be there when training camp opens on Sept. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really tough to say, but at this point it doesn't look  
good,'' Yashin said before teeing off in his charity golf 
tournament at nearby Rivermead. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin was to fly to Florida on Tuesday to participate in  
pre-training camp workouts with about 25 other Russians and NHLers. 
It might be the closest he comes to playing in the NHL for a while. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin and his agent, Mark Gandler, were rebuffed by Senators  
general manager Marshall Johnston when they brought up the subject 
of renegotiating Yashin's contract, which has one more year on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin is due to make $3.6 million this season, a bargain price  
for the NHL's sixth leading scorer last season with 94 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked to the team and thought they'd be happy to know  
what's going to happen for a few years, but it was a completely 
different response,'' Yashin said. ``It wasn't especially great. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love this city and I want to play in Ottawa. It's tough to  
play when you're wondering about your future. The (club's) response 
was hard and it came right away. It didn't make us feel very 
good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin said the topic was brought up because ``there was a  
feeling in the air about what was going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he doesn't want to play this year wondering what's going  
to happen after the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want my mind to be 110 percent on hockey,'' he said. ``It's  
hard to play. People will say you're selfish in front of the net to 
get a good contract. I'm also captain of the team, so I think it's 
important to be totally fair to hockey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin could be a restricted free agent next summer, but said he  
thinks his bargaining position is strongest right now. He pointed 
to the few offers restricted free agents receive in today's market 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want Marshall and Mark to talk and find a good agreement for  
the future,'' he said. ``It can change any time. I hope it will.'' 
  	   	
</P>
