<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Utah, Wis. To Receive Disaster Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton declared parts of Utah and  
Wisconsin disaster areas Monday and ordered federal funds be spent 
to help those states recover from devastating storms. 
</P>
<P>
	The disaster money, which will be handed out by the Federal  
Emergency Management Agency based on the states' requests, will pay 
75 percent of the costs for debris removal, emergency services and 
restoring roads, buildings and utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	In Utah, where a tornado ripped through downtown Salt Lake City  
on Aug. 11, the federal funding will be available to individuals 
and local governments in Salt Lake County. The assistance can 
include housing and low-cost loans for uninsured property losses. 
</P>
<P>
	In Wisconsin FEMA will manage similar federal aid to at least 10  
counties where severe storms and flooding caused damage beginning 
on July 4. After Clinton's declaration, FEMA Director James Lee 
Witt on Monday designated Ashland, Bayfield, Douglas, Florence, 
Iron, Oneida, Price, Rusk, Sawyer and Vilas counties as being 
eligible for federal aid. Witt said more Wisconsin counties may be 
added to the list based on new damage assessments. 
</P>
<P>
	A White House spokeswoman said no estimate was yet available for  
the total dollars the federal government expects to spend on 
disaster aid in those states. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
