<HEADLINE> Man Sentenced for DNC Contributions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A businessman was sentenced Monday to three  
years of probation for violating federal elections laws by giving 
the Democratic National Committee an illegal $150,000 donation 
drawn from a South Korean corporation. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert S. Lee, 49, was one of 19 people prosecuted in a Justice  
Department investigation of campaign finance abuses in the 1996 
election. Lee also received 250 hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
	He pleaded guilty April 26 to one misdemeanor count of aiding  
and abetting in illegal campaign contributions from foreign 
sources, a violation of the Federal Election Campaign Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee gave the DNC a check drawn from an account that was entirely  
funded by a South Korean corporation, according to the Department 
of Justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee was an adviser and consultant to the Los Angeles development  
firm K&AMP;L International Partners Inc. K&AMP;L, which generated no 
revenues in the United States, received all of its operating funds 
from foreign sources. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
