<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bucs QB Family Safe After Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Eric Zeier's smile gave way to a burst of  
laughter. 
</P>
<P>
	The family of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers quarterback escaped  
serious injury in the crash of a small plane over the weekend. 
Knowing everyone was back home safely allowed him to make light of 
not being told about the accident until after an exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to have a little talk with them,'' the fifth-year  
pro said Monday of his mother's request that the news not be 
relayed to him during the game because she didn't want him to 
worry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, our motto here is family first. I have a wife and a  
little baby at home. Her family and my family, we're all very 
close. Regardless of what goes on on the football field, that's 
what's really important. You've got to take care of your family and 
take care of all those people who are close to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zeier's parents and sister were flying from their home in  
Marietta, Ga., to Tampa for Saturday night's exhibition against 
Cleveland when the Cessna 172 piloted by his father lost power and 
attempted an emergency landing near Chiefland, southwest of 
Gainesville. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Zeier, 48, was making the trip with his wife, Sharon, 49;  
daughter, Ellen, 21; and James Strickland, 25. No one was seriously 
injured when the plane clipped a power line, flipped and came to 
rest upside down. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mom said my dad did a tremendous job of flying the plane  
down. It was just a miracle,'' said Zeier, who learned of the 
accident as he was leaving the field after the Bucs' 30-3 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even when I knew everybody was OK, I was shaken up because I  
could imagine the fear that they felt in the air. It's a scary 
thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zeier said his father received his pilot's license about a month  
ago, so information vital to making emergency landings was fresh in 
his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``Under the circumstances, my dad did a really good job of  
getting the plane to where they could have landed safely,'' Zeier 
said. ``It's just one of those things. We haven't been able to 
figure out why it happened or what happened. Who knows. I'm just 
thankful everybody's OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Tony Dungy granted the quarterback time off to be with his  
family. But after speaking with his parents by telephone, Zeier 
decided against making the 100-mile drive from Tampa to Chiefland. 
</P>
<P>
	``They said: `No, don't worry about it.' ... They had some bumps  
and bruises and were beat up a little bit. But they said everything 
was fine and they rented a car and got on the road pretty early 
(Sunday).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zeier, a backup obtained in a draft-day trade with the Baltimore  
Ravens, was 11-of-16 for 135 yards and one interception in his 
preseason debut for the Bucs. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he appreciated his family not wanting the accident to  
become a distraction for him, Zeier said he would have preferred to 
have been given the news immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously it does shake you up a little bit, but I could have  
gone and played. It would have been tough. Who knows how I would 
have played or what I would have done? But something like that, it 
would have been nice to know,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regardless of what goes on on the field, whether it's a  
regular season game or a preseason game, you've got priorities in 
your life. ... It doesn't mean I don't take football seriously. I 
take football as seriously as anyone, but you really can't put 
football ahead of those things.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
