<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 03:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teammates Remember Reese As Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- At first, Randy Willis wasn't quite sure  
why his father was so excited. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were enjoying a minor league baseball game when his  
father, Henry, pointed out an older man sitting several rows behind 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told me it was Pee Wee Reese,'' Willis, 34, said before  
teeing off Sunday at a Louisville golf course located on a street 
named for the famous Brooklyn and Los Angeles Dodgers captain. ``I 
was only about 20 at the time and didn't really know who he was. 
But my dad knew everything about him. He went on and on about what 
a great player and a great man he was. 
</P>
<P>
	``He must have seen us looking at him because as he got up to  
leave, he came over and introduced himself, just out of the blue. 
You should have seen the look on my dad's face. I'll never forget 
it. And I know my dad never did either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reese, the Hall of Fame shortstop who helped ease the way for  
Jackie Robinson to break baseball's color barrier, died about 4 
p.m. Saturday at his Louisville home. 
</P>
<P>
	Reese, who overcame prostate cancer years ago, underwent  
radiation treatment for lung cancer in March 1997 after doctors 
removed a malignant tumor. He had been ill in recent years and had 
dramatically reduced his public appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Famer Duke Snider called Reese the greatest Dodger of  
them all. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you asked anyone on the ballclub how Pee Wee Reese helped  
him, they would say not only in baseball, but in their lives. 
Without his help, I never would have been a Hall of Fame player. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is the finest person I think I've ever met,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	An eight-time All-Star, Reese sparked the Dodgers to seven  
National League pennants. He led Brooklyn to its only World Series 
championship in 1955, fielding the final ball in a 2-0 victory in 
Game 7 at Yankee Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Inducted into baseball's Hall of Fame in 1984, his plaque at the  
Cooperstown, N.Y., institution only touches on his significance to 
the game and to those around him: 
</P>
<P>
	``Harold Henry `Pee Wee' Reese, Brooklyn, N.L., 1940-1957, Los  
Angeles, N.L., 1958. Shortstop and captain of great Dodger teams of 
1940s and `50s. Intangible qualities of subtle leadership on and 
off field, competitive fire and professional pride complemented 
dependable glove, reliable base running and clutch hitting as 
significant factors in 7 Dodger pennants. Instrumental in easing 
acceptance of Jackie Robinson as baseball's first black 
performer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Don Zimmer was one of a number of shortstops brought up to  
dislodge Reese. None ever did. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I played, if you came up as a shortstop, the starting  
shortstop wouldn't even talk to you,'' Zimmer said. ``When I got to 
Brooklyn, Pee Wee was like a father to me. That's the way it's been 
to this day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Reese's friendship with Robinson for which he will be  
most remembered. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pee Wee had a very simple nature,'' said former Brooklyn  
pitcher Carl Erskine, a teammate of Reese and Robinson for nine 
seasons. ``He saw things as they were. He was not going to be 
anyone's savior. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was just a southern boy who saw through (the bigotry). Pee  
Wee avoided ever taking a stand (publicly). He played a neutral 
role. He was a supporter (of Robinson) without being a crusader.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre grew up in Brooklyn rooting for the  
rival New York Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	``He managed me in a game when I was 16 and played a sandlot  
game at Ebbets Field,'' Torre said before Sunday's game with 
Minnesota. ``He told my brother, Frank, that I must really like the 
groceries because I was a fat kid. I got a double that game. I 
always respected him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reese was born on July 23, 1918, on a farm in Ekron, Ky., and  
moved to Louisville with his family as a child. He gained the 
nickname Pee Wee not because of his size -- he was listed at 
5-foot-10 and 160 pounds -- but from his prowess at marbles. A ``pee 
wee'' was a common type of marble. 
</P>
<P>
	All was quiet Sunday on Pee Wee Reese Road in east Louisville.  
No ribbons, flowers or other tributes placed on the street sign 
bearing his name leading into Seneca Park -- which most likely was 
the way Reese would have wanted it. 
</P>
<P>
	``As famous as he was, he was just a regular guy,'' said Mary  
Barney, director of baseball operations for Louisville's AAA 
baseball team. ``He really was just the man next door.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral services for Reese will be held Wednesday at Southeast  
Christian Church in Louisville. Visitation will be held from 2-4 
p.m. and 6-8 p.m. Tuesday at Pearson's Funeral Home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
