<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Venture Capital at All-Time High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There may be no better time than the present to  
be an entrepreneur in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Start-up companies received a record $7.7 billion in venture  
capital investments during the second quarter of 1999, nearly 
double the previous record of $4.3 billion set in the first 
quarter, according to the accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers. 
</P>
<P>
	The $12 billion that venture capitalists showered on  
entrepreneurs during the first six months of the year represents a 
62 percent increase over the same period a year ago, the firm said. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are the good old days,'' said Kirk Walden, national  
director of venture capital research for PricewaterhouseCoopers, 
which publishes the Money Tree Survey. ``Any entrepreneur with a 
technology idea and a good business plan should be able to get 
funding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the number of companies that received venture capital  
investments during the second quarter rose 30 percent to 992, up 
from 763 during the same three-month period a year earlier. And the 
average size of an investment rose 57 percent to $7.4 million, 
compared to $4.9 million in the second quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Walden said the striking increase in the amounts of money  
flowing from venture capitalists to start-up companies ``forces me 
to conclude that venture capitalism is now an integral part of the 
U.S. economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morever, Walden predicted that the broader distribution of  
investment dollars will ultimately result in increased innovation 
and productivity because technology will be allowed to move forward 
at a faster rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Venture capitalists raise money from a variety of investors and  
then re-invest the money in fledgling businesses. The venture 
capitalist firms generally receive low-cost stock in return for 
their investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Should the start-up company stay afloat and eventually complete  
a successful initial public offering of its stock, the shares 
become much more valuable and the venture capitalists see a huge 
return on their investment. 
</P>
<P>
	This formula has been particularly successful in recent years,  
as venture capitalists have helped numerous new Internet businesses 
survive until they can raise additional money through an IPO. 
</P>
<P>
	So experts said it's hardly a coincidence that start-up Internet  
companies received about half of the record second quarter bounty, 
or $3.8 billion. Overall, technology companies received $6.9 
billion in the second quarter, or 90 percent of the total amount 
distributed. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesse Reyes, managing director of Venture Economics, a Newark,  
N.J., firm that tracks venture capital trends, said large 
corporations have contributed to the surge in overall venture 
capital investing by jumping into the spending spree. ``It's the 
dot-com factor,'' he said. ``No one wants to be left out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, venture capital firms were the primary investors in  
start-up companies, and the firms did so for the sole purpose of 
reaping returns on their investments, Reyes explained. But large 
corporations are now getting into the act -- especially in the 
burgeoning online world -- for strategic rather than financial 
purposes, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Large telecommunications and cable companies, for example, have  
been pouring money into Internet start-ups to gain a stronger 
foothold on the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	PricewaterhouseCoopers' survey found that the investment  
largesse is finding its way across the country. Companies located 
in Silicon Valley attracted the most money during the 
record-breaking second quarter, receiving $2.7 billion. New 
England-based companies followed with $1.1 billion, and the New 
York metropolitan area, the Los Angeles/Orange County region and 
the Southeast each received more than $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	John Barry, a general partner with Prospect Street Ventures, a  
New York venture capital firm that invests in information 
technology companies, said Silicon Valley will likely remain the 
focal point for venture capital spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But other geographic regions are starting to attract more money  
as the large venture capital firms realize that Internet companies 
are sprouting up all over the country, Barry said, noting that 
one-third of the Internet companies that completed IPOs during the 
first six months of 1999 are located in the New York metropolitan 
area. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 12:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tough New Contract for SNL Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When he was TV's biggest star in the 1950s,  
Milton Berle happily signed a 30-year exclusive contract with NBC. 
He lived to regret it. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, NBC is handing potential stars that it signs for ``Saturday  
Night Live'' a contract that could tie them to the network for as 
long as 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	According to The New York Observer, first-year cast members must  
now sign a contract that not only retains the performer's services 
for five or six years, but can then transfer the player from 
``SNL'' to an NBC sitcom -- for a potential contract extension of as 
much as six more years. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract also contains a three-film option, giving NBC and  
``SNL'' executive producer Lorne Michaels the right to place the 
player in a movie they produce under the SNL Films banner for a 
lower fee than a competing studio might offer, the Observer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like `SNL' puts a gun to your head and says you're  
auditioning,'' complained one agent who represents a comic. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently the new strategy is NBC's way of holding onto the  
stars ``SNL'' creates, then often loses, going back to when John 
Belushi became a box office sensation with ``Animal House'' in the 
1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	It's also a way to lock in the services of emerging new talent  
for NBC prime-time at a time when the network's ratings dominance 
is no longer a sure thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Michaels nor NBC West Coast president Scott Sassa would  
comment on the contract. But in the Observer story, Sassa insisted 
the new terms were only fair. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody who comes in and is, basically, virtually unknown and  
young has an opportunity to be on a very, very powerful 
sketch-comedy show and to be able to launch a film career and be in 
sitcoms,'' he said. ``I think that's a pretty good opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michaels told The Observer ``the idea that the whole culture of  
the place is changing is just idiotic. ... We've been very, as they 
say in Hollywood, talent-friendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No new ``SNL'' players have been announced yet for the show's  
25th season, which begins Oct. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1951, NBC signed Berle to an unprecedented contract calling  
for $100,000 a year for 30 years -- whether he worked or not. But by 
1965, after Berle's star quality had faded, he got the network to 
let him work elsewhere, and Berle accepted a pay cut to $60,000 a 
year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 08:07:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher Monday  
on the back of last week's rally on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average jumped  
390.86 points, or 2.24 percent, to close at 17,826.03. On Friday, 
the average finished up 12.20 points, or 0.07 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	International blue-chip stocks in Tokyo posted strong gains in  
line with a surge in share prices in the United States last week. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 184.26  
points Friday to close at 10,973.65. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's big blue chip stocks often rise in tandem with Wall  
Street because they do much of their business in the United States 
and their fates are closely linked to those of U.S. companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 114.84 yen in  
late-afternoon trading, down 0.08 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and 
below its late New York level of 115.74 yen Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks rebounded strongly as fears eased of possible  
sharp increases in U.S. interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 286.60 points, or 2.3 percent, to close at 
12,894.78. On Friday, the index had slumped 171.57 points, or 1.3 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said prices surged in reaction to a U.S. Labor  
Department report on Friday that suggested that inflation in the 
United States remains in check, easing investors' fears of sharp 
interest rate increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hong Kong market was also boosted by Friday's sharp rally on  
Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Taiwan surged in reaction to last week's  
announcement that Morgan Stanley Capital International has decided 
to double Taiwan's weighting in its indexes beginning February 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taipei market's Weighted Stock Price Index rose 392.42  
points or 5.1 percent, to 8,018.47. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers said investors were still busy with asset reallocation  
following last Thursday's news that MSCI has raised Taiwan's 
weighting to 100 percent from 50 percent in its indexes effective 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher, buoyed by a  
strong futures market and Friday's strong gains on Wall Street. The 
All Ordinaries Index closed at 3017.9, up 59.1 points, or 2 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: The benchmark Straits Times Index rose 28.91 points,  
or 1.5 percent, to 1,998.59. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher, boosted by  
Friday's rally on Wall Street. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index 
rose 20.54 points, or 0.95 percent, to 2,186.55. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed mixed as gains spurred by Wall  
Street's advance were offset by profit-taking. The Philippine Stock 
Exchange index of 30 selected companies rose 4.31 points, or 0.2 
percent, to 2,175.30. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed lower on continued worries over  
rising local interest rates due to the Daewoo Group's financial 
woes. The main Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 10.19 points, 
or 1.1 percent, to 907.28. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed lower on  
profit-taking following Friday's sharp gains. The Composite Index, 
which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, fell 6.47 points, or 0.8 
percent, to 766.41. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesia share prices closed higher in thin trading.  
The key Composite Index rose 2.772 points, or 0.5 percent, to 
560.481. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed lower. The Stock Exchange of  
Thailand (SET) index fell 5.67 points, or 1.3 percent, to 418.11. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
