<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Gets Prison, Fine for Polluting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A man portrayed by prosecutors as an  
incorrigible polluter has been sentenced to 13 years in prison for 
releasing millions of gallons of contaminants. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Richard Lazzara on Monday also ordered  
62-year-old Gary Benkovitz to pay a $14,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Benkovitz's company, Bay Drum and Steel Inc., cleans and resells  
55-gallon drums for commercial use. He and the company were charged 
with releasing more than 4 million gallons of contaminated water 
and more than 636,350 pounds of sludge as a result of the 
drum-washing operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Benkovitz pleaded guilty in March to illegally disposing of  
hazardous waste and knowingly discharging pollutants. That plea 
came after he was awaiting sentencing on a guilty plea to similar 
1997 charges involving another of his facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's shown a total lack of remorse, and worse than that, he  
has continued to damage the community,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney 
Teri Donaldson told the judge last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Benkovitz's lawyers argued that there was no evidence that their  
client's actions put the public at risk. Most of the contaminants 
filtered into the city's sanitary system, not into open bodies of 
water, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
