<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agency: Nichols Defense Too Pricey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The head of the state agency that appoints  
public defenders told a judge Monday that the office does not have 
the money to adequately defend bombing conspirator Terry Nichols. 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature appropriated $1 million to the Oklahoma Indigent  
Defense System last year for Nichols' defense on state murder 
charges. Jim Bednar, the agency's executive director, has said 
defending Nichols could cost up to $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, however, the Legislature withdrew $900,000 of the funds  
in Nichols' case and reallocated it to help victims of tornadoes 
that killed 44 people and destroyed thousands of homes that month. 
An attempt to restore the funds failed during a special session in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	During a hearing on the agency's request to withdraw as Nichols'  
attorney, Bednar told Judge Robert M. Murphy Jr. that ``with the 
disapproval of that funding, we believe our appointment fails.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy responded that he has ``a hard time seeing'' the need to  
help tornado victims ``as a legitimate reason to withdraw the 
money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing was expected to last through the day and possibly  
continue on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols and Timothy McVeigh were convicted of federal charges in  
the April 19, 1995, bombing. McVeigh was sentenced to death for the 
bombing and the deaths of eight federal law enforcement officers. 
Nichols is serving life for conspiracy and involuntary manslaughter 
for those deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, Oklahoma County District Attorney Bob Macy filed 160  
murder charges against Nichols and said he will seek the death 
penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months later, the Legislature redirected the $900,000 to  
tornado victims and reappropriated $300,000 that had been promised 
to Macy's office for Nichols' prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Cal Hobson testified that the money was withdrawn  
because lawmakers deemed a state trial unnecessary, since Nichols 
already is serving life in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	But Murphy said it is not up to the Legislature to tell a  
prosecutor which cases to prosecute. 
</P>
<P>
	Macy opposes the agency's motion to withdraw from Nichols' case,  
saying the office has other resources it could use to pay for 
Nichols' defense. ``We are very concerned that he have competent 
counsel,'' Macy said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 17:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MCI WorldCom To Atone for Outage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom Inc., having restored its data  
network to full power over the weekend after 10 days of service 
disruptions, is now trying to restore confidence among the 
thousands of businesses thrown offline by the outages. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, one of the world's biggest operators of Internet  
``backbone'' networks, said Monday it would provide 20 days of free 
service to about 3,000 customers, including major names such as 
America Online Inc., as well as smaller Internet service providers 
and other businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear, however, whether that compensation would satisfy  
many clients who were unable to provide service to thousands of 
their own customers during the outages on one of four major MCI 
WorldCom networks. 
</P>
<P>
	The network began breaking down Aug. 5 after a software upgrade  
from Lucent Technologies, one of the three leading manufacturers of 
Internet and other networking equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	As various attempts to stabilize the network failed, the  
situation also became a public relations problem, similar to those 
faced recently by Internet brokers overwhelmed by huge trading 
volume or two years ago, when America Online couldn't handle floods 
of members trying a new unlimited usage plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``MCI WorldCom compounded the problem by the way they dealt with  
it,'' said Lisa Pierce, an industry analyst for Giga Information 
Group, asserting that ``the service credits they offered are an 
insult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bombarded by complaints it reacted too slowly and failed to keep  
customers updated, MCI WorldCom took the entire network out of 
service over the weekend to remove the new Lucent software. The old 
software was restored and the network was put back in service on 
Sunday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	A Lucent spokeswoman said the software in question has been  
deployed successfully on other networks and suggested that the 
problem was caused by the installation process rather than the 
software itself. 
</P>
<P>
	The outages disrupted ATM cash machine networks and affected  
organizations as prominent as the Chicago Board of Trade, whose 
electronic trading system was idled. The exchange issued an angry 
statement criticizing MCI WorldCom's handling of the situation and 
suggested it might take its business elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	There was only a marginal impact at AOL, since the online  
company uses a multitude of communications carriers and networks to 
serve its 17 million-plus members. 
</P>
<P>
	But some MCI WorldCom clients and their customers were hit much  
harder. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a trickle-down situation,'' said Rick Daniluk, a  
spokesman for Mountain Computer Wizards of Buena Vista, Colo., 
which provides dial-up Internet access for 1,500 customers as well 
as other Web and data services for businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to compensate our clients,'' said Daniluk,  
whose company's Internet traffic is carried by DX Net, an MCI 
WorldCom customer hit hard by the outages. ``We're going to go to 
DX Net for compensation. It amounts to more than our monthly fees 
we pay DX Net.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to Bernard J. Ebbers, MCI WorldCom president and chief  
executive, the refunds and compensation for lost network time will 
produce ``a very, very slight downtick in revenues,'' but the 
company is still comfortable with current Wall Street profit 
forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Ebbers also said no customers have indicated they will switch to  
a different data carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	But even if most data clients stay with MCI WorldCom, some might  
decide to at least send some of their business elsewhere as a 
precaution against relying too much on any one carrier and getting 
stuck in a similar situation. 
</P>
<P>
	``A surprising number of companies don't have a backup  
alternative in case there are emergencies,'' said Pierce, noting 
that most businesses use only one data carrier to get a volume 
discount. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a tradeoff between savings and safety, and I think  
some customers are going to look at that again,'' Pierce said. 
``Ebbers said he doesn't expect it to hurt the bottom line very 
much. I doubt that he's right. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of MCI WorldCom closed down 25 cents to $78.43 3/4 in  
trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
