<DOCNO> APW19990816.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 18:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins Say Underwood Off Waivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Jimmy Johnson hopes to persuade Dimitrius Underwood  
that there's room in his life for both religion and the Miami 
Dolphins. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, a first-round draft choice released last week by the  
Minnesota Vikings after he left them to pursue his faith, was 
claimed off waivers Monday by the Dolphins. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson acknowledged that the 22-year-old defensive end may not  
want to join the Dolphins -- at least not right away. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it so happens he doesn't play for the Dolphins this year,  
we'll retain his rights for the future,'' Johnson said. ``We're 
going to let him have some time to talk about the opportunity here. 
Then we'll be getting with him in the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one in the organization has talked to Underwood, Dolphins  
spokesman Harvey Greene said. Director of football operations Bob 
Ackles talked with Underwood's agent, Craig Domann, but details of 
the conversation weren't disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Domann didn't return a phone call seeking comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Underwood is Johnson's latest reclamation project, although the  
other cases are much different. The Dolphins' training camp roster 
includes three convicted felons and receiver Tony Martin, currently 
on trial on federal charges of laundering drug money. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami was awarded the rights to Underwood because no NFL team  
with a worse record last year claimed him. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dolphins assume his five-year, $5.3 million contract, but  
they're not responsible for his $1.75 million signing bonus. His 
base salary for 1999 is less than $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said the Dolphins studied Underwood extensively before  
the April draft. They decided against picking him in the first 
round, and he was instead taken with the 29th choice by Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a very talented defensive end,'' Johnson said.  
</P>
<P>
	Underwood went AWOL after his first practice with the Vikings on  
Aug. 2, leaving his family, his agent and team officials to 
speculate about his motive and whereabouts. He said last week he 
would rejoin the Vikings but instead was released after agreeing to 
return about $543,000 in bonus money, most of which was frozen at 
his bank when he disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood explained his absence by saying he was torn between a  
desire to pursue the ministry and the need to support his family, 
including his 16-month-old twins who live in Michigan with his 
former girlfriend. 
</P>
<P>
	He sought spiritual guidance from defensive end-turned-minister  
Reggie White, who retired from the Green Bay Packers last winter. 
White encouraged Underwood to return to football. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood sat out the 1998 season at Michigan State with a  
sprained ankle. He had eight sacks as a junior. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
