<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Aug. 16, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Columbine Students Return To School  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Students at Columbine High returned for  
the start of the school year today, four months after two gunmen 
sent them fleeing in horror. On April 20, students Dylan Klebold 
and Eric Harris killed 12 classmates and a teacher and wounded 23 
people before committing suicide. In classrooms today, teachers 
reminded students that counseling is available. Two mental health 
experts have been added to the staff. The Jefferson County School 
District spent $1.2 million to transform the inside of Columbine 
from a scene of carnage back into a place of learning. 

</P>
<P>
	Alexander Quits, But Doesn't Endorse  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lamar Alexander did not endorse any of his  
Republican rivals today as he announced he was abandoning his bid 
for the White House. But Alexander suggested Texas Gov. George W. 
Bush was inexperienced for the job of president. In Texas, Bush 
issued a statement calling Alexander ``a good man who poured his 
heart into his campaign.'' Bush is expected to pick up most of 
Alexander's fund-raising team. Alexander, the former Tennessee 
governor, was the first in a crowded Republican field to drop out 
after finishing sixth in Saturday's Iowa straw vote. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Pounds Rebel-Held Villages  
</P>
<P>
	BOTLIKH, Russia (AP) -- Russian fighter jets roared over the  
Caucasus region of Dagestan today, pressing ahead with a bombing 
campaign against Islamic militants holed up in several mountain 
villages. Still reluctant to launch a large ground offensive, 
Moscow was relying on air power and heavy artillery against the 
entrenched rebels. The fighting began Aug. 7, when rebels crossed 
from Chechnya into Dagestan and seized several villages. Meanwhile, 
ex-KGB agent Vladimir Putin won confirmation today as Russia's 
fifth prime minister since early last year. Putin told parliament 
he would crack down on Islamic militants in the Caucasus Mountains 

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Jewish Center Reopens  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Clowns and magicians were on hand today along  
with guards and police officers as children returned to the Jewish 
community center where a white supremacist went on a shooting 
rampage last week. Many of the youngsters arrived with bright green 
and purple hair for ``crazy hair day,'' aimed at creating an 
atmosphere of fun for the reopening of day camp at the North Valley 
Jewish Community Center. More than 160 children attended camp today 
and only five were absent. On Aug. 10, Buford O. Furrow Jr. 
allegedly fired 70 shots and wounded a 68-year-old receptionist, a 
16-year-old counselor and three boys. 

</P>
<P>
	HP's Quarterly Profits Rise  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Hewlett-Packard Co., pushing to  
revitalize itself with a recent split and a new chief executive, 
reported a 37 percent rise in quarterly profit that beat Wall 
Street forecasts. HP, the world's second largest computer company, 
said today it earned $853 million,in the fiscal third quarter, up 
from a profit of $621 million in the same period last year. In 
March, HP split into two separate ventures -- a computer and imaging 
business, and a testing and measurement business dubbed Agilent 
Technologies -- in an effort to revitalize underperforming divisions 
and improve sagging profits. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford To Test Hydrogen-Powered Engine  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. said today that  
researchers later this year plan to begin road-testing a 
hydrogen-powered internal combustion engine that promises up to 30 
percent better fuel efficiency. Fuel cells produce electricity from 
an electrochemical reaction between hydrogen and oxygen; the only 
emission is water. Automakers are spending hundreds of millions of 
dollars on fuel-cell research as government pressure for 
zero-emission vehicles increases, but few experts expect them to 
become commercially viable within the next decade. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 73.14; Nasdaq Up 7.47  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- While shares of the nation's major computer  
makers rose sharply, the broader stock market held to slim gains 
today, with investors making few bets while they awaited the 
government's consumer price report. The Dow Jones industrial 
average rose 73.14 to close at 11,046.79, the index's first close 
above 11,000 since July 21. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,553-1,425. The Nasdaq rose 7.47 to 
2,645.28. 

</P>
<P>
	Elliott Stable After Kidney Surgery  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- San Antonio Spurs star Sean Elliott was in  
stable condition today after undergoing a kidney transplant, 
receiving a healthy organ from his brother, Noel. Doctors have said 
it will take two to three months before they'll know whether 
Elliott could try to continue to play basketball, but he has said 
he hopes to return to the game. Elliott needed a transplant because 
of a condition that slows the kidneys, preventing them from 
properly filtering waste from the blood. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  



  	   	
</P>
