<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bubby Brister is the Denver Broncos starting quarterback but  
Brian Griese made a strong case for the job on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Griese, who played about half of Denver's 38-7 preseason rout of  
the Arizona Cardinals, completed 18 of 21 passes for 192 yards and 
two touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brian showed a lot of poise and made some good decisions,''  
said Broncos coach Mike Shanahan. ``He never seemed to get rattled. 
He was reading the break on his receivers and made a number of 
great throws.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona got its lone score late in the third quarter, closing to  
17-7 on Michael Pittman's 2-yard run. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Broncos responded with three fourth-quarter touchdowns --  
Griese's 13-yard pass to Byron Chamberlain, rookie Olandis Gary's 
1-yard run and cornerback Tito Paul's 67-yard interception return. 
</P>
<P>
	In other preseason games Saturday night, it was Tampa Bay 30,  
Cleveland 3; Green Bay 27, New York Jets 16; Buffalo 24, Seattle 
10; and Indianapolis 20, Cincinnati 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas played at Oakland and Tennessee was at Kansas City on  
Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Brister, rebounding from a lackluster performance in the  
Broncos' exhibition opener, was 8-of-10 for 93 yards. Terrell Davis 
left the game late in the first period after carrying six times for 
43 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-time defending Super Bowl champion Broncos dominated in  
almost every phase of the game, outgaining Arizona 448 yards to 
161. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know one phase of our football team that I was pleased  
with,'' Arizona coach Vince Tobin said. ``We were outplayed in 
almost every area. We stepped up in class to play the world 
champions, and we didn't meet force with force. I don't think I've 
ever seen a team beaten as consistently as we were on defense 
tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
                       *Buccaneers 30, Browns 3    	
</P>
<P>
	Trent Dilfer completed 7 of 10 passes for 122 yards, including a  
45-yard TD to Jacquez Green to lift Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Backups Eric Zeier and Shaun King each led two scoring drives as  
the Bucs outgained the Browns 386 yards to 58. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland No. 1 draft pick, Tim Couch, played like a rookie  
after an impressive debut in the Browns' victory over Dallas in the 
Hall of Fame game. In six series, he was unable to lead the team to 
a first down, finishing 5-of-12 passing for 27 yards. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Packers 27, Jets 16    	
</P>
<P>
	Matt Hasselbeck, a second-year quarterback who spent last season  
on the Green Bay's practice squad, threw two touchdown passes in 
the second half to lead the Packers. 
</P>
<P>
	Packers reserves earned the victory, but New York's starters  
outplayed Green Bay in the first half. The Green Bay offense was 
inconsistent under Brett Favre and Rick Mirer, while Jets 
quarterback Vinny Testaverde directed two sharp scoring drives. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Bills 24, Seahawks 10    	
</P>
<P>
	Manny Martin returned an interception 96 yards for a touchdown  
as Buffalo spoiled Mike Holmgren's debut as Seattle's coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo's third-string quarterback, Alex Van Pelt, hit Jeremy  
McDaniel for an 11-yard touchdown pass in the fourth quarter to put 
the game out of reach. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Colts 20, Bengals 17    	
</P>
<P>
	Peyton Manning was 12-of-16 for 137 yards, including a  
31-touchdown pass to Marvin Harrison, and the Colts won on a late 
26-yard field goal from Mike Vanderjagt. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanderjagt broke a 17-all tie with three seconds left in the  
game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts played without rookie running back Edgerrin James, who  
signed two days earlier and was watching from the sideline. 
Indianapolis managed just 34 yards on the ground without James. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Sunday's Games    	
</P>
<P>
                        *Raiders 10, Cowboys 3    	
</P>
<P>
	Backup quarterback Scott Dreisbach led Oakland for most of a  
10-play, 77-yard drive that led to the winning score before he 
broke his leg in the Raiders' win. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyrone Wheatley capped the drive with a 1-yard plunge with 35  
seconds remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Dreisbach was tackled while trying to get to the sideline on a  
bootleg with 1:45 left. He landed on his right leg at the Dallas 5, 
grimacing in pain before being taken off the field on a cart. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Chiefs 22, Titans 20    	
</P>
<P>
	Todd Collins, trying to hold his job as Kansas City's third  
quarterback, finished a long third-quarter drive with his second 
touchdown pass of the exhibition game as the Chiefs beat Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Elvis Grbac started for the Chiefs and was 7-of-10 for 73 yards.  
</P>
<P>
	Titans quarterback Steve McNair was 6-of-11 for 66 yards with an  
interception. Neil O'Donnell, who may unseat him as the starter, 
was 10-of-17 for 73 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie George rushed nine times for 53 yards for the Titans.  
  	   	
</P>
