<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbus, Ohio, Acts on Police Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The city has reached a tentative agreement  
with the U.S. Justice Department to resolve allegations of police 
abuse, possibly avoiding a federal civil rights lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	A Justice Department review of more than 300 complaints found  
that Columbus police officers engaged in a pattern of violations, 
including use of excessive force, false arrests and illegal 
searches. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement would be one of just a few in the country between  
a city and the Justice Department's Civil Rights Division, and is 
notable because the alleged pattern of misconduct is not 
race-related. 
</P>
<P>
	City officials on Monday said the proposed agreement, which  
includes a call for an independent monitor and increased training, 
needs approval from the Fraternal Order of Police because of union 
contract changes that would be required. The union expects to 
review it in the next 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, the Justice Department's Civil Rights Division told  
the city it was prepared to file a lawsuit, but would wait to see 
if the city took steps to correct the problems. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
