<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Considers Straw Poll a Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole had money on her mind  
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the average wage earner is working five months to pay the  
government, there's something wrong,'' she told workers at 
RealWorld Corp., an accounting software company. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just can't wait to get the IRS out of your pockets and out  
of your lives,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole promised to release a comprehensive tax reform plan this  
fall that she said would rein in the Internal Revenue Service and 
eliminate the marriage and federal estate taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	She also talked about her own finances.  
</P>
<P>
	Dole said she considers finishing third in the Iowa Straw Poll,  
behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush and publisher Steve Forbes, a 
victory because she spent only $250,000, while they spent millions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll demonstrate that the candidate with the most experience  
is more qualified than the candidates with the most money,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Dukes, 32, director of product management at RealWorld,  
said he thinks Dole can build the support she needs to close the 
gap with Bush. ``She's very straightforward,'' he said. ``She gives 
her position and doesn't put her finger up in the air before giving 
an opinion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, speaking to Manchester Rotarians at a local restaurant,  
Dole called for a strengthening of the country's schools and 
traditional values. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole said the key is to increase local control of schools, give  
teachers the power to remove troublemakers from their classes and 
involve parents in their children's education. 
</P>
<P>
	Debby Curran, who lives and teaches in Amherst, listened to Dole  
while waiting tables. She was impressed, but didn't think much of 
Dole's education platforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Curran said her parents are involved and she already has the  
authority to remove rowdy students. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
