<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lutherans To Vote on Church Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Leaders of the nation's largest Lutheran  
denomination vote this week on whether to form an alliance with the 
Episcopal Church that could mean fundamental changes in the way the 
Lutherans ordain their clergy. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the pact, the Episcopal Church and the Evangelical  
Lutheran Church in America would recognize and share each other's 
sacraments and clergy and cooperate in missionary projects. 
Together, they have about 7.5 million members. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike similar pacts the Lutheran group has with three other  
denominations, this agreement -- already supported by the Episcopal 
Church -- requires the Lutherans to follow an ordination practice 
known as the historic episcopate: Each bishop is installed by a 
laying on of hands by three predecessor bishops from a line 
believed to extend back to Christ's apostles. 
</P>
<P>
	That has raised opposition within the Lutheran ranks.  
</P>
<P>
	When the Lutheran delegates voted two years ago on a similar  
pact with the Episcopal Church, it was narrowly rejected. During 
the same convention, the delegates approved pacts with the 
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), Reformed Church in America and United 
Church of Christ -- none of which required changes in Lutheran 
tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	The Episcopal Church has said for over a century that its full  
recognition of other churches depends on their having the historic 
episcopate. 
</P>
<P>
	It has agreed to suspend the rule to recognize current Lutheran  
clergy. However, future Lutheran ordinations would have to be done 
the Episcopal way. 
</P>
<P>
	Lutheran teachings don't require such historic succession, and  
many of the world's Lutheran bodies do not practice it. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, 1,039 Lutheran convention delegates -- clergy and  
laity -- are expected to vote on the pact during a national 
convention that started Monday in Denver. If the Lutherans approve 
it, Episcopalians will act on it during their convention in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be very close,'' said H. George Anderson, the  
Lutherans' presiding bishop. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1997 vote was six votes shy of the two-thirds majority  
necessary for approval. But according to a tally by the Rev. 
Bradley Jenson of Duluth, Minn., nearly half of Lutherans voting at 
regional meetings earlier this year said they opposed the Episcopal 
pact. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Daniel W. Perry, the ecumenical officer for the  
Episcopalians, said the pact would help both denominations because 
they could share clergy and mission work in urban and rural areas 
where their resources are spread thin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 16:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
