<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 12:00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlin Prospect To Start Vs. L.A. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Florida Marlins top pitching prospect A.J. Burnett,  
who has struggled this season in the minor leagues, will make his 
major-league debut Tuesday against the Los Angeles Dodgers and then 
return to Double-A Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if he pitches a no-hitter, he's going back down,''  
Marlins manager John Boles said. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnett will fill in for Alex Fernandez, who will miss one start  
after receiving a cortisone shot in his pitching shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year-old Burnett is 6-11 with a 5.78 ERA at Portland,  
where he was demoted last week to the bullpen. But the Marlins say 
he has pitched better lately. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think he has a chance to pitch well,'' Marlins general  
manager Dave Dombrowski said. ``Maybe it will give him a shot in 
the arm. But there's nothing lost. I think he will handle it either 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burnett led the minor leagues with 186 strikeouts at Single-A  
Kane County last year and contended briefly this spring for a 
starting job with the Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	At Portland he has allowed 122 hits and 70 walks with 119  
strikeouts in 113 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know you ask, `Why is a guy who is having a bad year being  
rewarded?''' Boles said. ``But he is still a top prospect. Top 
prospects are a priority. We're calling him up just to see him. I 
hope it will light a fire under him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
