<DOCNO> APW19990816.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 03:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Paddy Devlin    	
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Paddy Devlin, a committed  
socialist who helped found Northern Ireland's largest Roman 
Catholic party, died Sunday after a lenghty hospitalization. He was 
74. 
</P>
<P>
	A tireless campaigner against sectarianism and violence, Devlin  
participated in Northern Ireland's first and only experiment in a 
joint Protestant-Catholic government. As minister for health and 
human services, he was the second highest ranking Catholic in that 
1974 administration. 
</P>
<P>
	That government soon collapsed, and the British government  
resumed ``direct rule'' from London, an arrangement that continues 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	As an idealistic member of the IRA, he served a three-year  
prison sentence starting in 1942 for membership in the group. He 
renounced violence in prison, and later became a fierce critic of 
the IRA campaign to destabilize Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, Devlin co-founded the moderate Social Democratic and  
Labor Party, which since has always won the most votes from the 
province's Catholic minority, but resigned in 1977 in protest that 
the party appealed too narrowly to Catholic interests at the 
expense of working-class Protestants. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981, Devlin was forced to abandon his home in his native  
Catholic west Belfast after facing intimidation from IRA 
supporters, who were angered by his criticism of the IRA prison 
hunger strike at the time. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Dezider Grunberger    	
</P>
<P>
	CRESSKILL, N.J. (AP) -- Dezider Grunberger, a cancer researcher  
and professor emeritus at Columbia University College of Physicians 
and Surgeons, died Aug. 7 of colon cancer. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of his research focused on chemical carcinogens. Grunberger  
helped develop antitumor drugs derived from propolis, a waxy 
substance bees collect from tree buds that has long been used as a 
folk remedy for various ailments. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunberger was born in Kosice, then part of Czechoslovakia,  
where he earned a master's degree in inorganic chemistry and 
doctoral degrees in biochemistry. 
</P>
<P>
	He settled in the United States in 1968 and eventually became a  
professor of biochemistry and biophysics and deputy director of 
Columbia's Comprehensive Cancer Center. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Frederick Hart    	
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Sculptor Frederick Hart, best known for the  
``Creation Sculptures'' at the National Cathedral in Washington, 
died Friday of pneumonia after suffering from lung cancer. He was 
in his mid-50s. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21-by-15 foot sculpture ``Ex Nihilo,'' a bas-relief work at  
the cathedral's main entrance, is considered Hart's masterwork. He 
completed the work of eight larger-than-life-size figures in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart also is known for the ``Three Soldiers'' bronze statue at  
the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart's work includes the bust of South Carolina Sen. Strom  
Thurmond for the U.S. Capitol and the statue of former President 
Jimmy Carter for the Georgia Capitol grounds. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Jack B. Jackson    	
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Jack B. Jackson, a former president of J.C. Penney  
Co., died Thursday at the age of 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson began working at the retailer while in college and rose  
through the ranks to become president in 1972. He retired in 1976 
after 38 years with the company. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a trustee of Austin College in his native Sherman and  
bred show horses at his ranch in Aubrey, Texas. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Robert Lee    	
</P>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Longtime Nebraska Associated Press newsman  
Robert Lee, 76, died Friday of renal failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee spent 36 years with the AP in Nebraska and retired in 1985.  
</P>
<P>
	His father, the late Herbert F. Lee, worked for United Press  
International before becoming a radio news writer in Omaha. 
</P>
<P>
	A brother, Bill Lee, is a retired managing editor of the Chico  
Enterprise-Record in California. Don Lee, another brother, is a 
retired sportswriter for the Omaha World-Herald. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee is survived by his wife, Philomena; sons, Garry, Kevin, Tom,  
Ron, Dan, and Dave; daughters Karen Kafka and Mary Beth Castle, 
both of Omaha; and brothers Bill, Don and Dale. Also surviving are 
20 grandchildren and one great-grandchild. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Lane Kirkland    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lane Kirkland, who reunited the major U.S.  
unions during his presidency of the AFL-CIO from 1979 to 1995, died 
Saturday of lung cancer. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton called Kirkland ``one of the towering figures  
in the American labor movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Born of southern aristocracy in Camden, S.C., and schooled in  
international relations at Georgetown University, Kirkland bucked 
the stereotypes of union leadership when he was elected AFL-CIO 
president in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	He appealed for reunification of the nation's largest and  
best-known unions under the AFL-CIO because, he said, ``all sinners 
belong in the church.'' By 1990 he had brought back the United Auto 
Workers, the Teamsters, the West Coast Longshoremen, Chemical 
Workers, Mine Workers and Locomotive Engineers. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO under Kirkland reached out to workers in other  
countries where the trade union movement was suppressed, including 
Poland, South Africa, China, Cuba and Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirkland was the heir to a long line of Southern cotton growers  
whose roots date back to the American Revolution. As a teen-ager, 
he enrolled in the U.S. Merchant Marine Academy and served as an 
officer during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Irena, five children, five  
grandchildren and two great-grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Jerome Kleinerman    	
</P>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Fla. (AP) -- Jerome Irving Kleinerman, a pathologist and  
lung specialist who did extensive research on coal miners and on 
the effects of tobacco smoke on lungs, died in an auto accident on 
Aug. 6. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Kleinerman, a former resident of Shaker Heights, Ohio, retired  
to Palm Beach Gardens fours years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	His research aided in the diagnosis of lung diseases for coal  
miners. He also helped develop national workplace health standards 
and drew attention to the need for health safeguards in mines and 
other industrial settings. 
</P>
<P>
	Kleinerman began in 1951 as a pathology researcher at Case  
Western Reserve University in Cleveland. He retired in 1995 as 
professor emeritus of pathology and environmental health sciences 
and chairman of the pathology department at the affiliated Metro 
Health Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	He was chairman of the pathology department at Mount Sinai  
School of Medicine in New York from 1978 to 1986, and was director 
of pathology at Mount Sinai Hospital. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Philip Klutznick    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Philip M. Klutznick, an innovative real estate  
developer, former secretary of the U.S. Commerce Department, 
philanthropist and Jewish activist, died Saturday. He was 92 and 
had suffered from Alzheimer's disease. 
</P>
<P>
	During World War II, President Franklin D. Roosevelt placed  
Klutznick in charge of building housing for defense workers in the 
nation's eastern half. He built Oak Ridge, Tenn., which played a 
major role in development of the atomic bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	He served as head of the federal Public Housing Authority, then  
moved to the Chicago area and developed suburbs and suburban 
shopping malls. 
</P>
<P>
	After anticipating the post-war exodus to the suburbs, Klutznick  
was one of the first developers to sense a new back-to-the-city 
mood in the 1970s. He moved back into Chicago with the completion 
of Water Tower Place, a 74-story shopping, office and residential 
complex on Chicago's Michigan Avenue. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is anything I have learned at all,'' he once said,  
``it is that everything is temporary in this world, and there isn't 
much difference between peoples.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Klutznick had close ties with Adlai E. Stevenson, the former  
Illinois governor and two-time Democratic presidential candidate. 
He also served as an envoy to the United Nations under presidents 
Dwight D. Eisenhower, John F. Kennedy and Jimmy Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	He served briefly as Secretary of Commerce under Carter.  
</P>
<P>
	He was president of B'nai B'rith from 1953 to 1959 and president  
of the World Jewish Congress in the late 1970s. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Altina Schinasi Miranda    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) -- Artist-filmmaker Altina Schinasi Miranda,  
a cigarette-roller heiress and avant-garde eyeglass designer, died 
Thursday. She was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Schinasi studied under George Grosz at the Art Students League  
of New York and designed window displays for Fifth Avenue 
department stores during the Depression. 
</P>
<P>
	Her Harlequin eyeglasses became fashionable after World War II  
and won the Lord and Taylor Annual American Design Award in 1939. 

</P>
<P>
                           *John S. Pingel    	
</P>
<P>
	PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. (AP) -- John S. Pingel, an All-America  
halfback at Michigan State in 1938 and member of the National 
Football Foundation Hall of Fame, died Saturday. He was 82 and had 
heart trouble for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	Pingel lived in Grosse Pointe Woods, Mich., and Juno Beach, Fla.  
The Michigan Sports Hall of Famer was best known as a halfback. He 
led the Spartans to their first bowl game, a 6-0 loss to Auburn in 
the Orange Bowl on Jan. 1, 1938. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a first-round draft pick of the Detroit Lions in 1939 and  
was with the team one season before World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	He served in the Army, rising to the rank of lieutenant colonel.  
He entered the advertising business after the war, becoming 
president of Ross Roy in 1962 and chief executive and vice chairman 
in 1980. He retired in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	President Gerald Ford, who played football at rival Michigan,  
appointed Pingel to the President's Council on Physical Fitness. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Pee Wee Reese    	
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Pee Wee Reese, the Hall of Fame shortstop  
and Brooklyn Dodgers captain who smoothed Jackie Robinson's entry 
into major league baseball as its first black player, died 
Saturday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Reese, who overcame prostate cancer years ago, underwent  
radiation treatment for lung cancer in March 1997 after doctors 
removed a malignant tumor. He also was recovering from a broken hip 
at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	An eight-time All-Star, Reese led the Dodgers to seven National  
League pennants and helped Brooklyn win its only World Series 
championship in 1955. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicknamed ``The Little Colonel,'' he batted .269 in a career  
that spanned 1940-58 and included the Dodgers' first year in Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	But his offensive career totals -- 126 home runs, 885 RBIs -- did  
not begin to measure the value of Harold Henry Reese to the 
Dodgers, or to baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Known for his calm leadership, sure-handed fielding and clutch  
hits, Reese played a key role in easing Robinson's road into the 
majors in 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	During one particularly tough time when the abuse was getting  
ugly at Crosley Field in Cincinnati, Reese walked over and put his 
arm over the rookie's shoulder, a show of unity from a white to a 
black that spoke volumes. 
</P>
<P>
	That moment is cited as a turning point in Robinson's  
transition. Later, Reese and Robinson would play golf and tennis 
together on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 1972 book ``The Boys of Summer,'' author Roger Kahn  
hailed Reese as a ``catalyst of baseball integration'' for his 
friendship with Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were times when I went over to talk to him on the field,  
thinking that people would see this and figure we were friends and 
this would help Jack,'' Reese told Kahn. 
</P>
<P>
	Reese was inducted into baseball's Hall of Fame in 1984.  
</P>
<P>
	After his baseball career, Reese worked as a broadcaster with  
CBS, NBC and the Cincinnati Reds. He later became director of the 
college and professional baseball staff at Hillerich &AMP; Bradsby, 
maker of Louisville Slugger bats. 

</P>
<P>
                          *George Robinson    	
</P>
<P>
	HAMMOND, Ind. (AP) -- George Robinson, the Rev. Jesse Jackson's  
half-brother, died of cancer Saturday at age 55. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, of Calumet City, Ill., grew up in Greenville, S.C.,  
moved to Chicago in 1976 and worked in restaurant management. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson praised Robinson for his activism in the Rainbow/Push  
Coalition, where he worked on voter registration drives. 
</P>
<P>
	``He never stopped fighting to make America better,'' Jackson  
said. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Celestine Sibley    	
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Celestine Sibley, the journalist and author of  
homespun columns on everything from gardening to politics, died 
Sunday. She was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Sibley was the author of 25 books, but she was best known  
for the folksy columns she wrote for The Atlanta 
Journal-Constitution for more than 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Her first newspaper job, while still in high school, was with  
The Mobile (Ala.) Press. She was a reporter with the Pensacola 
(Fla.) News Journal from 1936-41. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1941 she moved to Atlanta, where her journalist husband  
suggested she seek work with The Atlanta Journal or The Atlanta 
Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	She took a job at the Constitution for $35 a week, covering  
everything from murder trials to the state Legislature to the death 
of Margaret Mitchell, the author of ``Gone With The Wind.'' In 
1945, she began writing columns. 
</P>
<P>
	She is survived by two daughters, a son and nine grandchildren.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
