<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Site of L.A. Shooting Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Six-year-old Scott Pincus was a little  
worried about returning to the Jewish community center where a 
gunman shot five people, including his two best friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``First, he said the camp was bad. I told him it wasn't the camp  
that was bad, it was the person who did this,'' said his mother, 
Leslie Pincus. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid tight security Monday, more than 160 children returned to  
the North Valley Jewish Community Center for the first time since 
the Aug. 10 shooting. Only five were absent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullet holes were patched and the shattered glass replaced. The  
only evidence of the rampage -- memories of a ``monster'' who fired 
70 bullets in the center's lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	``To the best of our ability, there is no evidence of the  
carnage that occurred here last Tuesday. We're making it as normal 
as possible,'' said Jeffrey Rouss, executive vice president of the 
12 Jewish Community Centers of Greater Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged gunman, Buford O. Furrow Jr., was charged with  
murder and attempted murder after surrendering to the FBI in Las 
Vegas. After the rampage at the community center, police say Furrow 
shot and killed postal carrier Joseph Ileto a few miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of a ``monster,'' as the gunman is referred to by the  
children and staff, the youngsters were met Monday by a clown, a 
magician and a contingent of police and security. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him to have a good day and that I would be back to get  
him this afternoon,'' Mrs. Pincus said after dropping off her son 
at the center's day camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The sounds of children at play, screams and laughter, could be  
heard from the street. Many appeared in good spirits, smiling and 
waving at the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to day camp,'' 5-year-old Rachel Blaisch yelled out  
the window as she was driven to the center. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the children arrived with bright green and purple hair  
for ``crazy hair day,'' which was aimed at bringing an atmosphere 
of fun to the reopening. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten grief counselors from the Jewish Family Services were on  
hand to help children and parents cope with returning to the 
center, which is located in the middle-class suburban neighborhood 
of Granada Hills. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of like reclaiming their home for them,'' said Sally  
Weber of Jewish Family Services. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Jesse Jackson also paid a visit.  
</P>
<P>
	``We saw two children with casts on their legs who'd been shot.  
We saw rabbis praying with congregants. We saw parents hugging 
children,'' Jackson said. ``We saw a community turning pain into 
power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only shooting victim still hospitalized, 5-year-old Benjamin  
Kadish, was in serious condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
