<HEADLINE> Time Warner Names Ames Music Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner Inc. named Roger Ames as head of the  
media giant's Warner Music Group, filling the second half of a hole 
left when the two leaders of its movie, television and music 
division announced their resignations last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Ames, a member of the senior management group of Warner Music  
International, has an extensive background in the music industry, 
dating back to 1975. He joined Warner Music International in April, 
after leaving The PolyGram Music Group, where he had served as 
president since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Ames is taking over some of the responsibilities held by  
departing chiefs Terry Semel and Bob Daly, who worked together 
running Warner Music Group and the company's studio operations. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 2, Time Warner announced that Barry Meyer had been  
selected to run the studio operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roger Ames has the perfect blend of artistic sensitivity,  
executive know-how and financial understanding to run Warner Music 
Group. He's worked in the United States and abroad, as both an 
entrepreneur and within a corporate setting, and won the respect of 
colleagues and competitors alike,'' Time Warner chairman Gerald 
Levin said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Ames will begin his new post Oct. 4 and report to Time Warner  
president Richard Parsons. 
</P>
<P>
	Entertainment industry analysts said the timing of the  
appointments was a coincidence and not a sign that the company is 
in the midst of any significant changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very complicated and well-run company,'' said Marvin  
Roffman, president of Roffman Miller Associates, a Philadelphia 
money management firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides, he said, ``it's musical chairs when it comes to  
management changes'' at large corporations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
