<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Adviser: Dolphins' Martin Warned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Miami Dolphins receiver Tony Martin ignored a  
warning from his father to stay away from a longtime friend who had 
narcotics ties, saying it was none of his business, Martin's former 
financial adviser testified Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Norton, a San Diego-based financial planner, said he was at  
Martin's Southern California home when Hal Martin tried to warn his 
son. The elder Martin said he didn't think his son should associate 
with Rickey Brownlee, Norton testified. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know that drugs specifically came up,'' he said. ``But  
the implication was that Rickey Brownlee was a drug dealer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what Martin's response was, Norton said: ``That he  
basically didn't care what he did for a living.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin is being tried alongside Brownlee, a previously convicted  
drug dealer, in a case largely focusing on Brownlee's alleged drug 
activities from 1995-97. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin is charged with five counts of money laundering. He is  
accused of leasing three cars in his name on behalf of Brownlee, 
who paid him back with cash. Martin also is accused of writing a 
check to Brownlee's first lawyer in exchange for cash. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is whether Martin, who has known Brownlee since  
childhood and calls him his uncle, knew he was accepting drug 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Norton testified that Martin, despite earning millions from  
playing professional football, has been heavily in debt since they 
first met while Martin was playing for the San Diego Chargers. 
Norton himself loaned Martin more than $100,000 during their 
relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	And yet, he said, Martin paid some $29,000 in cash to lease a  
Mercedes 500 SL for Brownlee in May 1996. Norton, who was 
responsible for paying Martin's bills, said he didn't learn of the 
deal until hearing from a leasing agent about an overdue payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Another time, he said, Martin called and ordered him to write a  
check to Brownlee for $46,673.05, saying the money would be 
reimbursed within a day or two. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of what had been portrayed as Rickey Brownlee's  
occupation, I was worried that would be money laundering,'' Norton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin later called to say the money wasn't needed, and the  
check was voided, Norton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys, pointing to a memo in which Norton voiced his  
objection to a recording studio deal that later failed, asked 
Norton if he ever told Martin he disapproved of his friendship with 
Brownlee. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's more of an internal matter,'' Norton said. ``Writing  
him a letter to that effect, I didn't think that was my 
discretion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors also played a March 1998 tape Norton made of a phone  
conversation with Martin, in which the player said he needed a 
$100,000 check to pay a lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm writing a check for this lawyer, but I'm going to send  
cash to you so you can put it in the account,'' Martin said on the 
tape. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin called the next day to say he had $175,000 in cash,  
Norton testified, and that he was going to fly to California to 
deliver it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in shock,'' Norton said. ``I said, `I hope you don't get  
mugged.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say Martin stopped payment on the check after  
federal investigators subpoenaed his financial records. He repaid 
Brownlee with two cashier's checks, an IRS agent testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Brownlee spent seven years in prison for 1980s drug convictions.  
Known on the streets as ``the Mayor of Opa-locka,'' he is charged 
with five counts of possessing heroin or cocaine with the intent to 
distribute, and one count of conspiracy to possess and distribute. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers spent the afternoon hammering at Norton's  
credibility. Martin attorney Howard Srebnick outlined a series of 
checks worth $137,500 from Martin's account to Norton or his firm 
that made no mention of why they were written. 
</P>
<P>
	Srebnick also questioned two agreements Martin signed in which  
Norton's description of the deal differed from what was in writing. 
One stipulated Norton would receive a $350 hourly fee in addition 
to 10 percent of Martin's earnings. Norton testified he charged 
only the 10 percent commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The other was an agreement that used Martin's home as collateral  
on a loan. The document said Martin would receive $330,000 in the 
deal, but Norton testified that it was for money previously loaned. 
</P>
<P>
	``You had Tony sign a deal that didn't reflect the agreement,''  
Srebnick said. ``It makes no sense in this transaction. It only 
does if you're around to explain it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norton has been investigated by California's attorney general  
and is a central figure in at least two other business 
controversies there. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
