<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Teams With EMusic.com </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DULLES, Va. (AP) -- America Online Inc. has reached a three-year  
deal with Internet music service EMusic.com that will allow online 
visitors to buy and download music from three Web sites owned by 
AOL. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, EMusic's 20,000-song collection will be  
available on AOL's Spinner.com and Winamp.com, as well as ICQ.com, 
a chat service. EMusic will develop co-branded sites for the three 
services, selling music in the MP3 format. 
</P>
<P>
	EMusic, based in Redwood City, Calif., will pay AOL a fixed  
marketing fee and a share of transaction revenue. The company sells 
albums for $8.99 and individual songs for 99 cents. The company's 
catalog includes alternative, blues, hip-hop, jazz, pop, punk, 
techno and Indie rock music. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, AOL acquired Spinner.com, the Internet's  
largest music service, and Nullsoft, which makes the music player 
Winamp, in a deal worth $400 million in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL, based in Dulles, Va., is a leading Internet provider with  
more than 17 million members. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of EMusic soared on news of the deal, rising $2.62 1/2 to  
$17.75 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Shares of AOL were trading at 
$96.12 1/2, down 75 cents, on the New York Stock Exchange. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
