<HEADLINE> Waste Management Ousts No. 2 Exec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Waste Management Inc. has ousted its No. 2  
executive as part of a companywide overhaul designed to get the big 
trash hauler's ailing business back on track. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also acknowledged in a filing Monday with the  
Securities and Exchange Commission that the SEC and the New York 
Stock Exchange are conducting inquiries into insider sales of the 
company's stock prior to an earnings warning it issued on July 6. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the filing, Waste Management said that $30.2 million  
was incorrectly reported as operating income for the quarter ending 
March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Including charges, earnings for the three months ended March 31  
were revised to $346.7 million, or $0.55 per diluted share, 
compared to $364.3 million, or $0.58 as originally reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's almost as if we had taken a two year-detour,'' said Hugh  
Holman, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens. ``The issues 
they are dealing with today are very similar to the same issues the 
old Waste Management was grappling with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the problems the first incarnation of Waste Management  
had involved lax internal controls and overly optimistic 
accounting. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of its management reorganization, Waste Management said  
it was replacing its chairman and chief executive officer, John 
Drury, who has been on medical leave for several months. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodney Proto will leave his job as president and chief operating  
officer and give up his seat on the board of directors, though 
Drury will retain his seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph Whitworth will move from acting chairman to chairman and  
Steve Miller to president and acting chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, a member of the Waste Management board, was chairman and  
CEO of the former Waste Management before last year's merger with 
USA Waste Services. Miller will remain CEO until a permanent 
replacement is hired, and the company also is looking for a chief 
financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The board's actions come in the wake of disappointing earnings  
and inaccurate forecasts, as well as challenges in integrating 
operations after Waste Management combined with Houston-based USA 
Waste Services for $13.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 6, the company warned that second-quarter earnings would  
be hurt by a decline in trash collection revenue. Earlier this 
month, the Oak Brook, Ill.-based Waste Management issued a second 
warning that revised accounting procedures and even worse revenue 
than first thought would further depress earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	In its SEC filing, Waste Management said both the quarterly  
earnings and the insider stock sales were being scrutinized by the 
SEC. It also said the NYSE's Market Trading Analysis Department was 
reviewing the stock transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, at least three class-action lawsuits have resulted  
from the trades. 
</P>
<P>
	Waste Management has previously acknowledged that some top  
officials sold shares in the months before the earnings warning. 
However, the company defended the timing, saying that for many of 
the officials, it was their first opportunity to sell stock in 
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Whitworth said the company will dispose of its  
non-strategic and underperforming businesses, including some or all 
of the company's international operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``My highest priority over the coming weeks and months will be  
to ensure the prompt and orderly execution of the board's strategic 
plan,'' Whitworth said. ``We realize that we must deliver results 
before we will see meaningful increases in our share price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts generally applauded the divestiture of international  
operations as a good streamlining move. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a time for them to retreat to the fortress and manage  
the very strong asset base they have in North America,'' Holman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Waste Management were down 62 1/2 cents to $23 in late  
afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
