<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another Ex-Steeler Joins Jaguars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Like so many ex-Steelers before him,  
fullback Tim Lester comes to a new team looking for a fresh start. 
</P>
<P>
	He signed a one-year deal with Pittsburgh's AFC Central rivals,  
the Jacksonville Jaguars, giving him two chances this season to 
show the Steelers exactly what they gave up. 
</P>
<P>
	Lester was the fullback credited with opening up so many big  
holes for Jerome Bettis over the last three years. Bettis 
complained loudly when the Steelers chose to sign untested Jon 
Witman and let Bettis' good friend enter the free-agent market. 
</P>
<P>
	They both should have expected it.  
</P>
<P>
	The Steelers are notorious for letting top free agents get away.  
Lester is the third player, joining Carnell Lake and Deon Figures, 
to leave Pittsburgh for Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really have nothing good to say about them,'' Lester said of  
the Steelers. ``I don't really want to talk about it. But I know a 
lot of guys feel the same way I do. A lot of guys have gone 
elsewhere and have done real well. I hope I can do the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lester said he appreciated Bettis' support, but knew the  
situation was out of both of their hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had been together five, six years playing and we became  
very good friends,'' Lester said. ``I guess he had to voice his 
opinion. I heard a lot of people got frustrated about him speaking 
out, but I know in the relationship we built over the years, it was 
something he felt he had to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jaguars seemed solid at the position with third-year veteran  
Daimon Shelton, but were lacking depth after rookie Trevor Bollers 
was lost to a knee injury last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no big secret, everybody thinks this could be the year  
for this team,'' said running back Fred Taylor, who rushed for 
1,223 yards behind Shelton's blocking last year. ``It's time to go 
ahead and get all your weapons and use all of them. Just go after 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lester, a seven-year veteran out of Eastern Kentucky, survived a  
long wait on the free-agent market before signing the deal that 
will pay him $500,000. He missed six games last season with 
injuries to his rotator cuff and knee. 
</P>
<P>
	His stock clearly diminished because of the injuries, but he  
doesn't think it will stop him from competing for a starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's how I'm going to approach it,'' he said. ``I've never  
been a backup. I'm going to approach it like I'm going to get a 
starting job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coughlin said he liked that attitude, but didn't consider the  
signing an indictment of Shelton. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had three fullbacks, we lost one fullback, we needed to  
bring one in, so we brought in the best one available,'' Coughlin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tight end Kyle Brady, the other key free-agent addition to the  
Jaguars offense, said whatever Lester's role, it's bound to help 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suppose coaches at this level are sort of like mechanics on  
the NASCAR circuit,'' Brady said. ``In all respects, they're always 
doing some tuning, trying to get it to the specifications they 
want.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
