<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Site of L.A. Shooting Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Children were greeted with hugs, love and  
performing clowns today as they returned to the Jewish community 
center that was a place of terror just six days earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	It was ``Funny Hair Day'' to let the youngsters forget -- and  
extra security to reassure their parents -- at the reopening of the 
North Valley Jewish Community Center, where an invader wounded 
three small children, a teen and one adult on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the attack, bullet holes have been filled and shattered  
glass replaced, to make the scene as normal as possible, and grief 
counselors were being brought in. 
</P>
<P>
	``My dad always said when you fall off your bike get right back  
on it,'' said Jeffrey L. Rouss, executive vice president of the 12 
Jewish Community Centers of Greater Los Angeles. ``We are sending a 
message that evil will be vanquished. We are not going to let a 
monster like that stop us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least 128 children showed up today for the center's day camp,  
just a shade below the normal Monday turnout of 130. Thirty-seven 
children came for preschool, where 40 is the usual number for a 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Gottlieb dropped off his 4-year-old daughter, Amanda.  
</P>
<P>
	``She seems a little apprehensive. She was 20 feet from the  
bullets,'' Gottlieb said. ``I told her to have a good day, that 
mommy was going to stay with her for a little while and I would 
pick her up later today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buford O. Furrow Jr. was charged with murder and attempted  
murder for allegedly wounding five people inside the center, then 
killing postal carrier Joseph Ileto a few miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	Five-year-old Benjamin Kadish, the only victim still  
hospitalized, was in serious condition at Childrens Hospital Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Furrow, who has ties to hate groups and a history of mental  
illness, turned himself in on Wednesday after fleeing to Las Vegas. 
Police found a small arsenal of weapons and ammunition in the 
vehicles Furrow is believed to have used to get to and from the 
attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The center opened shortly after dawn today and parents began  
arriving about 7:30 a.m. with their children. Five police squad 
cars were stationed at the school and uniformed security officers 
stood guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Rouss said the children were greeted inside with ``just hugs and  
love.'' Flowers, balloons, candles and banners were positioned 
outside the iron gate entrance. One of the signs read, ``We will 
overcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We've beefed up security at every JCC site, and it's visibly  
beefed up,'' Rouss told the throng of reporters gathered outside 
the center. Reporters were not allowed inside the school. 
</P>
<P>
	Lesley Pincus dropped off her 6-year-old son, Scott, and said  
the boy was eager about returning. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's fine and I'm fine. The kids, I think, really felt loved  
and special,'' she said. When asked about the heavy security, she 
said, ``It has been a wake-up call for all of us to take extra 
steps to protect ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At nearby California State University, Northridge, on Sunday,  
Gov. Gray Davis, Attorney General Janet Reno and religious leaders 
spoke during a community ``unity rally'' to honor the people who 
saved lives during the rampage. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, a pair of hecklers shouted down Davis when he  
vowed to take assault weapons off the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Second Amendment is just as important,'' yelled Irv Rubin  
of the Jewish Defense League, referring to the right to bear arms. 
Last weekend Rubin and thousands of others successfully blocked a 
parade in the nation's capital by white supremacists, including 
Aryan Nations members. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis responded to the hecklers by saying that, as a Vietnam War  
veteran, he knows the destructive power of assault weapons. ``They 
have a place in a theater of war,'' he said, ``but they have no 
place in a civilized society.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Parris Moskowitz, the center's president, thanked police,  
paramedics and hospital workers who helped at the shooting. After 
the rally, about 300 individuals received a certificate 
acknowledging their service and stating that a ``Unity Garden'' 
would be created in their honor at the center. 
</P>
<P>
	About 25 members of Unitarian Universalist Church in Canoga Park  
came to the rally to let their Jewish friends and neighbors know 
that the violence that struck their region won't be tolerated, said 
Gail Geisenhainer, the church's minister. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
