<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander Quits Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lamar Alexander ended his dogged six-year  
pursuit of the White House on Monday, saying ``there's really no 
realistic way to keep going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Quayle, who finished yet two places behind Alexander's  
meager sixth-place showing in the Iowa straw vote, suffered the 
defection of his South Carolina leadership to rival John McCain. 
Quayle aides said he is now reorganizing to concentrate ``almost 
all paid staff'' in just Iowa and New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander, the former Tennessee governor, was the first in a  
crowded Republican field to drop out after the weekend's nonbinding 
vote confirmed the Texas governor as front-runner. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a powerful force for George W. Bush's nomination in  
this country, and I saw it in Iowa last weekend,'' said Alexander, 
flanked by his wife and children at the Tennessee state Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	His all-out drive to prove himself an improved contender since  
losing to Bob Dole in 1996, ended with an unmatched -- and lonely -- 
21-day blitz through Iowa before the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Alexander faced a crowd of news cameras with  
bittersweet humor: ``I seem to be attracting more attention getting 
out than I did getting in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He gave no endorsement to any of his surviving rivals, but  
sounded his refrain suggesting Bush is inexperienced for the job of 
president. Alexander said he feared Republicans might discover 
``during a debate with Albert Gore Jr. that we've nominated someone 
who is not ready to be president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, Bush issued a statement calling Alexander ``a good man  
who poured his heart into his campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush is expected to pick up most of Alexander's fund-raising  
team and perhaps his top adviser in Iowa, former Gov. Terry 
Branstad, who has been courted by Michigan Gov. John Engler, a top 
Bush operative. 
</P>
<P>
	Over in Quayle's camp, described as despondent after the former  
vice president was bested in Iowa by little-known radio host Alan 
Keyes, aides insisted the struggling Quayle was in the race to 
stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rats may be jumping off the ship, but the ship isn't  
sinking,'' said Quayle press secretary Jonathan Baron. 
</P>
<P>
	National chairman Kyle McSlarrow cast the loss of campaign  
leaders in South Carolina, the state whose Feb. 19 primary makes it 
a critical gateway to the South, as part of a strategic 
reorganization that would now focus on next winter's leadoff 
nominating contests in Iowa and New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	The scramble to reorganize, despite the brave talk, came as  
aides privately worried Quayle might not be able to turn his 
fortunes around. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle's South Carolina campaign director, Jim Merrill, led the  
desertion of four organizers to McCain, who refused to compete in 
the Iowa straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	In his resignation letter, Merrill said his job had become a  
full-time fund-raising position. With a candidate in eighth place, 
``it has become apparent that the resources necessary to wage a 
successful campaign will not be forthcoming,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed McMullen, president of a South Carolina conservative think  
tank, wrote Quayle: ``We are losing elected officials and core 
conservatives who believe that your candidacy would be the winning 
team for conservative ideas.'' McMullen's resignation letter was 
released by the McCain campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan, a repeat Republican contender, also faces tough  
choices. 
</P>
<P>
	He placed behind Gary Bauer, his main rival for the social  
conservative vote, and now must decide whether to push forward, 
give up his third presidential bid, or start fresh with the Reform 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said Buchanan had not decided on a tack and plans  
were in the works for routine campaign events this week and next. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Buchanan was in the race to stay, spokesman Bob Adams  
said Monday: ``I'm booking radio ads, while we speak, in New 
Hampshire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in the GOP field, a contented Steve Forbes, who  
finished second in Iowa to Bush, took the week off for time with 
his family before his daughters head back to school. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning in New Hampshire, Elizabeth Dole cast her  
third-place finish as a victory earned, not bought, and said she 
hoped to attract Alexander supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time, she put a price tag on her efforts leading  
up to the pay-per-vote straw poll -- $250,000, less than a third of 
what Bush spent. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that you need to spend gobs of money'' to win,  
Dole told about 50 workers at RealWorld Corporation, a software 
company in Manchester. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll demonstrate that the candidate with the most experience  
is more qualified than the candidates with the most money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, the late-entry dark horse, expressed  
sympathy for Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a really fine fellow. I feel sorry he couldn't make it,''  
Hatch said as he campaigned in Merrimack, N.H. ``I didn't think he 
could make it, but I look at the rest of them, and I don't feel a 
lot of the rest of them can make it either.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
