<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Are Little Changed / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices were little changed Monday ahead of  
Tuesday's inflation report, which could determine whether the 
Federal Reserves will need to raise interest rates for a second 
time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 3/16 point, or  
$1.87 1/2 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, fell to 6.08 percent from 6.10 percent on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer price index, due out Tuesday, is the last major  
economic data release before Fed policy-makers meet next week to 
decide whether to raise short-term interest rates to cool off the 
economy. Few traders were willing to take large positions ahead of 
the data. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader secondary market, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities were unchanged, and intermediate maturities ranged from 
unchanged to 1/16 point higher, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.82 percent with a  
discount of 4.69 percent, up 0.07 percentage point from late 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields were 5.09 percent while the discount was 4.80  
percent, up 0.03 percentage point from late Friday. One-year yields 
were 5.19 percent with a discount of 4.94 percent, up 0.04 
percentage point from late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.19 percent from 5.06 late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 7/8 to 112 5/8. The average yield to 
maturity was 5.88 percent up from 5.82 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
