<DOCNO> APW19990816.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 22:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Automatic Lawn Mower Does Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Imagine mowing the lawn in your sleep. Or while  
you golf. 
</P>
<P>
	The ultimate lazy person's lawnmower -- a 15-pound race  
car-shaped contraption that does the job automatically -- should be 
available in the United States early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swedish-built Auto Mower, which will come in  
battery-operated and solar-powered models, is a hit at this year's 
National Hardware Show, drawing crowds who want a peek at what some 
hope is the hands-free future of lawn care. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody wants to work, so it will sell,'' said Bart  
Colenbrander of Toronto, who left his exhibitor booth for a look at 
the mower. ``I've wondered why anyone wasn't making something like 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Auto Mower manufacturer Husqvarna promises a near-hassle  
free lawn mowing system -- no fumes, no grass clippings to clean up. 
</P>
<P>
	A 20-volt wire around the boundary of the yard tells the mower  
where to cut and prevents it from wandering into flower beds or 
neighbors' yards. 
</P>
<P>
	And because it cuts a fraction of the blade at a time -- but does  
it more often -- the mower leaves no lines on the lawn, product 
manager Denis Bedard said. 
</P>
<P>
	When its 12-volt battery runs low, the mower finds its  
recharging station, juices up and goes back to work, stopping only 
when its preset mowing time is up. It can mow 1,000 square feet per 
hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do you care if it takes one hour or 10 hours -- you don't  
have to man it,'' Bedard said. ``In today's environment, we want to 
spend less time on the lawn and more time with the kids and 
recreational activities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $1,500 to $1,800 mower -- it comes with its own burglar alarm  
and security code -- will be targeted to middle- and upper-income 
buyers, Bedard said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Steve DePaepe, whose family has owned Chicago Lawn Mower for  
39 years, said he doubts the mower's selling potential because 
mowers and lawn services are more affordable than ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are looking for cheaper and cheaper products,'' he  
said. ``We've seen a shift from the average consumer buying a 
quality piece to buying an el cheapo. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of our competitors folded because the industry's changed  
so much.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 15:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Venator To Exit Noncore Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Venator Group Inc. moved closer to becoming  
primarily a sporting goods retailer with its announcement Monday to 
sell or close eight of its noncore businesses, totaling more than 
500 stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based company, formerly known as Woolworth, also  
said that its president, Dale Hilpert, was named chief executive 
officer. He will replace Roger Farah, who will remain Venator's 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the latest step in the restructuring of Venator,''  
said John Shanley, an analyst at First Security Van Kasper. ``It's 
a smart move to get rid of those stores that don't have growth 
potential and have limited earnings capabilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a tough few years for Venator, which has attempted to  
boost profits by reducing costs and closing more than 4,000 stores 
-- including all of its Woolworth five-and-dime and Kinney Shoe 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Venator lost $113 million, or $1 a share, compared  
with a loss of $10 million, or 7 cents a share, the year before. 
Sales fell to $4.56 billion, from $4.6 billion. It stock is trading 
at about $10, compared to more than $28 two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Venator is now mostly a sporting goods company, with 6,000  
stores, including the Foot Locker and Champs Sports chains. It also 
operates the Northern Group of apparel stores and the accessories 
chain Afterthoughts. 
</P>
<P>
	Venator said the businesses it will now exit include San  
Francisco Music Box, Randy River, Foot Locker Outlets, Colorado 
U.S., Team Edition, Going to the Game, Weekend Edition and some 
Burger King franchises. 
</P>
<P>
	These businesses had sales of $97 million and incurred a pretax  
operating loss of about $26 million for the six months ended July 
31. 
</P>
<P>
	``We anticipated that they would get out of these businesses,  
but we think the timetable was accelerated by the losses that the 
eight businesses had been collecting this year,'' Shanley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Venator will sell up to 51 of its 87 Weekend Edition women's  
apparel stores in Canada to YM Inc., a Toronto-based retailer. 
Details of the transaction were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Venator spokesman Juris Pagrabs said the company will try to  
sell the other seven businesses. If it doesn't find buyers, then 
Venator will consider closing the remaining stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The restructuring charge and operating losses are expected to be  
about $48 million, most of which will be recorded in the three 
months ended July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding the restructuring costs, Venator expects its  
second-quarter earnings to be between 3 cents and 5 cents a share, 
above forecasts of 2 cents a share by Wall Street analysts. Results 
will be announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Venator's shares rose $1.12 1/2 to $10 in trading on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``The business seems to be improving and now they will get rid  
of all of these businesses that were a distraction,'' said Alfred 
Kingsley, senior managing director at Greenway Partners, which owns 
14 percent stake in Venator and has been a vocal critic of 
Venator's slow turnaround. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilpert, who will retain the president's title, had been serving  
as chief operating officer, a position that the company has no 
present plans to fill. He joined Venator in 1995 after serving as 
chairman and CEO of Payless Shoe Source. 
</P>
<P>
	Farah, who has been chairman and CEO since 1994, was formerly  
president and chief operating officer at R.H. Macy &AMP; Co. Farah 
recently extended his contract with Venator through 2003, but 
analysts question if he will stay with the company until his 
contract expires. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
