<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Faces Prison in Vaccine Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) -- A military judge ruled Monday  
that a sailor who refused to take an anthrax vaccine cannot submit 
evidence about the vaccine's safety during his court-martial. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Raymond Kreichelt also ruled during the preliminary  
hearing that the military order requiring Airman Zachary Johnson to 
take the vaccine was legal. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 22, is charged with willfully disobeying a direct order  
and failing to obey a lawful regulation. If convicted, he faces up 
to six months in prison, loss of pay, reduction in rank and a bad 
conduct discharge. 
</P>
<P>
	His court-martial was scheduled to start Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Kreichelt told defense attorneys they could not offer evidence  
linking the anthrax vaccine to Gulf War syndrome or call an expert 
to testify on the vaccine's safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor, Lt. Christopher Ludmer, had argued that medical  
evidence was irrelevant to the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The anthrax vaccine is being given to all 2.4 million members of  
the armed services to protect against biological warfare. The 
Pentagon said that of the 900,000 personnel vaccinated so far, more 
than 79 reported adverse effects, such as rashes, headaches and 
fever, but all recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 military personnel have refused to take the six-shot  
immunization, but Johnson is the first sailor to face a 
court-martial. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a Marine helicopter crew chief was sentenced to 30  
days in confinement and issued a bad conduct discharge for his 
refusal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
