<DOCNO> APW19990816.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 10:47:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US, SKorea Military Exercises Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The United States and South Korea  
kicked off a 12-day joint military exercise Monday amid growing 
tensions with North Korea and fears that the communist country may 
test-fire a new long-range missile. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea denounced the exercise as a rehearsal for war on the  
Korean peninsula, warning that it will hurt relations with the 
South and adversely affect talks under way between Pyongyang and 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and South Korea hold several joint military  
exercises each year, routinely prompting criticism from North 
Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Ferguson, spokeswoman of the U.S. military command in Seoul,  
rejected the North Korean accusations and said the 25th annual 
drill is ``no more than a routine, defensive training exercise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean President Kim Dae-jung said his country and the  
United States should maintain a strong defense to cope with growing 
North Korean military threats, including a missile launch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Through this exercise, we must let North Koreans know that our  
military posture is firm and strong ever,'' Kim said. 
</P>
<P>
	The exercise is one of the largest conducted annually by the  
U.S. and South Korean armed forces. It mostly involves computer 
simulations designed to evaluate and improve joint contingency 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The training involves 14,000 U.S. soldiers stationed in South  
Korea and 5,400 others brought from the U.S. mainland, Japan and 
Guam, along with 56,000 South Korean troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Ridge, the flagship of the U.S. 7th Fleet, will lead an  
unspecified number of warships during the exercise. The Blue Ridge 
is normally based in Yokosuka, Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	About 37,000 U.S. troops are stationed in South Korea under a  
defense treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Separate from the joint exercise, South Korea announced plans to  
conduct its own annual field training exercise later this month 
involving a large number of soldiers, police and civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea denounced the South Korean drill as ``intentional  
and premeditated war moves to aggravate the situation on the Korean 
peninsula.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea claims that it has a sovereign right to develop and  
test-fire a missile. But it is believed to be weighing the merit of 
another missile launch, which is certain to invite economic and 
other sanctions from the United States, Japan and South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea sent shock waves through the region last August by  
launching a multi-stage missile over Japan and into the Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
	The two Koreas are still technically at war, since they did not  
sign a peace treaty at the end of the 1950-53 Korean War. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 07:55:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ben Jones Operates Novelty Store </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPERRYVILLE, Va. (AP) -- ``Dukes of Hazzard'' devotees can enjoy  
Uncle Jessie's Apple Cider or Daisy's Homemade Country Honey along 
with their reruns. 
</P>
<P>
	And to be sure, Cooter's Place, a theme shop that pays homage to  
the 1980s CBS series, is doing a booming business. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's phenomenal,'' said Ben Jones, who played the show's  
aw-shucks mechanic and operates the novelty store. ``The show seems 
to have found a new generation which is just as enthusiastic about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who also served as a U.S. congressman from Georgia, moved  
to rural Virginia several years ago. In June, he opened Cooter's 
Place in an old garage near Shenandoah National Park, including a 
replica of the ``General Lee,'' the show's signature orange Dodge 
Charger driven by characters Bo and Luke Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the other memorabilia at Cooter's Place: action figures of  
dimwitted deputy Cletus and a can of Hoggoco Motor Oil, along with 
``Dukes'' lunch boxes, napkins and Halloween costumes. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen years after the show was exiled to reruns, Jones still  
has difficulty comprehending its popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like being in a Beatles movie,'' he said. ``Our lives  
changed.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
