<DOCNO> APW19990816.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 03:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Reached on Marching Band </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Several hundred American student  
marching band members will be dumped from the opening ceremonies of 
the Sydney Olympics as part of a settlement reached with Games 
organizers Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games has agreed  
to pay the American company World Projects Corporation an extra 
$650,000 to train an expanded band of about 2,200 from 20 nations, 
on top of its initial fee of $585,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the initial contract, broken by SOCOG, the 2,000-member  
band was to have included 1,300 Americans from schools in 
California and Georgia, plus 200 Japanese and 500 Australians. 
SOCOG dropped the international band after a public backlash but 
has been forced into an embarrassing backflip. 
</P>
<P>
	The new band is to include 900 Australians and they are to  
provide the largest number from one country. At least 400 American 
students, who have been raising funds to pay for their trips Down 
Under, will be cut from the program. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG president Michael Knight, heavily criticized over the  
issue, said Monday that the new deal was satisfactory. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the negotiated compromise is not what either side would  
ideally prefer it is now closer to the concept of a world band,'' 
Knight said. 
</P>
<P>
	``WPC has taken full responsibility for reducing the number of  
Americans, maintaining the Japanese numbers and recruiting other 
young musicians from around the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The out-of-court deal was settled in the midst of legal action  
Monday after WPC attorney Paul Brereton accused SOCOG of a 
``calculated, deliberate and flagrant'' breach of contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Brereton added that SOCOG's actions were ``a deliberate  
flaunting of the rights of World Projects, partly to pander to what 
was perceived as public opinion and partly to avoid a perceived 
loss of revenue through ticket sales.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing before Justice John Bryson lasted just over an hour  
until an adjournment was called. When the parties returned, 
Brereton told the court that the matter was settled. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue became an embarrassing public relations disaster for  
Knight and SOCOG after the board dumped the student band members. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of a seven-minute performance at the opening ceremony,  
the students were offered a chance to play at non-Olympic venues in 
Sydney during the Games, including the Opera House. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight's handling of the matter has come under attack locally  
and internationally and he admitted last week that the board had 
``collectively made a mess'' of the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight told reporters July 6 there was no way he would reinstate  
overseas performers in the opening ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, we've made a decision nearly two weeks ago at the board to  
remove the foreign musicians from the massed band during the 
opening ceremony and that decision stands,'' Knight said at the 
time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 13:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Gas Co. Bids for Competitor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Linde AG, a German engineering and  
industrial gas company, is offering $3.7 billion for rival Swedish 
industrial gas group AGA AB. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined companies would have an 11 percent share of the  
global market and become the world's fourth-largest industrial gas 
group, said Gerhard Full, Linde's chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Linde already has 12.8 percent of the shares in AGA, and it  
reached agreement with major shareholders on Saturday to increase 
its stake to 62.5 percent. At a news conference Monday, Full said 
the AGA deal could be completed within two months. 
</P>
<P>
	Linde also is working on the acquisition of Hoechst AG's 66  
percent share in gas company Messer-Griesheim GmbH. Should both 
deals go through, Linde would control 16 percent of the global gas 
market and rank second after French Air Liquide. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement outlining Linde's bid for AGA, the German company  
said the alliance would mean lower distribution and production 
costs. Job cuts in Scandinavia were unlikely, Full said. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the Linde takeover offer pushed AGA's stock up 5.3  
percent on the Stockholm market. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 10:49:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Pounds Rebel-Held Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOTLIKH, Russia (AP) -- Plumes of smoke rose over three contested  
villages in the Caucasus Mountains today after Russian jets and 
helicopter gunships struck at dawn in a renewed attempt to drive 
out Islamic militants entrenched there. 
</P>
<P>
	After a quiet night, Russian Su-25 jets and Mi-8 helicopters  
began hammering the villages at 6 a.m. and continued airstrikes 
throughout the morning. Smoke was visible from Botlikh, the nearby 
town where forward Russian forces are based. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's offensive in the southern republic of Dagestan is  
concentrated on the isolated villages of Ansalta, Rahata and 
Shodroda, where the rebels are thought to be concentrated, just a 
few miles from the rugged border with the breakaway region of 
Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	Chechnya, which denies any connection to the rebels, declared a  
state of emergency Sunday, beefing up border posts, putting troops 
on combat alert and imposing a partial curfew. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moscow, President Boris Yeltsin promised ``rigid measures''  
against the militants, but said he would not impose any state of 
emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will bring order both to Dagestan and other republics in  
the North Caucasus,'' Yeltsin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Viktor Kazantsev, commander of the North Caucasus military  
district, insisted that Russian troops need only a few days to get 
rid of the rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Shamil Basayev, the Chechen warlord leading the  
militants, told Russian journalists he would unleash a new military 
operation against Russia in less than three days and bring eventual 
independence to Dagestan. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Air Force said it attacked 18 targets Sunday, and  
destroyed two buses carrying militants. Warplanes also were 
dropping mines to block possible rebel escape routes. 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestani volunteers fighting with the Russian troops caused an  
intentional mini-avalanche Sunday that trapped and killed dozens of 
rebels, according to Dagestan's Interior Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Interior Ministry acknowledged that it bombed suspected  
guerrilla positions just inside Chechnya on Saturday, and the 
government has said it will strike inside the territory if it 
considers such attacks necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Bombing raids on Chechnya, however, risk widening the conflict.  
And Russian forces appear reluctant to launch a major ground attack 
and risk heavy casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	After 10 days of fighting and hundreds of Russian sorties, the  
rebels have full control of several villages, but have not been 
able to extend their operations beyond the remote hamlets in the 
mountains along the border region. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen Russian soldiers have been killed and 40 wounded since  
the fighting began, according to Russia's Interior Ministry. The 
rebels have lost 400 fighters, and 300 more have been wounded, 
according to the ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures could not be independently confirmed.  
</P>
<P>
	The fighting began Aug. 7, when rebels crossed from Chechnya and  
seized several villages. The conflict is the worst inside Russia 
since Chechnya's 1994-96 war for independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Chechnya has effectively been independent since Russian troops  
pulled out nearly three years ago, though Moscow still claims it is 
part of Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestan, a neighboring republic on the Caspian Sea, has shown  
no sign of splitting from Moscow. Dagestan's political leaders are 
working closely with the Russian military, and Dagestani volunteers 
have made up part of the force fighting the rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the militants fighting in Dagestan apparently belong to  
the fundamentalist Wahhabi sect and are seeking an independent 
Islamic republic in the mostly Muslim Caucasus Mountains region. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Dagestan's interior minister, Adilgerei Magomedtagirov,  
acknowledged that some of the rebels are Dagestanis who ``brought 
armed foreign gunmen to our homeland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dagestani authorities also said today that two missing Polish  
scientists were probably kidnapped. A van belonging to them was 
found last Tuesday about 45 miles southwest of the Dagestani 
capital, Makhachkala. Bloodstains and signs of a scuffle were found 
at the scene, said a spokesman for the local Interior Ministry's 
anti-abduction squad. 
</P>
<P>
	Zofia Fiszer-Malanowska, the director of the International  
Environment Center of the Polish Academy of Science, and her deputy 
Ewa Marchwinska-Wyrwal were in Dagestan at the invitation of the 
Biology Institute in Makhachkala. They had been expected to return 
home Aug. 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were on a trip to study rare animal species. A pair of  
Dagestani scientists accompanying them was also missing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990816.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-16 10:49:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
