<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Use Restraint When Buying Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Going away to college means leaving the family PC, and that  
usually means another gut punch to a budget that's already reeling 
from tuition bills the size of small national defense budgets. 
</P>
<P>
	Exercise a little restraint and make the blow as soft as  
possible, without sacrificing anything your kid really needs. Basic 
systems today at or under $1,200 offer more than enough computing 
power for any academic task and still have plenty of muscle for 
that rare break from studies when your student might play a game. 
</P>
<P>
	First, Windows or Macintosh? For years, the answer has been a  
PC, but the rise of the funny-colored iMac has changed that to a 
coin toss if the major use of the system is going to be academic 
work and connection to a school's network. 
</P>
<P>
	The iMac bundles the essential components -- except a floppy disk  
drive -- into a $1,199.97 bundle that includes an Ethernet 
connection, 56-kilobit modem, 24-speed CD-ROM drive, six gigabytes 
of disk space, 32 megabytes of RAM, speakers and a 15-inch color 
monitor all bossed by a 333-megahertz PowerPC G3. Bundled software 
includes the AppleWorks suite and the usual Internet browsers. The 
operating system is Mac OS 8.5.1. 
</P>
<P>
	In the PC world, $999 buys the Gateway Essential 400. You get an  
Intel Celeron processor at 400 megahertz, 32 megabytes of RAM, 
40-speed CD-ROM drive, sound card, speakers, 56-kilobit modem 6.8 
gigabyte hard drive. Figure on another $25 for an Ethernet network 
card. The software suite is Microsoft Works and the operating 
system is Windows 98. 
</P>
<P>
	At Dell, a comparable system, the Dimension L400c, is $899. The  
hard drive on the L400c is 4.3 gigabytes, and the system RAM is 64 
megabytes. Otherwise, it pretty much tracks the Gateway offering. 
</P>
<P>
	Over at Compaq, the Prosignia Desktop 320 for $799 also has a  
4.3 gigabyte hard drive, the 400-megahertz Intel Celeron processor, 
32-speed CD-ROM drive and 32 megabytes of RAM, but it offers 16 
megabytes of video memory while the others have eight. It has 
comparable software, but if you want a modem, that's $39 more. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the PC packages include 15-inch color monitors.  
</P>
<P>
	The three PC manufacturers also will customize the system for  
you, but the price goes up more often than it goes down. And in all 
cases, shipping is extra if you're buying online or by telephone. 
And you may get pitches on ``expandability,'' but most of us never 
open a PC's case, and those of us who do, except for hobbyists, 
would rather not, so don't pay extra for capabilities you're 
unlikely to use. 
</P>
<P>
	Which one? I've used and liked systems from all three  
manufacturers over the years, but I've had the longest experience 
with Gateway and it's been a good one. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter what system you select, your student will need a  
printer. Make it a color inkjet -- they're small and quiet, a big 
consideration in cramped dormitories. Shop Lexmark, Epson, Canon 
and Hewlett-Packard in the $150 range for a color printer. You can 
pay more, but it isn't worth it to generate mostly monochrome 
college papers. And, sometimes with sales and rebates, you can pay 
less for output in the 600-dot-per-inch range. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Questions and comments are welcome. E-mail via the Internet to  
lblasko(at)ap.org, or send regular mail to Larry Blasko, AP, 50 
Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10020. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
