<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Approves New Sleeping Pill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, N.J. (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration has  
approved Sonata, a new prescription sleeping pill that can be taken 
in the middle of the night without worries of feeling groggy in the 
morning, drugmaker American Home Products said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonata should hit the pharmacy shelves in about a month.  
</P>
<P>
	Users must be able to stay in bed for four or more hours in  
order to avoid that ``hungover'' feeling often associated with 
sleeping aids, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of Sonata has not been set yet, although a company  
official said it will be ``competitively priced.'' Ambien, the 
nation's most widely prescribed sleeping pill, has an average 
wholesale price of $1.65 to $2.14 per pill, depending on the 
dosage. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say Sonata may reduce fears some people have about  
becoming dependent because they won't be tempted to take it every 
night -- before they are sure they cannot fall asleep. 
</P>
<P>
	Insomnia affects nearly 84 million Americans, according to the  
National Sleep Foundation. It may be caused by lifestyle changes 
such as a new home or job, jetlag, pain from arthritis or 
headaches, stress or anxiety, or use of certain medications. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonata was approved in Europe this summer. It is being sold in  
Germany, Sweden and Denmark. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
