<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Machinists Start Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATAC, Wash. (AP) -- Boeing and its largest union formally  
started round-the-clock negotiations Monday on a new three-year 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	At a joint news conference, lead Boeing negotiator Jerry Calhoun  
and Dick Schneider, head negotiator for the International 
Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers, said they were 
confident an agreement could be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are here to negotiate the best contract we can, and not to  
negotiate a strike,'' Schneider told a news conference at a hotel 
near Seattle-Tacoma International Airport where the talks are 
taking place. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe at the end of the day everyone's interests can be  
satisfied,'' Calhoun said. 
</P>
<P>
	Job security, control of pension funds and work schedules are  
the key issues going into the negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks come at a crucial time for Boeing, which is facing  
tough competition from Airbus Industrie to build planes for the 
world's airlines. If a strike occurs, it could cut short Boeing's 
financial recovery following two troubled years. 
</P>
<P>
	The union represents 44,000 of Boeing's 210,000 workers  
worldwide, mostly in the Seattle area. 
</P>
<P>
	The current contract expires Sept. 2. The Machinists have gone  
on strike in two of the past three contract talks, most recently 
for 69 days in 1995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
